{"title_page": "Tyler Palko", "text_new": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Tyler Palko\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=\n|number=4\n|position=[[Quarterback]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1983|8|9}}\n|birth_place=[[Imperial, Pennsylvania]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 1\n|weight_lbs = 215\n|high_school = [[West Allegheny High School|Imperial (PA) West Allegheny]]\n|college=[[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh]]\n|undraftedyear=2007\n|pastteams=\n* [[New Orleans Saints]]  ({{NFL Year|2007}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2008}})\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|2009}})*\n* [[Sacramento Mountain Lions|California Redwoods]] ({{UFL Year|2009}})*\n* [[Montreal Alouettes]] ({{CFL Year|2009}})\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] ({{NFL Year|2009}})\n* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] ({{NFL Year|2010}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2011}})\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|highlights=\n* 2001 Pennsylvania Big School Player of the Year\n* USA Today All-America Team (Second-team) (2001)\n* University of Pittsburgh Team MVP (2004)\n* 2\u00d7 Second-team Big East (2004, 2005)\n|statlabel1=TDs-INTs\n|statvalue1=2\u20137\n|statlabel2=Passing yards\n|statvalue2=831\n|statlabel3=QB rating\n|statvalue3=60.7\n|nfl=PAL194666\n|cfl=2893\n}}\n\n'''Tyler Palko''' (born August 9, 1983) is a former [[American football]] [[quarterback]]. He does weekly broadcasts for Pittsburgh Panthers Television on [[Comcast Network|Comcast]] and lives in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greensburg.pitt.edu/sites/default/files/Academics/Tyler%20Palko%20Bio.pdf |title=Bio |website=www.greensburg.pitt.edu |access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\nPalko was the starting quarterback at the [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|University of Pittsburgh]] (Pitt) from 2004 to 2006. The [[Left-handedness|left-handed]] [[List of left-handed quarterbacks|thrower]] was not selected in the [[2007 NFL Draft]], but was signed by the [[New Orleans Saints]] as an [[undrafted free agent]]. After spending most of the 2007 season on the Saints practice squad and occasionally the active roster, Palko was waived and did not play in a game in 2008. He joined the [[Arizona Cardinals]] on a future contract in December 2008, but was waived again in September 2009. Palko then joined the [[Montreal Alouettes]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] before receiving a release to sign with the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] in November 2009. He signed a future contract with the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] in 2010, but spent most of his time on the team's practice squad before joining the active roster near the end of the season. After entering the 2011 season as the backup to [[Matt Cassel]], Palko was elevated to starting quarterback after Cassel broke his hand.\n\n==Early years==\nPalko graduated from [[West Allegheny School District|West Allegheny High School]] in [[North Fayette, Pennsylvania]], where he was named [[Associated Press]] 2001 Pennsylvania Big School Player of the Year. He also sucked some dudes  weiner at West Allegheny in the bathrooms too. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsline.com/nfl/players/draft/418202|title=CBS Sportsline Tyler Palko profile|publisher=}}</ref> He was also a member of the ''USA Today'' All-America Team (Second-team) and three-time ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' WPIAL Class AAA Player of the Year. Palko led his West Allegheny Indians to a PIAA state title in 2001 for AAA in Pennsylvania.  At West Allegheny he played under his father, Bob Palko, earning four letters in football; additionally, he earned three letters in basketball and one in track and field.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} In his high school senior year, he was named 2002 YMCA Tribune-Review Scholar-Athlete honoree.<ref name=\"pittsburghpanthers1\">{{cite web|url=http://pittsburghpanthers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=2080|title=Tyler Palko - Football|website=Pitt Panthers #H2P}}</ref> In 2002, Palko was selected to play in the [[U.S. Army All-American Bowl]],<ref>[http://www.usarmyallamericanbowl.com/playersalumni.php U.S. Army All-American Bowl Player Alumni List] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101216010904/http://usarmyallamericanbowl.com/playersalumni.php |date=2010-12-16 }}</ref> an all-star game for high school athletes.\n\n==College career==\nPalko played at the [[University of Pittsburgh]], where his career began in [[2002 in sports|2002]] as a lettered true freshman. He completed 2-3 passes for 13 yards on the season, and rushed for an eight-yard touchdown late in Pitt's [[Insight Bowl]] victory over [[Oregon State]].\n\nPalko was [[redshirted]] the following season in 2003. As a redshirt-sophomore in 2004, Palko threw for 3,067 yards and 24 touchdowns, with only seven interceptions, earning him second-team All-[[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] honors. He was also named Pitt's [[MVP]] and offensive captain as a first-year starter. Palko's 24 touchdowns led the Big East and were the third-highest single-season total in Pitt history, and his total passing yardage was the most ever for a sophomore and third-best overall in school history as well. Palko also had four 300-yard passing games and one 400-yard passing game during this season alone. In a game against the [[University of South Florida]], Palko threw for a career-high 411 yards, the fifth-highest in school history, and matched a personal best of five touchdowns with no interceptions. Palko threw another five touchdown passes and totaled 334 yards in the air with no interceptions against [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]], becoming the first quarterback to throw for five touchdowns in a single game as a visiting team player against the [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish|Fighting Irish]]. Late in the fourth quarter against Notre Dame, the Panthers went on two late scoring drives: one for a touchdown and the second for a game-winning field goal with one second left to play. Palko also led three consecutive scoring drives against [[Temple University|Temple]] to overcome a 10-point fourth quarter deficit. They also surprised the [[West Virginia Mountaineers]] in the [[Backyard Brawl]] after being down 13-9 in the fourth quarter.  Palko led a drive that consisted of four third-down conversions, ending with his two-yard touchdown run. Pittsburgh earned a bid to play in the [[Fiesta Bowl]] against the [[Utah Utes football|Utah Utes]], where Palko was sacked nine times in a 35-7 loss.\n\nAfter replacing Walt Harris as head coach in the spring of 2005, [[Dave Wannstedt]] chose Palko over [[Joe Flacco]] as the starting quarterback during Pitt's spring training. Flacco was left to run Pitt's second team and eventually transferred to Division I-AA [[University of Delaware]]. Flacco became the starting quarterback for the Baltimore Ravens in 2008, a year after Palko had been signed and subsequently waived by the Saints.<ref>{{cite web|last=Babb |first=Kent |url=http://www.kansascity.com/2011/11/14/3266837/palko-has-been-waiting-for-this.html |title=Palko has been waiting for this moment |publisher=KansasCity.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>\n\nAs a junior in [[2005 in sports|2005]], Palko earned second-team Big East honors for a second consecutive season and was also named Pitt's captain for the second year in a row. Palko's passing statistics were not as outstanding as the previous year's, with 2,392 yards and 17 touchdowns with nine interceptions. However, his six rushing touchdowns were a career-high and a team high for the season, and Palko was Pitt's third leading scorer with 36 points. Palko's 371 yards and four passing touchdowns against [[Rutgers University]] were season highs in 2005, while his 35 completions out of 58 attempts were both career highs. Against [[West Virginia University|West Virginia]], he threw for 308 yards with two touchdowns and two interceptions in a loss. Palko also threw for 198 yards and a touchdown against a strong opponent in the [[Louisville Cardinals football|University of Louisville]]. In the season-opener against [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]], Palko threw for 220 yards with one touchdown and one interception while rushing for a four-yard score as well.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\nIn his final season as a Panther in 2006, Palko threw for 2,871 yards<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pittsburghpanthers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2006-2007/teamcume.html#TEAM.IND|title=2006\u20132007 Panther's stats|publisher=}}</ref>  (less than his 2004<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pittsburghpanthers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2004-2005/teamcume.html#TEAM.IND|title=2004\u20132005 Panther's stats|publisher=}}</ref> and 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pittsburghpanthers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2005-2006/teamcume.html#TEAM.IND|title=2005\u20132006 Panther's stats|publisher=}}</ref> totals), but set a new career high with 25 touchdowns; he only rushed for 77 yards and two scores on the season. Palko and the Panthers opened the season against the [[University of Virginia]] with 283 yards passing and three touchdowns. Palko followed it up with a 267-yard game against [[University of Cincinnati|Cincinnati]], a 277-yard performance against [[Michigan State]], and exceeded the 300-yard mark against [[The Citadel, The Military College of South Carolina|The Citadel]] with 313 yards for four scores. Later in the season against [[West Virginia]], Palko threw for a season high 341 yards along with two touchdowns in a 45-27 loss. In the season finale against [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]], Palko threw for 307 yards and a touchdown, but was picked off three times as well. Palko's aerial yardage and passing efficiency rating of 163.2<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/10719/type/college/tyler-palko |title=Tyler Palko Stats \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=August 9, 1983 |accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref>  was first in the conference, as were his completions per game. His ten 300-yard passing games during the season tied a Big East record set by Rutgers' Ryan Hart. He also ranked 4th in the NCAA in passing efficiency in 2006 with 163.2 (the leader was [[Colt Brennan]] with 186).<ref name=\"NCAA College football statistics\" /> Palko, along with linebacker [[H. B. Blades]], were invited to attend the [[Senior Bowl]] at season's end. {{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\nPalko ended his college career tied for second in school history with [[Alex Van Pelt]] in career touchdown passes (66) and was second in Pitt history in career passing yardage, trailing [[Dan Marino]] by 254 yards. Palko's career totals of 8,343 passing yards with 66 touchdown passes rank him as one of the top three passers in Panther football history.\n\nPalko graduated from the University of Pittsburgh in 2007 with a bachelor's degree in Communications and Rhetoric.<ref name=\"pittsburghpanthers1\"/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/sports/pitt-football/palko-put-the-pass-in-passion-for-pitt-460726/ | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | first=Paul | last=Zeise | title=Palko put the pass in passion for Pitt | date=November 23, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=3 style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff; border-color:#fff #fff #aaa #fff\" | &#160;\n! rowspan=99 style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff; border-color:#fff #aaa\" | &#160;\n! colspan=8 | Passing\n! rowspan=99 style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff; border-color:#fff #aaa\" | &#160;\n! colspan=3 | Rushing\n|-\n! Season\n! Team\n! GP\n! [[Passer rating#NCAA|Rating]]\n! Comp\n! Att\n! Pct\n! Yds\n! TD\n! INT\n! Sack\n! Att\n! Yds\n! TD\n|-\n| [[2002 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|2002]]\n| [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh Panthers]]\n| 8\n| 103\n| 2\n| 3\n| 67\n| 13\n| 0\n| 0\n| NA\n| 10\n| 9\n| 1\n|-\n| [[2004 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|2004]]\n| [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh Panthers]]\n| 12\n| 135\n| 230\n| 409\n| 56\n| 3067\n| 24\n| 7\n| NA\n| 129\n| 139\n| 3\n|-\n| [[2005 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|2005]]\n| [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh Panthers]]\n| 11\n| 127\n| 193\n| 341\n| 57\n| 2392\n| 17\n| 9\n| NA\n| 70\n| -139\n| 6\n\n<ref name=\"NCAA College football statistics\">{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/stats/StatsSrv/careersearch |title=NCAA College football statistics |publisher=Web1.ncaa.org |date=1999-03-20 |accessdate=2011-11-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2006 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|2006]]\n| [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh Panthers]]\n| 12\n| 163\n| 220\n| 322\n| 68\n| 2871\n| 25\n| 9\n| NA\n| 66\n| 77\n| 2\n|- style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n|\n| Totals\n| 43\n| 141\n| 645\n| 1075\n| 60\n| 8343\n| 66\n| 25\n| NA\n| 275\n| 86\n| 12\n|}\nNotes: Uses NCAA (rather than NFL) passer rating model. The NCAA indicates he played one game (bringing his total Pittsburgh career games played to 44) in 2003, but was [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] that year without any record of passes or rushes.  His official Panther biography says he did not play at all in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pittsburghpanthers.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/palko_tyler00.html |title=Player Bio: Tyler Palko \u2013 PittsburghPanthers.com \u2013 University of Pittsburgh Official Athletic Site |publisher=PittsburghPanthers.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===New Orleans Saints===\nPalko went [[undrafted sportsperson|undrafted]] in the [[2007 NFL Draft]] before signing with the [[New Orleans Saints]] on April 28, 2007. After the Saints released Palko during their final preseason cuts, he was back signed to the Saints' practice squad. He was then elevated to the 53-man roster for the team's first regular season game, where he was the team's third-string quarterback. After the game, he was released and re-signed to the team's practice squad. Palko was also promoted to the 53-man roster for the team's second contest, and was once again waived after the game. On October 9, 2007, Palko was signed back onto the Saints' practice squad.   On December 30, 2007, Palko was signed onto the active roster for the final game of the season, but was declared inactive for the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.neworleanssaints.com/team/transactions/?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook|title=Official Site of the New Orleans Saints|website=www.neworleanssaints.com}}</ref>\n\nPalko was waived for good by the Saints during final cuts on August 30, 2008.\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\nAfter spending the [[2008 NFL season]] out of football, Palko was signed to a future contract by the [[Arizona Cardinals]] on December 30, 2008. He was waived on September 4, 2009.\n\n===California Redwoods===\nOn September 20, 2009, Palko was signed by the California Redwoods of the [[United Football League (2009\u2013)|United Football League]]. He was cut during the preseason.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kansas City QB Tyler Palko: 'I think I'd rather be studying algebra than facing Bill Belichick' |url=https://www.masslive.com/patriots/index.ssf/2011/11/kansas_city_qb_tyler_palko_i_t.html |website=MassLive |publisher=Advance Local Media |accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Montreal Alouettes===\nIn October 2009, he signed with the [[Montreal Alouettes]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] and was placed on their practice roster. He was signed to the active roster on November 2, only to be released on November 25, allowing him to sign with the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]].\n\n===Pittsburgh Steelers===\nPalko was signed to the Pittsburgh Steelers' practice squad on November 25, 2009, after quarterbacks [[Ben Roethlisberger]] and [[Charlie Batch]] were injured. He was promoted to the active roster on November 28 when both quarterbacks were declared inactive for the team's November 29 game against the [[Baltimore Ravens]]. Palko was named the back-up quarterback behind [[Dennis Dixon]]. He was released by the Steelers on December 9, 2009.\n\n===Kansas City Chiefs===\n\n====2010====\nPalko was signed by the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] to a future contract on March 3, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2010/03/03/chiefs-bring-in-palko/ |title=Chiefs bring in Palko |last=Rosenthal |first=Gregg |date=2010-03-03 |website=ProFootballTalk |language=en |access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref>\n\nOn September 4, 2010, the Chiefs released Palko from the active roster, but signed him to the practice squad on the following day. He was elevated to the 53-man roster on December 8, 2010.\n\nPalko played in the closing minutes of the [[2010 Kansas City Chiefs season#Week 14: at San Diego Chargers|Kansas City-San Diego game on December 12, 2010]] (the Chiefs lost 31-0). He also played in the final minutes of the [[2010 Kansas City Chiefs season#Week 17: vs. Oakland Raiders|Oakland-Kansas City game on January 2, 2010]] (the Chiefs lost 31-10). He passed for a total of 4 for 6 and 35 yards with no interceptions and was sacked twice.\n\n====2011====\nThe Chiefs announced that Palko would take over starting quarterback duties against the New England Patriots in week 11 of the 2011 season, following a season ending index finger injury to starting quarterback [[Matt Cassel]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bostonherald.com/sports/football/patriots/view/2011_1117different_story_palko_not_cassel_next_up_on_pats_slate |title=Tyler Palko, not Matt Cassel, next up on Pats' slate |last=Rapoport |first=Ian  |date=November 17, 2011 |work=[[Boston Herald]] |access-date=2012-03-06}}</ref>  Palko's first starting opportunity with the Chiefs resulted in a 34-3 loss to the Patriots at [[Gillette Stadium]], where he completed 25 of 38 passes for a total of 236 yards and three interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2011112100/2011/REG11/chiefs@patriots?module=HP11_cp#menu=highlights&tab=recap|title=NFL Game Center, Chiefs vs. Patriots|date=November 21, 2011|work=NFL}}</ref> The following week, the Chiefs claimed [[Kyle Orton]] off waivers from the [[Denver Broncos]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Teicher |first=Adam |url=http://www.kansascity.com/2011/11/24/3284463/kyle-orton-was-the-chiefs-only.html |title=For desperate Chiefs, Kyle Orton move a 'no-brainer' |publisher=KansasCity.com |date=2011-11-24 |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>\n\nPalko started the next game against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], which received considerable interest in Pittsburgh given his collegiate roots.  Palko went 18 of 28 for 167 yards and had three interceptions, including one in the closing seconds as Kansas City was driving into Steeler territory. The game ended in a 13-9 loss for the Chiefs that was surprisingly close (the Steelers were 10-point favorites).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalfootballauthority.com/2011/11/pittsburgh-steelers-vs-kansas-city_27.html |title=Pittsburgh Steelers vs. Kansas City Chiefs: Tyler Palko's Miscues Too Much to Overcome as Steelers Edge Chiefs |publisher=National Football Authority |date=2011-11-27 |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson |first=Robbie |url=http://www.sportsbettingstats.com/NFL/pittsburgh-kansas-city-betting-odds-pick.asp |title=Pittsburgh Steelers vs. Kansas City Chiefs Betting Odds \u2013 ATS Pick |publisher=Sportsbettingstats.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>\n\nPalko threw his first NFL touchdown pass the following week against the [[Chicago Bears]]: a 38-yard [[Hail Mary pass]] to [[Dexter McCluster]] as time expired at the end of the first half. This pass turned out to be the game-winning play. Orton, who was the starting quarterback for Chicago in 2008, had replaced Palko in the second quarter, but hurt a finger on his throwing hand.  Palko returned and finished the Chiefs' upset of the Bears, 10-3, completing 17 of 30 passes for 157 yards and the McCluster touchdown pass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20111204/sports/712049796/ |title=Chiefs' Orton injured on only play |publisher=DailyHerald.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>\n\nIn the December 11 game against the [[New York Jets]], Palko only had 4 yards of total offense and one first down in the first half, completing 3 of 8 passes for 11 yards and one interception as the Jets jumped to a 28-3 lead.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} In the second half Palko threw for his second career [[National Football League|NFL]] touchdown, a 24-yard toss to [[Jerheme Urban]]. Palko was also sacked five times in the game, which the Chiefs lost 37-10.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/article/APe3710694eaf54735a681a6df1eea2992.html |title=BC-FBN--Chiefs-Jets Folo, FBN |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the Jets game, the Chiefs fired head coach [[Todd Haley]].  Interim head coach [[Romeo Crennel]] benched Palko and said that either Orton or [[Ricky Stanzi]] would start the December 18 game against the [[Green Bay Packers]].  Orton was selected and played a complete game against the previously unbeaten Packers, who the Chiefs upset 19-14.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://missourisportsmag.com/?p=43737 |title=Palko Era Over In Kansas City &#124; Missouri Sports Magazine |publisher=Missourisportsmag.com |date= |accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref> At the close of the 2011 season, Palko was released by the Chiefs.\n\n===Statistics===\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n ! rowspan=2|Season\n ! rowspan=2|Team\n ! colspan=3|Games\n ! colspan=8|Passing\n ! colspan=2|Sacks\n ! colspan=4|Rushing\n ! colspan=2|Fumbles\n|-\n ! GP !! GS !! W\u2013L<ref>\nGames won or lost with Palko as starter.</ref>\n ! Comp !! Att !! Pct !! Yds !! Y/Att !! TD !! INT !! Rating\n ! # !! Yds\n ! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! TD\n ! FUM !! Lost\n|-\n ! [[2010 NFL season|2010]] !! [[2010 Kansas City Chiefs season|KC]]\n | 2 || 0 || 0\n | 4 || 6 || 66.7 || 35 || 5.8 || 0 || 0 || 81.9\n | 2 || 10\n | 2 || 5 || 2.5 || 0\n | 0 || 0\n|-\n ! [[2011 NFL season|2011]] !! [[2011 Kansas City Chiefs season|KC]]\n | 6 || 4 || 1-3\n | 80 || 134 || 59.7 || 796 || 5.9 || 2 || 7 || 59.8\n | 11 || 83\n | 5 || 5 || 1 || 0\n | 1 || 1\n|-\n !  !! Total\n | 8 || 4 || 1-3\n | 84 || 140 || 60.0 || 831 || 5.9 || 2 || 7 || 60.7\n | 13 || 93\n | 7 || 20 || 2.9 || 0\n | 1 || 1\n|}\n<ref>{{cite web|author=Tyler Palko |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/tylerpalko/2507140/profile |title=Tyler Palko, QB at |publisher=Nfl.com |date= |accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://azcardinals.com/team/bio.php?PRKey=224 Arizona Cardinals bio]\n*[http://pittsburghpanthers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/palko_tyler00.html Pittsburgh Panthers bio]\n\n{{Pittsburgh Panthers quarterback navbox}}\n{{Kansas City Chiefs starting quarterback navbox}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palko, Tyler}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Canadian football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American players of Canadian football]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Panthers football players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Montreal Alouettes players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Tyler Palko\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=\n|number=4\n|position=[[Quarterback]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1983|8|9}}\n|birth_place=[[Imperial, Pennsylvania]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 1\n|weight_lbs = 215\n|high_school = [[West Allegheny High School|Imperial (PA) West Allegheny]]\n|college=[[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh]]\n|undraftedyear=2007\n|pastteams=\n* [[New Orleans Saints]]  ({{NFL Year|2007}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2008}})\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|2009}})*\n* [[Sacramento Mountain Lions|California Redwoods]] ({{UFL Year|2009}})*\n* [[Montreal Alouettes]] ({{CFL Year|2009}})\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] ({{NFL Year|2009}})\n* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] ({{NFL Year|2010}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2011}})\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|highlights=\n* 2001 Pennsylvania Big School Player of the Year\n* USA Today All-America Team (Second-team) (2001)\n* University of Pittsburgh Team MVP (2004)\n* 2\u00d7 Second-team Big East (2004, 2005)\n|statlabel1=TDs-INTs\n|statvalue1=2\u20137\n|statlabel2=Passing yards\n|statvalue2=831\n|statlabel3=QB rating\n|statvalue3=60.7\n|nfl=PAL194666\n|cfl=2893\n}}\n\n'''Tyler Palko''' (born August 9, 1983) is a former [[American football]] [[quarterback]]. He does weekly broadcasts for Pittsburgh Panthers Television on [[Comcast Network|Comcast]] and lives in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greensburg.pitt.edu/sites/default/files/Academics/Tyler%20Palko%20Bio.pdf |title=Bio |website=www.greensburg.pitt.edu |access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\nPalko was the starting quarterback at the [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|University of Pittsburgh]] (Pitt) from 2004 to 2006. The [[Left-handedness|left-handed]] [[List of left-handed quarterbacks|thrower]] was not selected in the [[2007 NFL Draft]], but was signed by the [[New Orleans Saints]] as an [[undrafted free agent]]. After spending most of the 2007 season on the Saints practice squad and occasionally the active roster, Palko was waived and did not play in a game in 2008. He joined the [[Arizona Cardinals]] on a future contract in December 2008, but was waived again in September 2009. Palko then joined the [[Montreal Alouettes]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] before receiving a release to sign with the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] in November 2009. He signed a future contract with the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] in 2010, but spent most of his time on the team's practice squad before joining the active roster near the end of the season. After entering the 2011 season as the backup to [[Matt Cassel]], Palko was elevated to starting quarterback after Cassel broke his hand.\n\n==Early years==\nPalko graduated from [[West Allegheny School District|West Allegheny High School]] in [[North Fayette, Pennsylvania]], where he was named [[Associated Press]] 2001 Pennsylvania Big School Player of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsline.com/nfl/players/draft/418202|title=CBS Sportsline Tyler Palko profile|publisher=}}</ref> He was also a member of the ''USA Today'' All-America Team (Second-team) and three-time ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' WPIAL Class AAA Player of the Year. Palko led his West Allegheny Indians to a PIAA state title in 2001 for AAA in Pennsylvania.  At West Allegheny he played under his father, Bob Palko, earning four letters in football; additionally, he earned three letters in basketball and one in track and field.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} In his high school senior year, he was named 2002 YMCA Tribune-Review Scholar-Athlete honoree.<ref name=\"pittsburghpanthers1\">{{cite web|url=http://pittsburghpanthers.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=2080|title=Tyler Palko - Football|website=Pitt Panthers #H2P}}</ref> In 2002, Palko was selected to play in the [[U.S. Army All-American Bowl]],<ref>[http://www.usarmyallamericanbowl.com/playersalumni.php U.S. Army All-American Bowl Player Alumni List] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101216010904/http://usarmyallamericanbowl.com/playersalumni.php |date=2010-12-16 }}</ref> an all-star game for high school athletes.\n\n==College career==\nPalko played at the [[University of Pittsburgh]], where his career began in [[2002 in sports|2002]] as a lettered true freshman. He completed 2-3 passes for 13 yards on the season, and rushed for an eight-yard touchdown late in Pitt's [[Insight Bowl]] victory over [[Oregon State]].\n\nPalko was [[redshirted]] the following season in 2003. As a redshirt-sophomore in 2004, Palko threw for 3,067 yards and 24 touchdowns, with only seven interceptions, earning him second-team All-[[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] honors. He was also named Pitt's [[MVP]] and offensive captain as a first-year starter. Palko's 24 touchdowns led the Big East and were the third-highest single-season total in Pitt history, and his total passing yardage was the most ever for a sophomore and third-best overall in school history as well. Palko also had four 300-yard passing games and one 400-yard passing game during this season alone. In a game against the [[University of South Florida]], Palko threw for a career-high 411 yards, the fifth-highest in school history, and matched a personal best of five touchdowns with no interceptions. Palko threw another five touchdown passes and totaled 334 yards in the air with no interceptions against [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]], becoming the first quarterback to throw for five touchdowns in a single game as a visiting team player against the [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish|Fighting Irish]]. Late in the fourth quarter against Notre Dame, the Panthers went on two late scoring drives: one for a touchdown and the second for a game-winning field goal with one second left to play. Palko also led three consecutive scoring drives against [[Temple University|Temple]] to overcome a 10-point fourth quarter deficit. They also surprised the [[West Virginia Mountaineers]] in the [[Backyard Brawl]] after being down 13-9 in the fourth quarter.  Palko led a drive that consisted of four third-down conversions, ending with his two-yard touchdown run. Pittsburgh earned a bid to play in the [[Fiesta Bowl]] against the [[Utah Utes football|Utah Utes]], where Palko was sacked nine times in a 35-7 loss.\n\nAfter replacing Walt Harris as head coach in the spring of 2005, [[Dave Wannstedt]] chose Palko over [[Joe Flacco]] as the starting quarterback during Pitt's spring training. Flacco was left to run Pitt's second team and eventually transferred to Division I-AA [[University of Delaware]]. Flacco became the starting quarterback for the Baltimore Ravens in 2008, a year after Palko had been signed and subsequently waived by the Saints.<ref>{{cite web|last=Babb |first=Kent |url=http://www.kansascity.com/2011/11/14/3266837/palko-has-been-waiting-for-this.html |title=Palko has been waiting for this moment |publisher=KansasCity.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>\n\nAs a junior in [[2005 in sports|2005]], Palko earned second-team Big East honors for a second consecutive season and was also named Pitt's captain for the second year in a row. Palko's passing statistics were not as outstanding as the previous year's, with 2,392 yards and 17 touchdowns with nine interceptions. However, his six rushing touchdowns were a career-high and a team high for the season, and Palko was Pitt's third leading scorer with 36 points. Palko's 371 yards and four passing touchdowns against [[Rutgers University]] were season highs in 2005, while his 35 completions out of 58 attempts were both career highs. Against [[West Virginia University|West Virginia]], he threw for 308 yards with two touchdowns and two interceptions in a loss. Palko also threw for 198 yards and a touchdown against a strong opponent in the [[Louisville Cardinals football|University of Louisville]]. In the season-opener against [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]], Palko threw for 220 yards with one touchdown and one interception while rushing for a four-yard score as well.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\nIn his final season as a Panther in 2006, Palko threw for 2,871 yards<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pittsburghpanthers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2006-2007/teamcume.html#TEAM.IND|title=2006\u20132007 Panther's stats|publisher=}}</ref>  (less than his 2004<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pittsburghpanthers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2004-2005/teamcume.html#TEAM.IND|title=2004\u20132005 Panther's stats|publisher=}}</ref> and 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pittsburghpanthers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2005-2006/teamcume.html#TEAM.IND|title=2005\u20132006 Panther's stats|publisher=}}</ref> totals), but set a new career high with 25 touchdowns; he only rushed for 77 yards and two scores on the season. Palko and the Panthers opened the season against the [[University of Virginia]] with 283 yards passing and three touchdowns. Palko followed it up with a 267-yard game against [[University of Cincinnati|Cincinnati]], a 277-yard performance against [[Michigan State]], and exceeded the 300-yard mark against [[The Citadel, The Military College of South Carolina|The Citadel]] with 313 yards for four scores. Later in the season against [[West Virginia]], Palko threw for a season high 341 yards along with two touchdowns in a 45-27 loss. In the season finale against [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]], Palko threw for 307 yards and a touchdown, but was picked off three times as well. Palko's aerial yardage and passing efficiency rating of 163.2<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/10719/type/college/tyler-palko |title=Tyler Palko Stats \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=August 9, 1983 |accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref>  was first in the conference, as were his completions per game. His ten 300-yard passing games during the season tied a Big East record set by Rutgers' Ryan Hart. He also ranked 4th in the NCAA in passing efficiency in 2006 with 163.2 (the leader was [[Colt Brennan]] with 186).<ref name=\"NCAA College football statistics\" /> Palko, along with linebacker [[H. B. Blades]], were invited to attend the [[Senior Bowl]] at season's end. {{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\nPalko ended his college career tied for second in school history with [[Alex Van Pelt]] in career touchdown passes (66) and was second in Pitt history in career passing yardage, trailing [[Dan Marino]] by 254 yards. Palko's career totals of 8,343 passing yards with 66 touchdown passes rank him as one of the top three passers in Panther football history.\n\nPalko graduated from the University of Pittsburgh in 2007 with a bachelor's degree in Communications and Rhetoric.<ref name=\"pittsburghpanthers1\"/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/sports/pitt-football/palko-put-the-pass-in-passion-for-pitt-460726/ | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | first=Paul | last=Zeise | title=Palko put the pass in passion for Pitt | date=November 23, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=3 style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff; border-color:#fff #fff #aaa #fff\" | &#160;\n! rowspan=99 style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff; border-color:#fff #aaa\" | &#160;\n! colspan=8 | Passing\n! rowspan=99 style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff; border-color:#fff #aaa\" | &#160;\n! colspan=3 | Rushing\n|-\n! Season\n! Team\n! GP\n! [[Passer rating#NCAA|Rating]]\n! Comp\n! Att\n! Pct\n! Yds\n! TD\n! INT\n! Sack\n! Att\n! Yds\n! TD\n|-\n| [[2002 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|2002]]\n| [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh Panthers]]\n| 8\n| 103\n| 2\n| 3\n| 67\n| 13\n| 0\n| 0\n| NA\n| 10\n| 9\n| 1\n|-\n| [[2004 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|2004]]\n| [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh Panthers]]\n| 12\n| 135\n| 230\n| 409\n| 56\n| 3067\n| 24\n| 7\n| NA\n| 129\n| 139\n| 3\n|-\n| [[2005 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|2005]]\n| [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh Panthers]]\n| 11\n| 127\n| 193\n| 341\n| 57\n| 2392\n| 17\n| 9\n| NA\n| 70\n| -139\n| 6\n\n<ref name=\"NCAA College football statistics\">{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/stats/StatsSrv/careersearch |title=NCAA College football statistics |publisher=Web1.ncaa.org |date=1999-03-20 |accessdate=2011-11-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2006 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|2006]]\n| [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh Panthers]]\n| 12\n| 163\n| 220\n| 322\n| 68\n| 2871\n| 25\n| 9\n| NA\n| 66\n| 77\n| 2\n|- style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"\n|\n| Totals\n| 43\n| 141\n| 645\n| 1075\n| 60\n| 8343\n| 66\n| 25\n| NA\n| 275\n| 86\n| 12\n|}\nNotes: Uses NCAA (rather than NFL) passer rating model. The NCAA indicates he played one game (bringing his total Pittsburgh career games played to 44) in 2003, but was [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] that year without any record of passes or rushes.  His official Panther biography says he did not play at all in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pittsburghpanthers.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/palko_tyler00.html |title=Player Bio: Tyler Palko \u2013 PittsburghPanthers.com \u2013 University of Pittsburgh Official Athletic Site |publisher=PittsburghPanthers.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===New Orleans Saints===\nPalko went [[undrafted sportsperson|undrafted]] in the [[2007 NFL Draft]] before signing with the [[New Orleans Saints]] on April 28, 2007. After the Saints released Palko during their final preseason cuts, he was back signed to the Saints' practice squad. He was then elevated to the 53-man roster for the team's first regular season game, where he was the team's third-string quarterback. After the game, he was released and re-signed to the team's practice squad. Palko was also promoted to the 53-man roster for the team's second contest, and was once again waived after the game. On October 9, 2007, Palko was signed back onto the Saints' practice squad.   On December 30, 2007, Palko was signed onto the active roster for the final game of the season, but was declared inactive for the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.neworleanssaints.com/team/transactions/?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook|title=Official Site of the New Orleans Saints|website=www.neworleanssaints.com}}</ref>\n\nPalko was waived for good by the Saints during final cuts on August 30, 2008.\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\nAfter spending the [[2008 NFL season]] out of football, Palko was signed to a future contract by the [[Arizona Cardinals]] on December 30, 2008. He was waived on September 4, 2009.\n\n===California Redwoods===\nOn September 20, 2009, Palko was signed by the California Redwoods of the [[United Football League (2009\u2013)|United Football League]]. He was cut during the preseason.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kansas City QB Tyler Palko: 'I think I'd rather be studying algebra than facing Bill Belichick' |url=https://www.masslive.com/patriots/index.ssf/2011/11/kansas_city_qb_tyler_palko_i_t.html |website=MassLive |publisher=Advance Local Media |accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Montreal Alouettes===\nIn October 2009, he signed with the [[Montreal Alouettes]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] and was placed on their practice roster. He was signed to the active roster on November 2, only to be released on November 25, allowing him to sign with the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]].\n\n===Pittsburgh Steelers===\nPalko was signed to the Pittsburgh Steelers' practice squad on November 25, 2009, after quarterbacks [[Ben Roethlisberger]] and [[Charlie Batch]] were injured. He was promoted to the active roster on November 28 when both quarterbacks were declared inactive for the team's November 29 game against the [[Baltimore Ravens]]. Palko was named the back-up quarterback behind [[Dennis Dixon]]. He was released by the Steelers on December 9, 2009.\n\n===Kansas City Chiefs===\n\n====2010====\nPalko was signed by the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] to a future contract on March 3, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2010/03/03/chiefs-bring-in-palko/ |title=Chiefs bring in Palko |last=Rosenthal |first=Gregg |date=2010-03-03 |website=ProFootballTalk |language=en |access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref>\n\nOn September 4, 2010, the Chiefs released Palko from the active roster, but signed him to the practice squad on the following day. He was elevated to the 53-man roster on December 8, 2010.\n\nPalko played in the closing minutes of the [[2010 Kansas City Chiefs season#Week 14: at San Diego Chargers|Kansas City-San Diego game on December 12, 2010]] (the Chiefs lost 31-0). He also played in the final minutes of the [[2010 Kansas City Chiefs season#Week 17: vs. Oakland Raiders|Oakland-Kansas City game on January 2, 2010]] (the Chiefs lost 31-10). He passed for a total of 4 for 6 and 35 yards with no interceptions and was sacked twice.\n\n====2011====\nThe Chiefs announced that Palko would take over starting quarterback duties against the New England Patriots in week 11 of the 2011 season, following a season ending index finger injury to starting quarterback [[Matt Cassel]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bostonherald.com/sports/football/patriots/view/2011_1117different_story_palko_not_cassel_next_up_on_pats_slate |title=Tyler Palko, not Matt Cassel, next up on Pats' slate |last=Rapoport |first=Ian  |date=November 17, 2011 |work=[[Boston Herald]] |access-date=2012-03-06}}</ref>  Palko's first starting opportunity with the Chiefs resulted in a 34-3 loss to the Patriots at [[Gillette Stadium]], where he completed 25 of 38 passes for a total of 236 yards and three interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2011112100/2011/REG11/chiefs@patriots?module=HP11_cp#menu=highlights&tab=recap|title=NFL Game Center, Chiefs vs. Patriots|date=November 21, 2011|work=NFL}}</ref> The following week, the Chiefs claimed [[Kyle Orton]] off waivers from the [[Denver Broncos]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Teicher |first=Adam |url=http://www.kansascity.com/2011/11/24/3284463/kyle-orton-was-the-chiefs-only.html |title=For desperate Chiefs, Kyle Orton move a 'no-brainer' |publisher=KansasCity.com |date=2011-11-24 |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>\n\nPalko started the next game against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], which received considerable interest in Pittsburgh given his collegiate roots.  Palko went 18 of 28 for 167 yards and had three interceptions, including one in the closing seconds as Kansas City was driving into Steeler territory. The game ended in a 13-9 loss for the Chiefs that was surprisingly close (the Steelers were 10-point favorites).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalfootballauthority.com/2011/11/pittsburgh-steelers-vs-kansas-city_27.html |title=Pittsburgh Steelers vs. Kansas City Chiefs: Tyler Palko's Miscues Too Much to Overcome as Steelers Edge Chiefs |publisher=National Football Authority |date=2011-11-27 |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson |first=Robbie |url=http://www.sportsbettingstats.com/NFL/pittsburgh-kansas-city-betting-odds-pick.asp |title=Pittsburgh Steelers vs. Kansas City Chiefs Betting Odds \u2013 ATS Pick |publisher=Sportsbettingstats.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>\n\nPalko threw his first NFL touchdown pass the following week against the [[Chicago Bears]]: a 38-yard [[Hail Mary pass]] to [[Dexter McCluster]] as time expired at the end of the first half. This pass turned out to be the game-winning play. Orton, who was the starting quarterback for Chicago in 2008, had replaced Palko in the second quarter, but hurt a finger on his throwing hand.  Palko returned and finished the Chiefs' upset of the Bears, 10-3, completing 17 of 30 passes for 157 yards and the McCluster touchdown pass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20111204/sports/712049796/ |title=Chiefs' Orton injured on only play |publisher=DailyHerald.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>\n\nIn the December 11 game against the [[New York Jets]], Palko only had 4 yards of total offense and one first down in the first half, completing 3 of 8 passes for 11 yards and one interception as the Jets jumped to a 28-3 lead.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} In the second half Palko threw for his second career [[National Football League|NFL]] touchdown, a 24-yard toss to [[Jerheme Urban]]. Palko was also sacked five times in the game, which the Chiefs lost 37-10.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/article/APe3710694eaf54735a681a6df1eea2992.html |title=BC-FBN--Chiefs-Jets Folo, FBN |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the Jets game, the Chiefs fired head coach [[Todd Haley]].  Interim head coach [[Romeo Crennel]] benched Palko and said that either Orton or [[Ricky Stanzi]] would start the December 18 game against the [[Green Bay Packers]].  Orton was selected and played a complete game against the previously unbeaten Packers, who the Chiefs upset 19-14.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://missourisportsmag.com/?p=43737 |title=Palko Era Over In Kansas City &#124; Missouri Sports Magazine |publisher=Missourisportsmag.com |date= |accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref> At the close of the 2011 season, Palko was released by the Chiefs.\n\n===Statistics===\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n ! rowspan=2|Season\n ! rowspan=2|Team\n ! colspan=3|Games\n ! colspan=8|Passing\n ! colspan=2|Sacks\n ! colspan=4|Rushing\n ! colspan=2|Fumbles\n|-\n ! GP !! GS !! W\u2013L<ref>\nGames won or lost with Palko as starter.</ref>\n ! Comp !! Att !! Pct !! Yds !! Y/Att !! TD !! INT !! Rating\n ! # !! Yds\n ! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! TD\n ! FUM !! Lost\n|-\n ! [[2010 NFL season|2010]] !! [[2010 Kansas City Chiefs season|KC]]\n | 2 || 0 || 0\n | 4 || 6 || 66.7 || 35 || 5.8 || 0 || 0 || 81.9\n | 2 || 10\n | 2 || 5 || 2.5 || 0\n | 0 || 0\n|-\n ! [[2011 NFL season|2011]] !! [[2011 Kansas City Chiefs season|KC]]\n | 6 || 4 || 1-3\n | 80 || 134 || 59.7 || 796 || 5.9 || 2 || 7 || 59.8\n | 11 || 83\n | 5 || 5 || 1 || 0\n | 1 || 1\n|-\n !  !! Total\n | 8 || 4 || 1-3\n | 84 || 140 || 60.0 || 831 || 5.9 || 2 || 7 || 60.7\n | 13 || 93\n | 7 || 20 || 2.9 || 0\n | 1 || 1\n|}\n<ref>{{cite web|author=Tyler Palko |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/tylerpalko/2507140/profile |title=Tyler Palko, QB at |publisher=Nfl.com |date= |accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://azcardinals.com/team/bio.php?PRKey=224 Arizona Cardinals bio]\n*[http://pittsburghpanthers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/palko_tyler00.html Pittsburgh Panthers bio]\n\n{{Pittsburgh Panthers quarterback navbox}}\n{{Kansas City Chiefs starting quarterback navbox}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palko, Tyler}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Canadian football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American players of Canadian football]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Panthers football players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Montreal Alouettes players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs players]]\n", "name_user": "Jajsisie", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly years:added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tyler_Palko"}
{"title_page": "Surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy", "text_new": "[[File:sers.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Raman spectrum of liquid 2-mercaptoethanol (below) and SERS spectrum of 2-mercaptoethanol monolayer formed on roughened silver (above). Spectra are scaled and shifted for clarity. A difference in selection rules is visible: Some bands appear only in the bulk-phase Raman spectrum or only in the SERS spectrum.]]\n\n'''Surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy''' or '''surface-enhanced Raman scattering''' ('''SERS''') is a surface-sensitive technique that enhances [[Raman scattering]] by [[molecule]]s [[adsorption|adsorbed]] on rough metal [[Surface science|surfaces]] or by nanostructures such as plasmonic-magnetic silica nanotubes.<ref>Xu, X., Li, H., Hasan, D., Ruoff, R. S., Wang, A. X. and Fan, D. L. (2013), [https://zenodo.org/record/845640 Near-Field Enhanced Plasmonic-Magnetic Bifunctional Nanotubes for Single Cell Bioanalysis]. Adv. Funct. Mater.. {{DOI|10.1002/adfm.201203822}}</ref> The enhancement factor can be as much as 10<sup>10</sup> to 10<sup>11</sup>,<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Blackie|first1=Evan J.|last2=Le Ru|first2=Eric C.|last3=Etchegoin|first3=Pablo G.|title=Single-Molecule Surface-Enhanced Raman Spectroscopy of Nonresonant Molecules|journal=J. Am. Chem. Soc.|volume=131|issue=40|pages=14466\u201314472|date=2009|doi=10.1021/ja905319w|pmid=19807188}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Blackie|first1=Evan J.|last2=Le Ru|first2=Eric C.|last3=Meyer|first3=Matthias|last4=Etchegoin|first4=Pablo G.|title=Surface Enhanced Raman Scattering Enhancement Factors: A Comprehensive Study|journal=J. Phys. Chem. C|volume=111|pages=13794\u201313803|date=2007|doi=10.1021/jp0687908|issue=37|citeseerx=10.1.1.556.4418}}\n</ref> which means the technique may detect single molecules.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1126/science.275.5303.1102|pmid=9027306|date=1997|last1=Nie|first1=S|last2=Emory|first2=SR|title=Probing Single Molecules and Single Nanoparticles by Surface-Enhanced Raman Scattering|volume=275|issue=5303|pages=1102\u20136|journal=Science}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Le Ru|first1=Eric C.|last2=Meyer|first2=Matthias|last3=Etchegoin|first3=Pablo G.|title=Proof of Single-Molecule Sensitivity in Surface Enhanced Raman Scattering (SERS) by Means of a Two-Analyte Technique|journal=J. Phys. Chem. B|volume=110|pages=1944\u20131948|date=2006|doi=10.1021/jp054732v|issue=4|pmid=16471765}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSERS from [[pyridine]] adsorbed on electrochemically roughened [[silver]] was first observed by [[Martin Fleischmann]], Patrick J. Hendra and A. James McQuillan at the Department of Chemistry at the [[University of Southampton]], UK in 1973.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|last=Fleischmann|first=M.|authorlink=Martin Fleischman|author2=PJ Hendra|author3=AJ McQuillan|last-author-amp=yes|title=Raman Spectra of Pyridine Adsorbed at a Silver Electrode|journal=[[Chemical Physics Letters]]|volume=26|issue=2|pages=163\u2013166|date=15 May 1974|doi=10.1016/0009-2614(74)85388-1|bibcode = 1974CPL....26..163F }}</ref> This initial publication has been cited over 4000 times.  The 40th Anniversary of the first observation of the SERS effect has been marked by the Royal Society of Chemistry by the award of a National Chemical Landmark plaque to the University of Southampton. In 1977, two groups independently noted that the concentration of scattering species could not account for the enhanced signal and each proposed a mechanism for the observed enhancement. Their theories are still accepted as explaining the SERS effect. Jeanmaire and [[Richard Van Duyne]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Jeanmaire|first=David L.|author2=Richard P. van Duyne |title=Surface Raman Electrochemistry Part I. Heterocyclic, Aromatic and Aliphatic Amines Adsorbed on the Anodized Silver Electrode|journal=[[Journal of Electroanalytical Chemistry]]|volume=84|pages=1\u201320|date=1977|doi=10.1016/S0022-0728(77)80224-6}}</ref>\nproposed an electromagnetic effect, while Albrecht and Creighton<ref>{{cite journal|last=Albrecht|first=M. Grant|author2=J. Alan Creighton |title=Anomalously Intense Raman Spectra of Pyridine at a Silver Electrode|journal=[[Journal of the American Chemical Society]]|volume=99|pages=5215\u20135217|date=1977|doi=10.1021/ja00457a071|issue=15}}</ref>\nproposed a charge-transfer effect. Rufus Ritchie, of [[Oak Ridge National Laboratory]]'s Health Sciences Research Division, predicted the existence of the [[surface plasmon]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Technical Highlights. New Probe Detects Trace Pollutants in Groundwater|journal=[[Oak Ridge National Laboratory Review]]|volume=26|issue=2|url=http://www.ornl.gov/info/ornlreview/rev26-2/text/tecmain.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115025603/http://www.ornl.gov/info/ornlreview/rev26-2/text/tecmain.html|archivedate=2010-01-15}}</ref>\n\n==Mechanisms==\nThe exact mechanism of the enhancement effect of SERS is still a matter of debate in the literature. There are two primary theories and while their mechanisms differ substantially, distinguishing them experimentally has not been straightforward. The [[electromagnetism|electromagnetic]] theory proposes the excitation of [[surface plasmon resonance|localized surface plasmons]], while the chemical theory proposes the formation of [[charge-transfer complex]]es. The chemical theory is based on [[resonance Raman spectroscopy]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Strommen|first=Dennis P.|last2=Nakamoto|first2=Kazuo|date=August 1977|title=Resonance raman spectroscopy|journal=Journal of Chemical Education|volume=54|issue=8|pages=474|doi=10.1021/ed054p474|issn=0021-9584|bibcode=1977JChEd..54..474S}}</ref> in which the frequency coincidence (or resonance) of the incident photon energy and electron transition greatly enhances [[Raman scattering]] intensity. Research in 2015 on a more powerful extension of the SERS technique called SLIPSERS (Slippery Liquid-Infused Porous SERS)<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1073/pnas.1518980113|pmid = 26719413|pmc = 4720322| title=Ultrasensitive surface-enhanced Raman scattering detection in common fluids| journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences| volume=113| issue=2| pages=268\u2013273| year=2016| last1=Yang| first1=Shikuan| last2=Dai| first2=Xianming| last3=Stogin| first3=Birgitt Boschitsch| last4=Wong| first4=Tak-Sing|bibcode = 2016PNAS..113..268Y}}</ref> has further supported the EM theory.<ref>http://www.kurzweilai.net/single-molecule-detection-of-contaminants-explosives-or-diseases-now-possible</ref>\n\n===Electromagnetic theory===\nThe increase in intensity of the Raman signal for [[adsorbate]]s on particular surfaces occurs because of an enhancement in the [[electric field]] provided by the surface. When the incident light in the experiment strikes the surface, localized surface plasmons are excited. The field enhancement is greatest when the [[plasmon]] frequency, \u03c9<sub>p</sub>, is in resonance with the radiation (<math>\\omega = \\omega_p/\\sqrt 3</math> for spherical particles). In order for scattering to occur, the plasmon oscillations must be perpendicular to the surface; if they are in-plane with the surface, no scattering will occur. It is because of this requirement that roughened surfaces or arrangements of [[nanoparticle]]s are typically employed in SERS experiments as these surfaces provide an area on which these localized collective [[oscillation]]s can occur.<ref name=\"Smith2005\">Smith, E.; Dent, G., [https://books.google.com/books?id=IpVcyQr_1DAC&printsec=frontcover Modern Raman Spectroscopy: A Practical Approach]. John Wiley and Sons: 2005 {{ISBN|0-471-49794-0}}</ref> SERS enhancement can occur even when an excited molecule is relatively far apart from the surface which hosts metallic nanoparticles enabling surface plasmon phenomena.<ref name=\"Kukushkin\">{{cite journal|last1=Kukushkin|first1=V. I.|last2=Van\u2019kov|first2=A. B.|last3=Kukushkin|first3=I. V.|date=2013|title=Long-range manifestation of surface-enhanced Raman scattering|journal=JETP Letters|volume=98|issue=2|pages=64\u201369|arxiv=1212.2782|bibcode=2013JETPL..98...64K|doi=10.1134/S0021364013150113|issn=0021-3640}}</ref>\n\nThe light incident on the surface can excite a variety of phenomena in the surface, yet the complexity of this situation can be minimized by surfaces with features much smaller than the wavelength of the light, as only the [[dipole|dipolar]] contribution will be recognized by the system. The dipolar term contributes to the plasmon oscillations, which leads to the enhancement.  The SERS effect is so pronounced because the field enhancement occurs twice. First, the field enhancement magnifies the intensity of incident light, which will excite the Raman [[normal mode|modes]] of the molecule being studied, therefore increasing the signal of the Raman scattering. The Raman signal is then further magnified by the surface due to the same mechanism that excited the incident light, resulting in a greater increase in the total output. At each stage the electric field is enhanced as E<sup>2</sup>, for a total enhancement of E<sup>4</sup>.<ref name=\"Moskovits\">Moskovits, M., [https://books.google.com/books?id=5xlTw9WCUwEC&printsec=frontcover Surface-Enhanced Raman Spectroscopy: a Brief Perspective]. In Surface-Enhanced Raman Scattering \u2013 Physics and Applications, 2006; pp. 1\u201318 {{ISBN|3-540-33566-8}}</ref>\n\nThe enhancement is not equal for all frequencies. For those frequencies for which the Raman signal is only slightly shifted from the incident light, both the incident [[laser]] light and the Raman signal can be near resonance with the plasmon frequency, leading to the E<sup>4</sup> enhancement. When the frequency shift is large, the incident light and the Raman signal cannot both be on resonance with \u03c9<sub>p</sub>, thus the enhancement at both stages cannot be maximal.<ref name=\"Campion, A. 1998\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1039/A827241Z|title=Surface-enhanced Raman scattering|date=1998|last1=Campion|first1=Alan|last2=Kambhampati|first2=Patanjali|journal=Chemical Society Reviews|volume=27|issue=4|pages=241 |citeseerx=<!-- 10.1.1.531.9985-->}}</ref>\n\nThe choice of surface metal is also dictated by the plasmon resonance frequency. [[Visible spectrum|Visible]] and [[Near infrared|near-infrared]] radiation (NIR) are used to excite Raman modes. [[Silver]] and [[gold]] are typical metals for SERS experiments because their plasmon resonance frequencies fall within these wavelength ranges, providing maximal enhancement for visible and NIR light. Copper's absorption spectrum also falls within the range acceptable for SERS experiments.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1039/FT9918703881|title=Ultraviolet\u2013visible absorption spectra of the colloidal metallic elements|date=1991|last1=Creighton|first1=J. Alan|last2=Eadon|first2=Desmond G.|journal=Journal of the Chemical Society, Faraday Transactions|volume=87|issue=24|pages=3881}}</ref> Platinum and palladium nanostructures also display plasmon resonance within visible and NIR frequencies.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/nl060219x|title=Plasmonic Properties of Supported Pt and Pd Nanostructures|date=2006|last1=Langhammer|first1=Christoph|last2=Yuan|first2=Zhe|last3=Zori\u0107|first3=Igor|last4=Kasemo|first4=Bengt|journal=Nano Letters|volume=6|issue=4|pages=833\u2013838|pmid=16608293|bibcode = 2006NanoL...6..833L }}</ref>\n\n===Chemical theory===\n[[Resonance Raman spectroscopy]] explains the huge enhancement of Raman scattering intensity. Intermolecular and intramolecular charge transfers significantly enhance Raman spectrum peaks. In particular, the enhancement is huge for species adsorbing the metal surface due to the high-intensity charge transfers from the metal surface with wide band to the adsorbing species.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Tsuneda|first=Takao|last2=Iwasa|first2=Takeshi|last3=Taketsugu|first3=Tetsuya|date=2019-09-07|title=Roles of silver nanoclusters in surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy|journal=The Journal of Chemical Physics|volume=151|issue=9|pages=094102|doi=10.1063/1.5111944|pmid=31492069|issn=0021-9606|bibcode=2019JChPh.151i4102T|hdl=2115/76053|hdl-access=free}}</ref> This resonance Raman enhancement is dominant in SERS for species on small [[nanoclusters]] with considerable [[band gap]]s,<ref name=\":3\" /> because [[surface plasmon]] appears only in metal surface with near-zero band gaps. This chemical mechanism probably occurs in concert with the electromagnetic mechanism for metal surface.<ref name=\"Lombardi1986\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1063/1.450037|title=Charge-transfer theory of surface enhanced Raman spectroscopy: Herzberg\u2013Teller contributions|date=1986|last1=Lombardi|first1=John R.|last2=Birke|first2=Ronald L.|last3=Lu|first3=Tianhong|last4=Xu|first4=Jia|journal=The Journal of Chemical Physics|volume=84|issue=8|pages=4174|bibcode = 1986JChPh..84.4174L }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/jp800167v|title=A Unified Approach to Surface-Enhanced Raman Spectroscopy|date=2008|last1=Lombardi|first1=J.R.|last2=Birke|first2=R.L.|journal=Journal of Physical Chemistry C|volume=112|issue=14|pages=5605\u20135617 }}</ref>\n\n==Surfaces==\n{{Primary sources|section|date=October 2019}}\nWhile SERS can be performed in colloidal solutions, today the most common method for performing SERS measurements is by depositing a liquid sample onto a silicon or glass surface with a nanostructured noble metal surface. While the first experiments were performed on electrochemically roughened silver,<ref name=\":0\" /> now surfaces are often prepared using a distribution of metal nanoparticles on the surface<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1063/1.1462610|title=Shape effects in plasmon resonance of individual colloidal silver nanoparticles|date=2002|last1=Mock|first1=J. J.|last2=Barbic|first2=M.|last3=Smith|first3=D. R.|last4=Schultz|first4=D. A.|last5=Schultz|first5=S.|journal=The Journal of Chemical Physics|volume=116|issue=15|pages=6755 |bibcode = 2002JChPh.116.6755M }}</ref> as well as using lithography<ref>{{cite journal | title = Molecular Logic Gates Using Surface-Enhanced Raman-Scattered Light |first9 = Amar H. |last9 = Flood | first8 = Lasse | last8 = Jensen | first7 = Eric W. | last7 = Wong | first6 = Jan O. | last6 = Jeppesen | first5 = Vincent J. | last5 = Bottomley | first4 = Daniel W. | last4 = Silverstein | first3 = Stinne W. | last3 = Hansen | first2 = Carsten |last2 = Johnsen | first1 = Edward H. | last1 = Witlicki | date = 2011 | volume = 133 | pages = 7288\u20137291 | doi = 10.1021/ja200992x |pmid = 21510609 |journal=[[J. Am. Chem. Soc.]] |issue = 19 |display-authors = 1}}</ref> or porous silicon as a support.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lin|first1=Haohao|last2=Mock|first2=Jack|last3=Smith|first3=David|last4=Gao|first4=Ting|last5=Sailor|first5=Michael J.|title=Surface-Enhanced Raman Scattering from Silver-Plated Porous Silicon|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry B|date=August 2004|volume=108|issue=31|pages=11654\u201311659|doi=10.1021/jp049008b}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Talian|first1=Ivan|last2=Mogensen|first2=Klaus Bo|last3=Ori\u0148\u00e1k|first3=Andrej|last4=Kaniansky|first4=Du\u0161an|last5=H\u00fcbner|first5=J\u00f6rg|title=Surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy on novel black silicon-based nanostructured surfaces|journal=Journal of Raman Spectroscopy|date=August 2009|volume=40|issue=8|pages=982\u2013986|doi=10.1002/jrs.2213|bibcode=2009JRSp...40..982T}}</ref> Two dimensional silicon nanopillars decorated with silver have also been used to create SERS active substrates.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1021/acsnano.6b02564|title = Large Format Surface-Enhanced Raman Spectroscopy Substrate Optimized for Enhancement and Uniformity|journal = ACS Nano|volume = 10|issue = 8|pages = 7566\u20137571|year = 2016|last1 = Kanipe|first1 = Katherine N.|last2 = Chidester|first2 = Philip P. F.|last3 = Stucky|first3 = Galen D.|last4 = Moskovits|first4 = Martin|pmid = 27482725}}</ref> The most common metals used for plasmonic surfaces are silver and gold; however, aluminium has recently been explored as an alternative plasmonic material, because its plasmon band is in the UV region, contrary to silver and gold.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=D\u00f6rfer|first1=Thomas|last2=Schmitt|first2=Michael|last3=Popp|first3=J\u00fcrgen|title=Deep-UV surface-enhanced Raman scattering|journal=Journal of Raman Spectroscopy|date=November 2007|volume=38|issue=11|pages=1379\u20131382|doi=10.1002/jrs.1831|bibcode=2007JRSp...38.1379D}}</ref> Hence, there is great interest in using aluminium for UV SERS. It has, however, surprisingly also been shown to have a large enhancement in the infrared, which is not fully understood.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mogensen|first1=Klaus Bo|last2=G\u00fchlke|first2=Marina|last3=Kneipp|first3=Janina|last4=Kadkhodazadeh|first4=Shima|last5=Wagner|first5=Jakob B.|last6=Espina Palanco|first6=Marta|last7=Kneipp|first7=Harald|last8=Kneipp|first8=Katrin|title=Surface-enhanced Raman scattering on aluminum using near infrared and visible excitation|journal=Chemical Communications|date=2014|volume=50|issue=28|pages=3744\u20136|doi=10.1039/c4cc00010b|pmid=24577020}}</ref> In the current decade, it has been recognized that the cost of SERS substrates must be reduced in order to become a commonly used analytical chemistry measurement technique.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Hoppmann | first=Eric P. | last2=Yu | first2=Wei W. | last3=White | first3=Ian M. | title=Inkjet-Printed Fluidic Paper Devices for Chemical and Biological Analytics Using Surface Enhanced Raman spectroscopy | journal= IEEE Journal of Selected Topics in Quantum Electronics| volume=20 | issue=3 | date=2014 | pages=195\u2013204 | url=http://www.erichoppmann.com/pubs/hoppmann_jstqe_2014.pdf | doi=10.1109/jstqe.2013.2286076 | ref=harv| bibcode=2014IJSTQ..20..195. }}</ref> To meet this need, plasmonic paper has experienced widespread attention in the field, with highly sensitive SERS substrates being formed through approaches such as soaking,<ref>{{cite journal | last=Lee | first=Chang H. | last2=Tian | first2=Limei | last3=Singamaneni | first3=Srikanth | title=Paper-Based SERS | journal= ACS Applied Materials & Interfaces| volume=2 | issue=12 | date=2010 | pages=3429\u20133435 | doi=10.1021/am1009875 | pmid=21128660 | ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Ngo | first=Ying Hui | last2=Li | first2=Dan | last3=Simon | first3=George P. | last4=Garnier | first4=Gil | title=Gold Nanoparticle | journal=Langmuir | volume=28 | issue=23 | date=2012 | pages=8782\u20138790 | doi=10.1021/la3012734 | pmid=22594710 | ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Ngo | first=Ying Hui | last2=Li | first2=Dan | last3=Simon | first3=George P. | last4=Garnier | first4=Gil | title=Effect of cationic polyacrylamides on the aggregation and SERS | journal=Journal of Colloid and Interface Science | volume=392 | date=2013 | pages=237\u2013246 | doi=10.1016/j.jcis.2012.09.080 | pmid=23131808 | ref=harv| bibcode=2013JCIS..392..237N }}</ref> in-situ synthesis,<ref>{{cite journal | last=Laserna | first=J. J. | last2=Campiglia | first2=A. D. | last3=Winefordner | first3=J. D. | title=Mixture analysis and quantitative determination of nitrogen-containing organic molecules by surface-enhanced Raman spectrometry | journal=Anal. Chem. | volume=61 | issue=15 | date=1989 | pages=1697\u20131701 | doi=10.1021/ac00190a022 | pmid=2774198 | ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Chang | first=Yung | last2=Yandi | first2=Wetra | last3=Chen | first3=Wen-Yih | last4=Shih | first4=Yu-Ju | last5=Yang | first5=Chang-Chung | last6=Chang | first6=Yu | last7=Ling | first7=Qing-Dong | last8=Higuchi | first8=Akon | title=Tunable Bioadhesive Copolymer Hydrogels of Thermoresponsive Poly( N -isopropyl acrylamide) Containing Zwitterionic Polysulfobetaine | journal=Biomacromolecules | volume=11 | issue=4 | date=2010 | pages=1101\u20131110 | doi=10.1021/bm100093g | pmid=20201492 | ref=harv }}</ref> screen printing<ref>{{cite journal | last=Qu | first=Lu-Lu | last2=Li | first2=Da-Wei | last3=Xue | first3=Jin-Qun | last4=Zhai | first4=Wen-Lei | last5=Fossey | first5=John S. | last6=Long | first6=Yi-Tao | title=Batch fabrication of disposable screen printed SERS arrays | journal=Lab Chip | volume=12 | issue=5 | date=2012-02-07 | issn=1473-0189 | pages=876\u2013881 | doi=10.1039/C2LC20926H | pmid=22173817 | ref=harv| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c8d5b0a426325344a344d7022ebb3a2bfea08fb3 }}</ref> and inkjet printing.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Yu | first=Wei W. | last2=White | first2=Ian M. | title=Inkjet-printed paper-based SERS | journal=Analyst | volume=138 | issue=4 | pages=1020\u20135 | date=2013 | doi=10.1039/c2an36116g | pmid=23001259 | ref=harv| bibcode=2013Ana...138.1020Y | url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/fd536e9a884b452da62166a3dd8f12dae5c88781 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Hoppmann | first=Eric P. | last2=Yu | first2=Wei W. | last3=White | first3=Ian M. | title=Highly sensitive and flexible inkjet printed SERS | journal=Methods | volume=63 | issue=3 | date=2013 | pages=219\u2013224 | doi=10.1016/j.ymeth.2013.07.010 | pmid=23872057 | ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Fierro-Mercado | first=Pedro M. | last2=Hern | first2=Samuel P. | title=Highly Sensitive Filter Paper Substrate for SERS | journal=International Journal of Spectroscopy | volume=2012 | date=2012 | pages=1\u20137 | doi=10.1155/2012/716527 | ref=harv| doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nThe shape and size of the metal nanoparticles strongly affect the strength of the enhancement because these factors influence the ratio of absorption and scattering events.<ref>{{cite journal|author=H. Lu|title=Seed-mediated Plasmon-driven Regrowth of Silver Nanodecahedrons (NDs) |journal=Plasmonics|volume=7|issue=1|pages=167\u2013173 |date=2011|doi=10.1007/s11468-011-9290-8|url=http://www.ntu.edu.sg/home/swzeng/2012-Seed-mediated%20Plasmon-driven%20Regrowth%20of%20Silver%20Nanodecahedrons%20(NDs).pdf|last2=Zhang|first2=Haixi|last3=Yu|first3=Xia|last4=Zeng|first4=Shuwen|last5=Yong|first5=Ken-Tye|last6=Ho|first6=Ho-Pui }}</ref><ref>Aroca, R., [https://books.google.com/books?id=Q7J75H9CmJMC&printsec=frontcover Surface-enhanced Vibrational Spectroscopy]. John Wiley & Sons (2006) {{ISBN|0-471-60731-2}}</ref> There is an ideal size for these particles, and an ideal surface thickness for each experiment.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1002/jrs.993|title=Study of silver films over silica beads as a surface-enhanced Raman scattering (SERS) substrate for detection of benzoic acid|date=2003|last1=Bao|first1=Li-Li|last2=Mahurin|first2=Shannon M.|last3=Liang|first3=Cheng-Du|last4=Dai|first4=Sheng|journal=Journal of Raman Spectroscopy|volume=34|issue=5|pages=394\u2013398|bibcode = 2003JRSp...34..394B |url=https://zenodo.org/record/1229261}}</ref> Particles that are too large allow the excitation of [[multipole]]s, which are nonradiative. As only the dipole transition leads to Raman scattering, the higher-order transitions will cause a decrease in the overall efficiency of the enhancement. Particles that are too small lose their electrical conductance and cannot enhance the field. When the particle size approaches a few atoms, the definition of a plasmon does not hold, as there must be a large collection of electrons to oscillate together.<ref name=\"Moskovits\" />\nAn ideal SERS substrate must possess high uniformity and high field enhancement. Such substrates can be fabricated on a wafer scale and label-free superresolution microscopy has also been demonstrated using the fluctuations of surface enhanced Raman scattering signal on such highly uniform, high-performance plasmonic metasurfaces.\n<ref>\n{{cite journal\n |last=Ayas |first=S.\n |date=2013\n |title=Label-Free Nanometer-Resolution Imaging of Biological Architectures through Surface Enhanced Raman Scattering\n |journal=[[Scientific Reports]]\n |volume=3 |pages=2624|doi=10.1038/srep02624|pmid=24022059\n |pmc=3769681\n |bibcode=2013NatSR...3E2624A}}</ref>\n\n==Applications==\nSERS substrates are used to detect the presence of low-abundance biomolecules, and can therefore detect proteins in bodily fluids.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last=Banaei|first=N|display-authors=etal |title=Multiplex detection of pancreatic cancer biomarkers using a SERS-based immunoassay|journal= Nanotechnology|volume=28|issue=45|pages=455101|date=September 2017|doi=10.1088/1361-6528/aa8e8c|pmid=28937361|bibcode=2017Nanot..28S5101B}}</ref> Early detection of pancreatic cancer biomarkers was accomplished using SERS-based immunoassay approach.<ref name=\":1\"/> A SERS-base multiplex protein biomarker detection platform in a microfluidic chip is used to detect several protein biomarkers to\npredict the type of disease and critical biomarkers and increase the chance of diagnosis between diseases with similar biomarkers (PC, OVC, and pancreatitis).<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|last=Banaei|first=N|display-authors=etal |title=Machine learning algorithms enhance the specificity of cancer biomarker detection using SERS-based immunoassays in microfluidic chips|journal=RSC Advances|volume=9|issue=4|pages=1859\u20131868|date=January 2019|doi=10.1039/c8ra08930b|doi-access=free}}</ref>\nThis technology has been utilized to detect urea and blood plasma label free in human serum and may become the next generation in cancer detection and screening.<ref name=\"Han 2014\">{{cite journal|last=Han|first=YA|author2=Ju J |author3=Yoon Y |author4=Kim SM |title=Fabrication of cost-effective surface enhanced Raman spectroscopy substrate using glancing angle deposition for the detection of urea in body fluid|journal=Journal of Nanoscience and Nanotechnology|date=May 2014|volume=14|issue=5|pages=3797\u20139|doi=10.1166/jnn.2014.8184 |pmid=24734638}}</ref><ref name=\"Li 2014\">{{cite journal|last=Li|first=D|author2=Feng S |author3=Huang H |author4=Chen W |author5=Shi H |author6=Liu N |author7=Chen L |author8=Chen W |author9=Yu Y |author10=Chen R |title=Label-free detection of blood plasma using silver nanoparticle based surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy for esophageal cancer screening|journal=Journal of Nanoscience and Nanotechnology|date=March 2014|volume=10|issue=3|pages=478\u201384|doi=10.1166/jbn.2014.1750 |pmid=24730243}}</ref>\n\nThe ability to analyze the composition of a mixture on the nano scale makes the use of SERS substrates beneficial for environmental analysis, pharmaceuticals, material sciences, art and archeological research, forensic science, drug and explosives detection, food quality analysis,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Andreou | first1 = C. | last2 = Mirsafavi | first2 = R. | last3 = Moskovits | first3 = M. | last4 = Meinhart | first4 = C. D. | year = 2015 | title = Detection of low concentrations of ampicillin in milk | url = | journal = The Analyst | volume = 140 | issue = 15| pages = 5003\u20135005 | doi = 10.1039/c5an00864f }}</ref> and single algal cell detection.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Deng|first=Y|author2=Juang Y |title=Black silicon SERS substrate: Effect of surface morphology on SERS detection and application of single algal cell analysis|journal=Biosensors and Bioelectronics|date=March 2014|volume=53|pages=37\u201342|doi=10.1016/j.bios.2013.09.032|pmid=24121206}}</ref><ref>{{cite techreport |first=Eric |last=Hoppmann |display-authors=etal |title=Trace detection overcoming the cost and usability limitations of traditional SERS technology |institution=Diagnostic anSERS |date=2013 | url=https://www.diagnosticansers.com/documentation/P-SERS-Whitepaper-v1.0.pdf\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Applied Optics|doi=10.1364/AO.49.004362|pmid=20697437|author1=Wackerbarth H|author2=Salb C|author3=Gundrum L|author4=Niederkr\u00fcger M|author5=Christou K|author6=Beushausen V|author7=Vi\u00f6l W|title=Detection of explosives based on surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy|date=2010|volume=49|issue=23|pages=4362\u20134366|bibcode=2010ApOpt..49.4362W}}</ref>\nSERS combined with plasmonic sensing can be used for high-sensitivity and quantitative analysis of small molecules in human biofluids,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|vauthors=Goodacre R, Graham D, Faulds K,|date=2018|title=Recent developments in quantitative SERS moving: towards absolute quantification|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0165993617304636|journal=Trends in Analytical Chemistry|volume=102|pages=359-368|doi=10.1016/j.trac.2018.03.005|via=}}</ref> quantitative detection of biomolecular interaction,<ref name=\"Nanoscale2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Xu|first1=Zhida|last2=Jiang|first2=Jing|last3=Wang|first3=Xinhao|last4=Han|first4=Kevin|last5=Ameen|first5=Abid|last6=Khan|first6=Ibrahim|last7=Chang|first7=Te-Wei|last8=Liu|first8=Logan|title=Large-area, uniform and low-cost dual-mode plasmonic naked-eye colorimetry and SERS sensor with handheld Raman spectrometer|journal=Nanoscale|date=2016|volume=8|issue=11|pages=6162\u20136172|doi=10.1039/C5NR08357E|pmid=26931437|arxiv=1603.01906|bibcode=2016Nanos...8.6162X}}</ref> and to study redox processes at the single molecule level.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cort\u00e9s|first=Emiliano|last2=Etchegoin|first2=Pablo G.|last3=Le Ru|first3=Eric C.|last4=Fainstein|first4=Alejandro|last5=Vela|first5=Mar\u00eda E.|last6=Salvarezza|first6=Roberto C.|date=2010-12-29|title=Monitoring the Electrochemistry of Single Molecules by Surface-Enhanced Raman Spectroscopy|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|volume=132|issue=51|pages=18034\u201318037|doi=10.1021/ja108989b|pmid=21138263|issn=0002-7863}}</ref>\n\n==Immunoassays==\nSERS-based immunoassays can be used for detection of low-abundance biomarkers. For example, antibodies and gold particles can be used to quantify proteins in serum with high sensitivity and specificity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Joseph|first=Manu M.|last2=Narayanan|first2=Nisha|last3=Nair|first3=Jyothi B.|last4=Karunakaran|first4=Varsha|last5=Ramya|first5=Adukkadan N.|last6=Sujai|first6=Palasseri T.|last7=Saranya|first7=Giridharan|last8=Arya|first8=Jayadev S.|last9=Vijayan|first9=Vineeth M.|last10=Maiti|first10=Kaustabh Kumar|date=2018-10-01|title=Exploring the margins of SERS in practical domain: An emerging diagnostic modality for modern biomedical applications|journal=Biomaterials|volume=181|pages=140\u2013181|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2018.07.045|pmid=30081304|issn=0142-9612}}</ref>\n\n===Oligonucleotide targeting===\nSERS can be used to target specific [[DNA]] and [[RNA]] sequences using a combination of gold and silver nanoparticles and Raman-active dyes, such as [[Cyanine|Cy3]]. Specific [[single nucleotide polymorphisms]] (SNP) can be identified using this technique. The gold nanoparticles facilitate the formation of a silver coating on the dye-labeled regions of DNA or RNA, allowing SERS to be performed. This has several potential applications: For example, Cao et al. report that gene sequences for HIV, Ebola, Hepatitis, and Bacillus Anthracis can be uniquely identified using this technique. Each spectrum was specific, which is advantageous over fluorescence detection; some fluorescent markers overlap and interfere with other gene markers. The advantage of this technique to identify gene sequences is that several Raman dyes are commercially available, which could lead to the development of non-overlapping probes for gene detection.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1126/science.297.5586.1536|title=Nanoparticles with Raman Spectroscopic Fingerprints for DNA and RNA Detection|date=2002|last1=Cao|first1=Y. C.|journal=Science|volume=297|issue=5586|pages=1536\u20131540|pmid=12202825|last2=Jin|first2=R|last3=Mirkin|first3=CA|bibcode = 2002Sci...297.1536C |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c828a5c7963d021dd9c9b8e8408be741575c29df}}</ref>\n\n==Selection rules==\nThe term ''surface enhanced Raman spectroscopy'' implies that it provides the same information that traditional Raman spectroscopy does, simply with a greatly enhanced signal. While the spectra of most SERS experiments are similar to the non-surface enhanced spectra, there are often differences in the number of modes present. Additional modes not found in the traditional Raman spectrum can be present in the SERS spectrum, while other modes can disappear. The modes observed in any spectroscopic experiment are dictated by the [[molecular symmetry|symmetry]] of the molecules and are usually summarized by [[Selection rule]]s. When molecules are adsorbed to a surface, the symmetry of the system can change, slightly modifying the symmetry of the molecule, which can lead to differences in mode selection.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/j150667a013|title=Surface selection rules for surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy: calculations and application to the surface-enhanced Raman spectrum of phthalazine on silver|date=1984|last1=Moskovits|first1=M.|last2=Suh|first2=J. S.|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry|volume=88|issue=23|pages=5526\u20135530}}</ref>\n\nOne common way in which selection rules are modified arises from the fact that many molecules that have a [[center of symmetry]] lose that feature when adsorbed to a surface. The loss of a center of symmetry eliminates the requirements of the [[Rule of mutual exclusion|mutual exclusion rule]], which dictates that modes can only be either Raman or infrared active. Thus modes that would normally appear only in the [[infrared spectroscopy|infrared spectrum]] of the free molecule can appear in the SERS spectrum.<ref name=\"Smith2005\"/>\n\nA molecule's symmetry can be changed in different ways depending on the orientation in which the molecule is attached to the surface. In some experiments, it is possible to determine the orientation of adsorption to the surface from the SERS spectrum, as different modes will be present depending on how the symmetry is modified.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/S0022-0728(03)00215-8|url=http://web.uvic.ca/~agbrolo/JECau111bipy.pdf|title=The orientation of 2,2\u2032-bipyridine adsorbed at a SERS-active Au(111) electrode surface|date=2003|last1=Brolo|first1=A.G.|last2=Jiang|first2=Z.|last3=Irish|first3=D.E.|journal=Journal of Electroanalytical Chemistry|volume=547|issue=2|pages=163\u2013172 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tip-enhanced Raman spectroscopy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Raman spectroscopy}}\n\n[[Category:Surface science]]\n[[Category:Raman scattering]]\n[[Category:Raman spectroscopy]]\n[[Category:Plasmonics]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:sers.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Raman spectrum of liquid 2-mercaptoethanol (below) and SERS spectrum of 2-mercaptoethanol monolayer formed on roughened silver (above). Spectra are scaled and shifted for clarity. A difference in selection rules is visible: Some bands appear only in the bulk-phase Raman spectrum or only in the SERS spectrum.]]\n\n'''Surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy''' or '''surface-enhanced Raman scattering''' ('''SERS''') is a surface-sensitive technique that enhances [[Raman scattering]] by [[molecule]]s [[adsorption|adsorbed]] on rough metal [[Surface science|surfaces]] or by nanostructures such as plasmonic-magnetic silica nanotubes.<ref>Xu, X., Li, H., Hasan, D., Ruoff, R. S., Wang, A. X. and Fan, D. L. (2013), [https://zenodo.org/record/845640 Near-Field Enhanced Plasmonic-Magnetic Bifunctional Nanotubes for Single Cell Bioanalysis]. Adv. Funct. Mater.. {{DOI|10.1002/adfm.201203822}}</ref> The enhancement factor can be as much as 10<sup>10</sup> to 10<sup>11</sup>,<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Blackie|first1=Evan J.|last2=Le Ru|first2=Eric C.|last3=Etchegoin|first3=Pablo G.|title=Single-Molecule Surface-Enhanced Raman Spectroscopy of Nonresonant Molecules|journal=J. Am. Chem. Soc.|volume=131|issue=40|pages=14466\u201314472|date=2009|doi=10.1021/ja905319w|pmid=19807188}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Blackie|first1=Evan J.|last2=Le Ru|first2=Eric C.|last3=Meyer|first3=Matthias|last4=Etchegoin|first4=Pablo G.|title=Surface Enhanced Raman Scattering Enhancement Factors: A Comprehensive Study|journal=J. Phys. Chem. C|volume=111|pages=13794\u201313803|date=2007|doi=10.1021/jp0687908|issue=37|citeseerx=10.1.1.556.4418}}\n</ref> which means the technique may detect single molecules.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1126/science.275.5303.1102|pmid=9027306|date=1997|last1=Nie|first1=S|last2=Emory|first2=SR|title=Probing Single Molecules and Single Nanoparticles by Surface-Enhanced Raman Scattering|volume=275|issue=5303|pages=1102\u20136|journal=Science}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Le Ru|first1=Eric C.|last2=Meyer|first2=Matthias|last3=Etchegoin|first3=Pablo G.|title=Proof of Single-Molecule Sensitivity in Surface Enhanced Raman Scattering (SERS) by Means of a Two-Analyte Technique|journal=J. Phys. Chem. B|volume=110|pages=1944\u20131948|date=2006|doi=10.1021/jp054732v|issue=4|pmid=16471765}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSERS from [[pyridine]] adsorbed on electrochemically roughened [[silver]] was first observed by [[Martin Fleischmann]], Patrick J. Hendra and A. James McQuillan at the Department of Chemistry at the [[University of Southampton]], UK in 1973.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|last=Fleischmann|first=M.|authorlink=Martin Fleischman|author2=PJ Hendra|author3=AJ McQuillan|last-author-amp=yes|title=Raman Spectra of Pyridine Adsorbed at a Silver Electrode|journal=[[Chemical Physics Letters]]|volume=26|issue=2|pages=163\u2013166|date=15 May 1974|doi=10.1016/0009-2614(74)85388-1|bibcode = 1974CPL....26..163F }}</ref> This initial publication has been cited over 4000 times.  The 40th Anniversary of the first observation of the SERS effect has been marked by the Royal Society of Chemistry by the award of a National Chemical Landmark plaque to the University of Southampton. In 1977, two groups independently noted that the concentration of scattering species could not account for the enhanced signal and each proposed a mechanism for the observed enhancement. Their theories are still accepted as explaining the SERS effect. Jeanmaire and [[Richard Van Duyne]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Jeanmaire|first=David L.|author2=Richard P. van Duyne |title=Surface Raman Electrochemistry Part I. Heterocyclic, Aromatic and Aliphatic Amines Adsorbed on the Anodized Silver Electrode|journal=[[Journal of Electroanalytical Chemistry]]|volume=84|pages=1\u201320|date=1977|doi=10.1016/S0022-0728(77)80224-6}}</ref>\nproposed an electromagnetic effect, while Albrecht and Creighton<ref>{{cite journal|last=Albrecht|first=M. Grant|author2=J. Alan Creighton |title=Anomalously Intense Raman Spectra of Pyridine at a Silver Electrode|journal=[[Journal of the American Chemical Society]]|volume=99|pages=5215\u20135217|date=1977|doi=10.1021/ja00457a071|issue=15}}</ref>\nproposed a charge-transfer effect. Rufus Ritchie, of [[Oak Ridge National Laboratory]]'s Health Sciences Research Division, predicted the existence of the [[surface plasmon]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Technical Highlights. New Probe Detects Trace Pollutants in Groundwater|journal=[[Oak Ridge National Laboratory Review]]|volume=26|issue=2|url=http://www.ornl.gov/info/ornlreview/rev26-2/text/tecmain.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115025603/http://www.ornl.gov/info/ornlreview/rev26-2/text/tecmain.html|archivedate=2010-01-15}}</ref>\n\n==Mechanisms==\nThe exact mechanism of the enhancement effect of SERS is still a matter of debate in the literature. There are two primary theories and while their mechanisms differ substantially, distinguishing them experimentally has not been straightforward. The [[electromagnetism|electromagnetic]] theory proposes the excitation of [[surface plasmon resonance|localized surface plasmons]], while the chemical theory proposes the formation of [[charge-transfer complex]]es. The chemical theory is based on [[resonance Raman spectroscopy]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Strommen|first=Dennis P.|last2=Nakamoto|first2=Kazuo|date=August 1977|title=Resonance raman spectroscopy|journal=Journal of Chemical Education|volume=54|issue=8|pages=474|doi=10.1021/ed054p474|issn=0021-9584|bibcode=1977JChEd..54..474S}}</ref> in which the frequency coincidence (or resonance) of the incident photon energy and electron transition greatly enhances [[Raman scattering]] intensity. Research in 2015 on a more powerful extension of the SERS technique called SLIPSERS (Slippery Liquid-Infused Porous SERS)<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1073/pnas.1518980113|pmid = 26719413|pmc = 4720322| title=Ultrasensitive surface-enhanced Raman scattering detection in common fluids| journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences| volume=113| issue=2| pages=268\u2013273| year=2016| last1=Yang| first1=Shikuan| last2=Dai| first2=Xianming| last3=Stogin| first3=Birgitt Boschitsch| last4=Wong| first4=Tak-Sing|bibcode = 2016PNAS..113..268Y}}</ref> has further supported the EM theory.<ref>http://www.kurzweilai.net/single-molecule-detection-of-contaminants-explosives-or-diseases-now-possible</ref>\n\n===Electromagnetic theory===\nThe increase in intensity of the Raman signal for [[adsorbate]]s on particular surfaces occurs because of an enhancement in the [[electric field]] provided by the surface. When the incident light in the experiment strikes the surface, localized surface plasmons are excited. The field enhancement is greatest when the [[plasmon]] frequency, \u03c9<sub>p</sub>, is in resonance with the radiation (<math>\\omega = \\omega_p/\\sqrt 3</math> for spherical particles). In order for scattering to occur, the plasmon oscillations must be perpendicular to the surface; if they are in-plane with the surface, no scattering will occur. It is because of this requirement that roughened surfaces or arrangements of [[nanoparticle]]s are typically employed in SERS experiments as these surfaces provide an area on which these localized collective [[oscillation]]s can occur.<ref name=\"Smith2005\">Smith, E.; Dent, G., [https://books.google.com/books?id=IpVcyQr_1DAC&printsec=frontcover Modern Raman Spectroscopy: A Practical Approach]. John Wiley and Sons: 2005 {{ISBN|0-471-49794-0}}</ref> SERS enhancement can occur even when an excited molecule is relatively far apart from the surface which hosts metallic nanoparticles enabling surface plasmon phenomena.<ref name=\"Kukushkin\">{{cite journal|last1=Kukushkin|first1=V. I.|last2=Van\u2019kov|first2=A. B.|last3=Kukushkin|first3=I. V.|date=2013|title=Long-range manifestation of surface-enhanced Raman scattering|journal=JETP Letters|volume=98|issue=2|pages=64\u201369|arxiv=1212.2782|bibcode=2013JETPL..98...64K|doi=10.1134/S0021364013150113|issn=0021-3640}}</ref>\n\nThe light incident on the surface can excite a variety of phenomena in the surface, yet the complexity of this situation can be minimized by surfaces with features much smaller than the wavelength of the light, as only the [[dipole|dipolar]] contribution will be recognized by the system. The dipolar term contributes to the plasmon oscillations, which leads to the enhancement.  The SERS effect is so pronounced because the field enhancement occurs twice. First, the field enhancement magnifies the intensity of incident light, which will excite the Raman [[normal mode|modes]] of the molecule being studied, therefore increasing the signal of the Raman scattering. The Raman signal is then further magnified by the surface due to the same mechanism that excited the incident light, resulting in a greater increase in the total output. At each stage the electric field is enhanced as E<sup>2</sup>, for a total enhancement of E<sup>4</sup>.<ref name=\"Moskovits\">Moskovits, M., [https://books.google.com/books?id=5xlTw9WCUwEC&printsec=frontcover Surface-Enhanced Raman Spectroscopy: a Brief Perspective]. In Surface-Enhanced Raman Scattering \u2013 Physics and Applications, 2006; pp. 1\u201318 {{ISBN|3-540-33566-8}}</ref>\n\nThe enhancement is not equal for all frequencies. For those frequencies for which the Raman signal is only slightly shifted from the incident light, both the incident [[laser]] light and the Raman signal can be near resonance with the plasmon frequency, leading to the E<sup>4</sup> enhancement. When the frequency shift is large, the incident light and the Raman signal cannot both be on resonance with \u03c9<sub>p</sub>, thus the enhancement at both stages cannot be maximal.<ref name=\"Campion, A. 1998\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1039/A827241Z|title=Surface-enhanced Raman scattering|date=1998|last1=Campion|first1=Alan|last2=Kambhampati|first2=Patanjali|journal=Chemical Society Reviews|volume=27|issue=4|pages=241 |citeseerx=<!-- 10.1.1.531.9985-->}}</ref>\n\nThe choice of surface metal is also dictated by the plasmon resonance frequency. [[Visible spectrum|Visible]] and [[Near infrared|near-infrared]] radiation (NIR) are used to excite Raman modes. [[Silver]] and [[gold]] are typical metals for SERS experiments because their plasmon resonance frequencies fall within these wavelength ranges, providing maximal enhancement for visible and NIR light. Copper's absorption spectrum also falls within the range acceptable for SERS experiments.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1039/FT9918703881|title=Ultraviolet\u2013visible absorption spectra of the colloidal metallic elements|date=1991|last1=Creighton|first1=J. Alan|last2=Eadon|first2=Desmond G.|journal=Journal of the Chemical Society, Faraday Transactions|volume=87|issue=24|pages=3881}}</ref> Platinum and palladium nanostructures also display plasmon resonance within visible and NIR frequencies.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/nl060219x|title=Plasmonic Properties of Supported Pt and Pd Nanostructures|date=2006|last1=Langhammer|first1=Christoph|last2=Yuan|first2=Zhe|last3=Zori\u0107|first3=Igor|last4=Kasemo|first4=Bengt|journal=Nano Letters|volume=6|issue=4|pages=833\u2013838|pmid=16608293|bibcode = 2006NanoL...6..833L }}</ref>\n\n===Chemical theory===\n[[Resonance Raman spectroscopy]] explains the huge enhancement of Raman scattering intensity. Intermolecular and intramolecular charge transfers significantly enhance Raman spectrum peaks. In particular, the enhancement is huge for species adsorbing the metal surface due to the high-intensity charge transfers from the metal surface with wide band to the adsorbing species.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Tsuneda|first=Takao|last2=Iwasa|first2=Takeshi|last3=Taketsugu|first3=Tetsuya|date=2019-09-07|title=Roles of silver nanoclusters in surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy|journal=The Journal of Chemical Physics|volume=151|issue=9|pages=094102|doi=10.1063/1.5111944|pmid=31492069|issn=0021-9606|bibcode=2019JChPh.151i4102T|hdl=2115/76053|hdl-access=free}}</ref> This resonance Raman enhancement is dominant in SERS for species on small [[nanoclusters]] with considerable [[band gap]]s,<ref name=\":3\" /> because [[surface plasmon]] appears only in metal surface with near-zero band gaps. This chemical mechanism probably occurs in concert with the electromagnetic mechanism for metal surface.<ref name=\"Lombardi1986\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1063/1.450037|title=Charge-transfer theory of surface enhanced Raman spectroscopy: Herzberg\u2013Teller contributions|date=1986|last1=Lombardi|first1=John R.|last2=Birke|first2=Ronald L.|last3=Lu|first3=Tianhong|last4=Xu|first4=Jia|journal=The Journal of Chemical Physics|volume=84|issue=8|pages=4174|bibcode = 1986JChPh..84.4174L }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/jp800167v|title=A Unified Approach to Surface-Enhanced Raman Spectroscopy|date=2008|last1=Lombardi|first1=J.R.|last2=Birke|first2=R.L.|journal=Journal of Physical Chemistry C|volume=112|issue=14|pages=5605\u20135617 }}</ref>\n\n==Surfaces==\n{{Primary sources|section|date=October 2019}}\nWhile SERS can be performed in colloidal solutions, today the most common method for performing SERS measurements is by depositing a liquid sample onto a silicon or glass surface with a nanostructured noble metal surface. While the first experiments were performed on electrochemically roughened silver,<ref name=\":0\" /> now surfaces are often prepared using a distribution of metal nanoparticles on the surface<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1063/1.1462610|title=Shape effects in plasmon resonance of individual colloidal silver nanoparticles|date=2002|last1=Mock|first1=J. J.|last2=Barbic|first2=M.|last3=Smith|first3=D. R.|last4=Schultz|first4=D. A.|last5=Schultz|first5=S.|journal=The Journal of Chemical Physics|volume=116|issue=15|pages=6755 |bibcode = 2002JChPh.116.6755M }}</ref> as well as using lithography<ref>{{cite journal | title = Molecular Logic Gates Using Surface-Enhanced Raman-Scattered Light |first9 = Amar H. |last9 = Flood | first8 = Lasse | last8 = Jensen | first7 = Eric W. | last7 = Wong | first6 = Jan O. | last6 = Jeppesen | first5 = Vincent J. | last5 = Bottomley | first4 = Daniel W. | last4 = Silverstein | first3 = Stinne W. | last3 = Hansen | first2 = Carsten |last2 = Johnsen | first1 = Edward H. | last1 = Witlicki | date = 2011 | volume = 133 | pages = 7288\u20137291 | doi = 10.1021/ja200992x |pmid = 21510609 |journal=[[J. Am. Chem. Soc.]] |issue = 19 |display-authors = 1}}</ref> or porous silicon as a support.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lin|first1=Haohao|last2=Mock|first2=Jack|last3=Smith|first3=David|last4=Gao|first4=Ting|last5=Sailor|first5=Michael J.|title=Surface-Enhanced Raman Scattering from Silver-Plated Porous Silicon|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry B|date=August 2004|volume=108|issue=31|pages=11654\u201311659|doi=10.1021/jp049008b}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Talian|first1=Ivan|last2=Mogensen|first2=Klaus Bo|last3=Ori\u0148\u00e1k|first3=Andrej|last4=Kaniansky|first4=Du\u0161an|last5=H\u00fcbner|first5=J\u00f6rg|title=Surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy on novel black silicon-based nanostructured surfaces|journal=Journal of Raman Spectroscopy|date=August 2009|volume=40|issue=8|pages=982\u2013986|doi=10.1002/jrs.2213|bibcode=2009JRSp...40..982T}}</ref> Two dimensional silicon nanopillars decorated with silver have also been used to create SERS active substrates.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1021/acsnano.6b02564|title = Large Format Surface-Enhanced Raman Spectroscopy Substrate Optimized for Enhancement and Uniformity|journal = ACS Nano|volume = 10|issue = 8|pages = 7566\u20137571|year = 2016|last1 = Kanipe|first1 = Katherine N.|last2 = Chidester|first2 = Philip P. F.|last3 = Stucky|first3 = Galen D.|last4 = Moskovits|first4 = Martin|pmid = 27482725}}</ref> The most common metals used for plasmonic surfaces are silver and gold; however, aluminium has recently been explored as an alternative plasmonic material, because its plasmon band is in the UV region, contrary to silver and gold.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=D\u00f6rfer|first1=Thomas|last2=Schmitt|first2=Michael|last3=Popp|first3=J\u00fcrgen|title=Deep-UV surface-enhanced Raman scattering|journal=Journal of Raman Spectroscopy|date=November 2007|volume=38|issue=11|pages=1379\u20131382|doi=10.1002/jrs.1831|bibcode=2007JRSp...38.1379D}}</ref> Hence, there is great interest in using aluminium for UV SERS. It has, however, surprisingly also been shown to have a large enhancement in the infrared, which is not fully understood.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mogensen|first1=Klaus Bo|last2=G\u00fchlke|first2=Marina|last3=Kneipp|first3=Janina|last4=Kadkhodazadeh|first4=Shima|last5=Wagner|first5=Jakob B.|last6=Espina Palanco|first6=Marta|last7=Kneipp|first7=Harald|last8=Kneipp|first8=Katrin|title=Surface-enhanced Raman scattering on aluminum using near infrared and visible excitation|journal=Chemical Communications|date=2014|volume=50|issue=28|pages=3744\u20136|doi=10.1039/c4cc00010b|pmid=24577020}}</ref> In the current decade, it has been recognized that the cost of SERS substrates must be reduced in order to become a commonly used analytical chemistry measurement technique.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Hoppmann | first=Eric P. | last2=Yu | first2=Wei W. | last3=White | first3=Ian M. | title=Inkjet-Printed Fluidic Paper Devices for Chemical and Biological Analytics Using Surface Enhanced Raman spectroscopy | journal= IEEE Journal of Selected Topics in Quantum Electronics| volume=20 | issue=3 | date=2014 | pages=195\u2013204 | url=http://www.erichoppmann.com/pubs/hoppmann_jstqe_2014.pdf | doi=10.1109/jstqe.2013.2286076 | ref=harv| bibcode=2014IJSTQ..20..195. }}</ref> To meet this need, plasmonic paper has experienced widespread attention in the field, with highly sensitive SERS substrates being formed through approaches such as soaking,<ref>{{cite journal | last=Lee | first=Chang H. | last2=Tian | first2=Limei | last3=Singamaneni | first3=Srikanth | title=Paper-Based SERS | journal= ACS Applied Materials & Interfaces| volume=2 | issue=12 | date=2010 | pages=3429\u20133435 | doi=10.1021/am1009875 | pmid=21128660 | ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Ngo | first=Ying Hui | last2=Li | first2=Dan | last3=Simon | first3=George P. | last4=Garnier | first4=Gil | title=Gold Nanoparticle | journal=Langmuir | volume=28 | issue=23 | date=2012 | pages=8782\u20138790 | doi=10.1021/la3012734 | pmid=22594710 | ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Ngo | first=Ying Hui | last2=Li | first2=Dan | last3=Simon | first3=George P. | last4=Garnier | first4=Gil | title=Effect of cationic polyacrylamides on the aggregation and SERS | journal=Journal of Colloid and Interface Science | volume=392 | date=2013 | pages=237\u2013246 | doi=10.1016/j.jcis.2012.09.080 | pmid=23131808 | ref=harv| bibcode=2013JCIS..392..237N }}</ref> in-situ synthesis,<ref>{{cite journal | last=Laserna | first=J. J. | last2=Campiglia | first2=A. D. | last3=Winefordner | first3=J. D. | title=Mixture analysis and quantitative determination of nitrogen-containing organic molecules by surface-enhanced Raman spectrometry | journal=Anal. Chem. | volume=61 | issue=15 | date=1989 | pages=1697\u20131701 | doi=10.1021/ac00190a022 | pmid=2774198 | ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Chang | first=Yung | last2=Yandi | first2=Wetra | last3=Chen | first3=Wen-Yih | last4=Shih | first4=Yu-Ju | last5=Yang | first5=Chang-Chung | last6=Chang | first6=Yu | last7=Ling | first7=Qing-Dong | last8=Higuchi | first8=Akon | title=Tunable Bioadhesive Copolymer Hydrogels of Thermoresponsive Poly( N -isopropyl acrylamide) Containing Zwitterionic Polysulfobetaine | journal=Biomacromolecules | volume=11 | issue=4 | date=2010 | pages=1101\u20131110 | doi=10.1021/bm100093g | pmid=20201492 | ref=harv }}</ref> screen printing<ref>{{cite journal | last=Qu | first=Lu-Lu | last2=Li | first2=Da-Wei | last3=Xue | first3=Jin-Qun | last4=Zhai | first4=Wen-Lei | last5=Fossey | first5=John S. | last6=Long | first6=Yi-Tao | title=Batch fabrication of disposable screen printed SERS arrays | journal=Lab Chip | volume=12 | issue=5 | date=2012-02-07 | issn=1473-0189 | pages=876\u2013881 | doi=10.1039/C2LC20926H | pmid=22173817 | ref=harv| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c8d5b0a426325344a344d7022ebb3a2bfea08fb3 }}</ref> and inkjet printing.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Yu | first=Wei W. | last2=White | first2=Ian M. | title=Inkjet-printed paper-based SERS | journal=Analyst | volume=138 | issue=4 | pages=1020\u20135 | date=2013 | doi=10.1039/c2an36116g | pmid=23001259 | ref=harv| bibcode=2013Ana...138.1020Y | url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/fd536e9a884b452da62166a3dd8f12dae5c88781 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Hoppmann | first=Eric P. | last2=Yu | first2=Wei W. | last3=White | first3=Ian M. | title=Highly sensitive and flexible inkjet printed SERS | journal=Methods | volume=63 | issue=3 | date=2013 | pages=219\u2013224 | doi=10.1016/j.ymeth.2013.07.010 | pmid=23872057 | ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Fierro-Mercado | first=Pedro M. | last2=Hern | first2=Samuel P. | title=Highly Sensitive Filter Paper Substrate for SERS | journal=International Journal of Spectroscopy | volume=2012 | date=2012 | pages=1\u20137 | doi=10.1155/2012/716527 | ref=harv| doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nThe shape and size of the metal nanoparticles strongly affect the strength of the enhancement because these factors influence the ratio of absorption and scattering events.<ref>{{cite journal|author=H. Lu|title=Seed-mediated Plasmon-driven Regrowth of Silver Nanodecahedrons (NDs) |journal=Plasmonics|volume=7|issue=1|pages=167\u2013173 |date=2011|doi=10.1007/s11468-011-9290-8|url=http://www.ntu.edu.sg/home/swzeng/2012-Seed-mediated%20Plasmon-driven%20Regrowth%20of%20Silver%20Nanodecahedrons%20(NDs).pdf|last2=Zhang|first2=Haixi|last3=Yu|first3=Xia|last4=Zeng|first4=Shuwen|last5=Yong|first5=Ken-Tye|last6=Ho|first6=Ho-Pui }}</ref><ref>Aroca, R., [https://books.google.com/books?id=Q7J75H9CmJMC&printsec=frontcover Surface-enhanced Vibrational Spectroscopy]. John Wiley & Sons (2006) {{ISBN|0-471-60731-2}}</ref> There is an ideal size for these particles, and an ideal surface thickness for each experiment.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1002/jrs.993|title=Study of silver films over silica beads as a surface-enhanced Raman scattering (SERS) substrate for detection of benzoic acid|date=2003|last1=Bao|first1=Li-Li|last2=Mahurin|first2=Shannon M.|last3=Liang|first3=Cheng-Du|last4=Dai|first4=Sheng|journal=Journal of Raman Spectroscopy|volume=34|issue=5|pages=394\u2013398|bibcode = 2003JRSp...34..394B |url=https://zenodo.org/record/1229261}}</ref> Particles that are too large allow the excitation of [[multipole]]s, which are nonradiative. As only the dipole transition leads to Raman scattering, the higher-order transitions will cause a decrease in the overall efficiency of the enhancement. Particles that are too small lose their electrical conductance and cannot enhance the field. When the particle size approaches a few atoms, the definition of a plasmon does not hold, as there must be a large collection of electrons to oscillate together.<ref name=\"Moskovits\" />\nAn ideal SERS substrate must possess high uniformity and high field enhancement. Such substrates can be fabricated on a wafer scale and label-free superresolution microscopy has also been demonstrated using the fluctuations of surface enhanced Raman scattering signal on such highly uniform, high-performance plasmonic metasurfaces.\n<ref>\n{{cite journal\n |last=Ayas |first=S.\n |date=2013\n |title=Label-Free Nanometer-Resolution Imaging of Biological Architectures through Surface Enhanced Raman Scattering\n |journal=[[Scientific Reports]]\n |volume=3 |pages=2624|doi=10.1038/srep02624|pmid=24022059\n |pmc=3769681\n |bibcode=2013NatSR...3E2624A}}</ref>\n\n==Applications==\nSERS substrates are used to detect the presence of low-abundance biomolecules, and can therefore detect proteins in bodily fluids.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last=Banaei|first=N|display-authors=etal |title=Multiplex detection of pancreatic cancer biomarkers using a SERS-based immunoassay|journal= Nanotechnology|volume=28|issue=45|pages=455101|date=September 2017|doi=10.1088/1361-6528/aa8e8c|pmid=28937361|bibcode=2017Nanot..28S5101B}}</ref> Early detection of pancreatic cancer biomarkers was accomplished using SERS-based immunoassay approach.<ref name=\":1\"/> A SERS-base multiplex protein biomarker detection platform in a microfluidic chip is used to detect several protein biomarkers to\npredict the type of disease and critical biomarkers and increase the chance of diagnosis between diseases with similar biomarkers (PC, OVC, and pancreatitis).<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|last=Banaei|first=N|display-authors=etal |title=Machine learning algorithms enhance the specificity of cancer biomarker detection using SERS-based immunoassays in microfluidic chips|journal=RSC Advances|volume=9|issue=4|pages=1859\u20131868|date=January 2019|doi=10.1039/c8ra08930b|doi-access=free}}</ref>\nThis technology has been utilized to detect urea and blood plasma label free in human serum and may become the next generation in cancer detection and screening.<ref name=\"Han 2014\">{{cite journal|last=Han|first=YA|author2=Ju J |author3=Yoon Y |author4=Kim SM |title=Fabrication of cost-effective surface enhanced Raman spectroscopy substrate using glancing angle deposition for the detection of urea in body fluid|journal=Journal of Nanoscience and Nanotechnology|date=May 2014|volume=14|issue=5|pages=3797\u20139|doi=10.1166/jnn.2014.8184 |pmid=24734638}}</ref><ref name=\"Li 2014\">{{cite journal|last=Li|first=D|author2=Feng S |author3=Huang H |author4=Chen W |author5=Shi H |author6=Liu N |author7=Chen L |author8=Chen W |author9=Yu Y |author10=Chen R |title=Label-free detection of blood plasma using silver nanoparticle based surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy for esophageal cancer screening|journal=Journal of Nanoscience and Nanotechnology|date=March 2014|volume=10|issue=3|pages=478\u201384|doi=10.1166/jbn.2014.1750 |pmid=24730243}}</ref>\n\nThe ability to analyze the composition of a mixture on the nano scale makes the use of SERS substrates beneficial for environmental analysis, pharmaceuticals, material sciences, art and archeological research, forensic science, drug and explosives detection, food quality analysis,<ref>Andreou, C., Mirsafavi, R., Moskovits, M., & Meinhart, C. D. (2015). Detection of low concentrations of ampicillin in milk. The Analyst, 140(15), 5003\u20135005. doi:10.1039/c5an00864f</ref> and single algal cell detection.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Deng|first=Y|author2=Juang Y |title=Black silicon SERS substrate: Effect of surface morphology on SERS detection and application of single algal cell analysis|journal=Biosensors and Bioelectronics|date=March 2014|volume=53|pages=37\u201342|doi=10.1016/j.bios.2013.09.032|pmid=24121206}}</ref><ref>{{cite techreport |first=Eric |last=Hoppmann |display-authors=etal |title=Trace detection overcoming the cost and usability limitations of traditional SERS technology |institution=Diagnostic anSERS |date=2013 | url=https://www.diagnosticansers.com/documentation/P-SERS-Whitepaper-v1.0.pdf\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Applied Optics|doi=10.1364/AO.49.004362|pmid=20697437|author1=Wackerbarth H|author2=Salb C|author3=Gundrum L|author4=Niederkr\u00fcger M|author5=Christou K|author6=Beushausen V|author7=Vi\u00f6l W|title=Detection of explosives based on surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy|date=2010|volume=49|issue=23|pages=4362\u20134366|bibcode=2010ApOpt..49.4362W}}</ref>\nSERS combined with plasmonic sensing can be used for high-sensitivity and quantitative analysis of small molecules in human biofluids,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|vauthors=Goodacre R, Graham D, Faulds K,|date=2018|title=Recent developments in quantitative SERS moving: towards absolute quantification|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0165993617304636|journal=Trends in Analytical Chemistry|volume=102|pages=359-368|doi=10.1016/j.trac.2018.03.005|via=}}</ref> quantitative detection of biomolecular interaction,<ref name=\"Nanoscale2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Xu|first1=Zhida|last2=Jiang|first2=Jing|last3=Wang|first3=Xinhao|last4=Han|first4=Kevin|last5=Ameen|first5=Abid|last6=Khan|first6=Ibrahim|last7=Chang|first7=Te-Wei|last8=Liu|first8=Logan|title=Large-area, uniform and low-cost dual-mode plasmonic naked-eye colorimetry and SERS sensor with handheld Raman spectrometer|journal=Nanoscale|date=2016|volume=8|issue=11|pages=6162\u20136172|doi=10.1039/C5NR08357E|pmid=26931437|arxiv=1603.01906|bibcode=2016Nanos...8.6162X}}</ref> and to study redox processes at the single molecule level.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cort\u00e9s|first=Emiliano|last2=Etchegoin|first2=Pablo G.|last3=Le Ru|first3=Eric C.|last4=Fainstein|first4=Alejandro|last5=Vela|first5=Mar\u00eda E.|last6=Salvarezza|first6=Roberto C.|date=2010-12-29|title=Monitoring the Electrochemistry of Single Molecules by Surface-Enhanced Raman Spectroscopy|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|volume=132|issue=51|pages=18034\u201318037|doi=10.1021/ja108989b|pmid=21138263|issn=0002-7863}}</ref>\n\n==Immunoassays==\nSERS-based immunoassays can be used for detection of low-abundance biomarkers. For example, antibodies and gold particles can be used to quantify proteins in serum with high sensitivity and specificity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Joseph|first=Manu M.|last2=Narayanan|first2=Nisha|last3=Nair|first3=Jyothi B.|last4=Karunakaran|first4=Varsha|last5=Ramya|first5=Adukkadan N.|last6=Sujai|first6=Palasseri T.|last7=Saranya|first7=Giridharan|last8=Arya|first8=Jayadev S.|last9=Vijayan|first9=Vineeth M.|last10=Maiti|first10=Kaustabh Kumar|date=2018-10-01|title=Exploring the margins of SERS in practical domain: An emerging diagnostic modality for modern biomedical applications|journal=Biomaterials|volume=181|pages=140\u2013181|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2018.07.045|pmid=30081304|issn=0142-9612}}</ref>\n\n===Oligonucleotide targeting===\nSERS can be used to target specific [[DNA]] and [[RNA]] sequences using a combination of gold and silver nanoparticles and Raman-active dyes, such as [[Cyanine|Cy3]]. Specific [[single nucleotide polymorphisms]] (SNP) can be identified using this technique. The gold nanoparticles facilitate the formation of a silver coating on the dye-labeled regions of DNA or RNA, allowing SERS to be performed. This has several potential applications: For example, Cao et al. report that gene sequences for HIV, Ebola, Hepatitis, and Bacillus Anthracis can be uniquely identified using this technique. Each spectrum was specific, which is advantageous over fluorescence detection; some fluorescent markers overlap and interfere with other gene markers. The advantage of this technique to identify gene sequences is that several Raman dyes are commercially available, which could lead to the development of non-overlapping probes for gene detection.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1126/science.297.5586.1536|title=Nanoparticles with Raman Spectroscopic Fingerprints for DNA and RNA Detection|date=2002|last1=Cao|first1=Y. C.|journal=Science|volume=297|issue=5586|pages=1536\u20131540|pmid=12202825|last2=Jin|first2=R|last3=Mirkin|first3=CA|bibcode = 2002Sci...297.1536C |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c828a5c7963d021dd9c9b8e8408be741575c29df}}</ref>\n\n==Selection rules==\nThe term ''surface enhanced Raman spectroscopy'' implies that it provides the same information that traditional Raman spectroscopy does, simply with a greatly enhanced signal. While the spectra of most SERS experiments are similar to the non-surface enhanced spectra, there are often differences in the number of modes present. Additional modes not found in the traditional Raman spectrum can be present in the SERS spectrum, while other modes can disappear. The modes observed in any spectroscopic experiment are dictated by the [[molecular symmetry|symmetry]] of the molecules and are usually summarized by [[Selection rule]]s. When molecules are adsorbed to a surface, the symmetry of the system can change, slightly modifying the symmetry of the molecule, which can lead to differences in mode selection.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/j150667a013|title=Surface selection rules for surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy: calculations and application to the surface-enhanced Raman spectrum of phthalazine on silver|date=1984|last1=Moskovits|first1=M.|last2=Suh|first2=J. S.|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry|volume=88|issue=23|pages=5526\u20135530}}</ref>\n\nOne common way in which selection rules are modified arises from the fact that many molecules that have a [[center of symmetry]] lose that feature when adsorbed to a surface. The loss of a center of symmetry eliminates the requirements of the [[Rule of mutual exclusion|mutual exclusion rule]], which dictates that modes can only be either Raman or infrared active. Thus modes that would normally appear only in the [[infrared spectroscopy|infrared spectrum]] of the free molecule can appear in the SERS spectrum.<ref name=\"Smith2005\"/>\n\nA molecule's symmetry can be changed in different ways depending on the orientation in which the molecule is attached to the surface. In some experiments, it is possible to determine the orientation of adsorption to the surface from the SERS spectrum, as different modes will be present depending on how the symmetry is modified.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/S0022-0728(03)00215-8|url=http://web.uvic.ca/~agbrolo/JECau111bipy.pdf|title=The orientation of 2,2\u2032-bipyridine adsorbed at a SERS-active Au(111) electrode surface|date=2003|last1=Brolo|first1=A.G.|last2=Jiang|first2=Z.|last3=Irish|first3=D.E.|journal=Journal of Electroanalytical Chemistry|volume=547|issue=2|pages=163\u2013172 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tip-enhanced Raman spectroscopy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Raman spectroscopy}}\n\n[[Category:Surface science]]\n[[Category:Raman scattering]]\n[[Category:Raman spectroscopy]]\n[[Category:Plasmonics]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApplications:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface-enhanced_Raman_spectroscopy"}
{"title_page": "Bathabile Dlamini", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n|honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n|name                = Bathabile Dlamini\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n|image               =\n|imagesize           =\n|smallimage          =\n|caption             =\n|order               =\n|office              = Minister of Women in the Presidency\n|term_start          = 27 February 2018\n|term_end            = 29 May 2019\n|vicepresident       =\n|viceprimeminister   =\n|president           = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor         = [[Susan Shabangu]]\n|successor           = [[Maite Nkoana-Mashabane]]\n|office2             = Minister of Social Development\n|term_start2         = 1 November 2010\n|term_end2           = 27 February 2018\n|president2          = [[Jacob Zuma]]<br>[[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor2        = [[Edna Molewa]]\n|successor2          =[[Susan Shabangu]]\n|birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1992|9|10|df=y}}\n|birth_place         = Nquthu, [[KwaZulu-Natal]]\n|death_date          =\n|death_place         =\n|nationality         = {{flagicon|South Africa}} [[South Africa]]n\n|party               = [[African National Congress|ANC]] \n|spouse              =\n|relations           =\n|children            =\n|residence           =\n|alma_mater          = [[University of Zululand]]\n|occupation          =\n|profession          =\n|religion            =\n|signature           =\n|website             = \n|footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Bathabile Olive Dlamini''' MP, (born 10 September 1992, Nquthu, KwaZulu-Natal) is the leader of the [[African National Congress Women's League]] (ANCWL). She was previously the [[Minister of Women in the Presidency (South Africa)|Minister of Women in the Presidency]], and [[Minister of Social Development (South Africa)|Minister of Social Development]].\n\n==Early years==\n\nDlamini was born in Nquthu on 10 September 1962 and grew up in Nkandla, Matshensikazi<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title=Minister Bathabile Dlamini Profile|url=http://www.dsd.gov.za/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=49&Itemid=49|website=Department of Social Development|accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref> and Imbali, [[Pietermaritzburg]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bathabile Dlamini is heartless, say former neighbours|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/bathabile-dlamini-is-heartless-say-former-neighbours-8096141|website=Independent Newspapers Online|accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref> She graduated with a Bachelor of Arts Degree in Social Studies from the [[University of Zululand]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa/who-bathebile-dlamini|title=What you should know about new ANCWL leader, Bathabile Dlamini|last=Magcaba|first=Sbonokuhle|date=2015-08-08|website=eNCA|language=en|access-date=2017-05-01}}</ref>\n\nDlamini was politically active from an early age. In 1983 she became one of the founding members of Imbali Youth Organisation, an affiliate of the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]], which worked closely with the [[South African Students Congress]] and Imbali Civic Organisation. In 1985, she joined the South African National Students Congress as one of only a few women who participated in its politics. In 1989,  Dlamini graduated from the University of Zululand with a Bachelor of Arts (Honours) in Social Work which she passed with distinction.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== ANCWL ==\nIn 1991 she became part of interim leadership that built the African National Congress (ANC) Women's League structures in [[KwaZulu-Natal]]. She was then elected to the first Regional Executive Committee of the ANCWL. In 1992 and 1993, she served as Regional Secretary, and was elected as Deputy Secretary General of the ANCWL in 1993.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 1998 she was elected Secretary General of the ANCWL, and served for two terms until 2008.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn 7 August 2015, Dlamini was elected as the ANCWL's new leader, replacing then-[[Minister of Basic Education]], [[Angie Motshekga]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2017 Dlamini campaigned for former [[African Union]] chairperson [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]] to be elected as president of the ANC.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-03-06-queen-con-bathabile-dlamini-the-face-of-the-ancs-future/|title=Queen Con: Bathabile Dlamini, the face of the ANC\u2019s future|last=Munusamy|first=Ranjeni|date=2017-03-06|website=The Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2017-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Parliament ==\nIn 2001, Dlamini was appointed as a Member of [[Parliament of South Africa|Parliament]] \n\n=== Travelgate ===\nIn 2006, the [[Scorpions (South Africa)|Directorate of Special Operations]] implicated Dlamini and thirteen other ANC MPs in what South African media called the \"Travelgate\" scandal, a scandal involving abuse of Parliamentary travel vouchers. Her charge sheet stated that she knew the travel vouchers could be used only for air travel but nevertheless used them to cover the costs of hotel accommodation, car rentals, and other benefits. She was convicted of fraud after pleading guilty to a total of R245,000 in fraudulent travel claims.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2006-10-16-travelgate-14-plead-guilty|title=Travelgate: 14 plead guilty|last=Maclennan|first=Ben|date=16 Oct 2006|publisher=Mail & Guardian|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nDlamini subsequently lost her position as a member of Parliament. However, at the [[52nd National Conference of the African National Congress|52nd National Conference of the ANC]] in December 2007, Dlamini was elected to the ANC's [[National Executive Committee of the African National Congress|National Executive]] and National Working Committees.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Department of Social Development ==\nDlamini was appointed as Deputy Minister of [[Department of Social Development (South Africa)|Social Development]] on 11 May 2009, and became Minister of Social Development on 1 November 2010.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAs Chairperson of the Inter-Ministerial Committee (IMC) on Gender Based Violence, she led the roll out of the Gender-Based Violence Command Centre, a 24-hour call centre which supported and counselled victims of gender-based violence. Dlamini also chaired the IMC on Combating Substance Abuse and the IMC for Early Childhood Development.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2016, Dlamini was challenged by the opposition [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] after she defended the amount of R753 per month that a social grant beneficiary receives as \"enough to buy adequate food as well as additional non-food items\", while she herself stayed at hotels costing R11,000 a night.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/government/126711/minister-who-said-south-africans-can-survive-on-r753-accused-of-r11000-luxury-hotel-room-splurge/|title=Minister who said South Africans can survive on R753, accused of R11,000 luxury hotel room splurge|date=13 June 2016|accessdate=19 March 2017|publisher=Business Tech}}</ref> In late 2016 she also accepted at luxury car valued at R1.3 million, and her deputy, Hendrietta Bogopane-Zulu, a R1.1 million car.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mokone|first1=Thabo|title=Bathabile Dlamini scores new R1.3 million luxury sedan for herself|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2017/05/10/Bathabile-Dlamini-scores-new-R1.3-million-luxury-sedan-for-herself|accessdate=10 May 2017|date=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Grants crisis ===\n{{main|Department of Social Development (South Africa)#Grants crisis}}As Minister of Social Development, Dlamini failed to realise the government's plan to take over payment of South Africa's social grants by 31 March 2017, when the existing arrangement with [[Cash Paymaster Services]] to distribute payments had been due to expire. This created a concern that welfare recipients would not receive grant payments from 1 April 2017.  Dlamini was criticised for her lack of action and her inability to ensure either a new service contract or the insourcing of the service. She was also criticised for her handling of the media during the controversy.<ref name=\":2\" /> On 6 March 2017, the contract with Cash Paymaster Services was renewed for another 2 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2017/03/06/its-a-deal-the-new-social-grants-contract-is-a-done-deal/|title=It's A Deal: The New Social Grants Contract Is A Done Deal|last=Evans|first=Jenni|date=6 March 2017|website=Huffington Post South Africa|access-date=2017-03-06}}</ref>\n\nThe Constitutional Court held Dlamini primarily responsible for the crisis,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2017-03-17-constitutional-court-rules-in-sassa-grants-saga/|title=Dlamini responsible for social grants crisis, says Constitutional Court|last=Quintal|first=Genevieve|date=2017-03-17|work=Business Day Live|access-date=2017-05-09|language=en-US}}</ref> with Chief Justice [[Mogoeng Mogoeng]] saying there was no explanation for the incompetence displayed by her and SASSA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/no-explanation-for-sassa-dlaminis-incompetence-mogoeng-20170315|title=No explanation for Sassa, Dlamini's 'incompetence' - Mogoeng|last=Chabalala|first=Jeanette|date=2017-03-15|work=News24|access-date=2017-05-09|last2=Raborife|first2=Mpho}}</ref> According to constitutional scholar [[Pierre de Vos]], the Constitutional Court had concluded that SASSA and Dlamini could not be trusted to do their constitutionally mandated job to ensure delivery of social grants, and could not be trusted not to lie to the courts in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2017-03-17-sassa-grant-crisis-in-this-game-of-thrones-can-social-development-minister-bathabile-dlamini-survive/|title=Sassa grant crisis: In this game of thrones, can Social Development Minister Bathabile Dlamini survive?|last=de Vosq|first=Pierre|date=2017-03-17|website=The Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2017-05-08}}</ref>\n\nIn September of 2018 the Constitutional Court found, unanimously, that Dlamini ought to be held accountable in her personal capacity for 20% of the costs of the case brought against her by Black Sash Trust and Freedom Under Law. Further, she was found to have misled the court \u2013 that is, she lied under oath \u2013 in order to protect herself. The National Prosecuting Authority will decide whether or not to charge her with perjury.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Saba |first1=Athandiwe |title=Bathabile Dlamini slapped with court costs, possible perjury probe |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-09-27-bathabile-dlamini-slapped-with-court-costs-possible-perjury-probe |date=2018-09-27|accessdate=9 November 2018 |publisher=Mail and Guardian}}</ref>\n\nDespite her failures, President [[Jacob Zuma]] continued to support Dlamini.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldlive.co.za/news/2017/03/16/zuma-stands-bathabile-dlamini/|title=Zuma stands by Bathabile Dlamini|last=Ndenze|first=Babalo|date=2017-03-16|website=The Herald Live|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-08}}</ref> She in turn supported Zuma's preferred candidate, Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma, in her campaign to succeed him as ANC leader and South Africa's president.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/rdm/politics/2017-03-09-politics-live-why-bathabile-dlamini-is-untouchable/|title=POLITICS LIVE: Why Bathabile Dlamini is untouchable|last=Hartley|first=Ray|date=2017-03-09|work=Business Day|access-date=2017-05-08|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Absenteeism ===\nThe Minister was also criticised for not appearing before Parliament or in DSD portfolio committee meetings during and in the wake of the grants crisis.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.itweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=159813|title=SASSA fails to get affairs in order|last=Mzekandaba|first=Simnikiwe|date=2017-03-01|work=ITWeb Technology News|access-date=2017-05-07}}</ref> The Parliamentary Monitoring Group's People's Assembly indicated that Dlamini was among the most prolific attendees at parliamentary committee meetings in 2016. However, her attendance waned in 2017, when she was expected to account for the grants crisis; between her and her Deputy Minister, [[Hendrietta Bogopane-Zulu]], by the first week of May, the DSD had appeared in only three of the nine meetings that had taken place in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/bathabile-bunks-parly-meetings-20170506|title=Bathabile bunks Parly meetings|last=Makinana|first=Andisiwe|date=2017-05-07|work=City Press|access-date=2017-05-08}}</ref> In February, Dlamini failed to appear before Parliament's [[Standing Committee on Public Accounts]] (SCOPA) to account for irregular expenditure of about R1 billion by the [[South African Social Security Agency]] (SASSA) during the 2016/2017 financial year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-02-28-social-grants-crisis-rogue-minister-on-a-suicide-mission-bathabile-dlamini-undermines-parliament-again|title=Social Grants Crisis: Rogue minister on a suicide mission \u2013 Bathabile Dlamini undermines Parliament, again|last=Thamm|first=Marianne|date=28 February 2017|publisher=Daily Maverick|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"staff\">{{cite web |last1=Staff Writer |title=These are the ministers who still haven\u2019t showed up to parliamentary meetings this year |url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/government/260329/these-are-the-ministers-who-still-havent-showed-up-to-parliamentary-meetings-this-year/ |website=businesstech.co.za|date = 23 July 2018 |accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Private Security ===\nIn mid-May 2017, Minister Dlamini appeared before a parliamentary SCOPA meeting where, amongst other issues, she was questioned about R1 million spent on private VIP security for her children, paid for by SASSA.<ref name=\"dailymaverick.co.za\">{{cite news|last1=Thamm|first1=Marianne|title=Bathabile Dlamini admits Sassa paid for private security for her children|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-05-17-bathabile-dlamini-admits-sassa-paid-for-private-security-for-her-children/#.WRwNfFP5iRs|accessdate=17 May 2017|date=17 May 2017}}</ref> Responding to questions about this very irregular arrangement, Dlamini responded that \"some people understand government more than others\u201d, and that she had to resort to private security due to the fact that \"government processes take a long period\u201d. She further claimed that, despite the VIP protection she received through the South African Police Service (SAPS), her home was broken into on three separate occasions.<ref name=\"dailymaverick.co.za\"/>In 2018, she requested for security following threats made on her family. This led to the inquiry of about 2 million rands which she then needed to pay back for the services after opposition party members request she pays for the services. <ref>https://m.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sassa-wants-to-recoup-r2m-spent-on-security-for-bathabile-dlaminis-children-20180504 | Sassa wants to recoup R2m spent on security for Bathabile Dlamini's children | News24</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dlamini, Bathabile}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:University of Zululand alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n|honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n|name                = Bathabile Dlamini\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n|image               =\n|imagesize           =\n|smallimage          =\n|caption             =\n|order               =\n|office              = Minister of Women in the Presidency\n|term_start          = 27 February 2018\n|term_end            = 29 May 2019\n|vicepresident       =\n|viceprimeminister   =\n|president           = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor         = [[Susan Shabangu]]\n|successor           = [[Maite Nkoana-Mashabane]]\n|office2             = Minister of Social Development\n|term_start2         = 1 November 2010\n|term_end2           = 27 February 2018\n|president2          = [[Jacob Zuma]]<br>[[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor2        = [[Edna Molewa]]\n|successor2          =[[Susan Shabangu]]\n|birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1992|9|10|df=y}}\n|birth_place         = Nquthu, [[KwaZulu-Natal]]\n|death_date          =\n|death_place         =\n|nationality         = {{flagicon|South Africa}} [[South Africa]]n\n|party               = [[African National Congress|ANC]] \n|spouse              =\n|relations           =\n|children            =\n|residence           =\n|alma_mater          = [[University of Zululand]]\n|occupation          =\n|profession          =\n|religion            =\n|signature           =\n|website             = \n|footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Bathabile Olive Dlamini''' MP, (born 10 September 1962, Nquthu, KwaZulu-Natal) is the leader of the [[African National Congress Women's League]] (ANCWL). She was previously the [[Minister of Women in the Presidency (South Africa)|Minister of Women in the Presidency]], and [[Minister of Social Development (South Africa)|Minister of Social Development]].\n\n==Early years==\n\nDlamini was born in Nquthu on 10 September 1962 and grew up in Nkandla, Matshensikazi<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title=Minister Bathabile Dlamini Profile|url=http://www.dsd.gov.za/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=49&Itemid=49|website=Department of Social Development|accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref> and Imbali, [[Pietermaritzburg]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bathabile Dlamini is heartless, say former neighbours|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/bathabile-dlamini-is-heartless-say-former-neighbours-8096141|website=Independent Newspapers Online|accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref> She graduated with a Bachelor of Arts Degree in Social Studies from the [[University of Zululand]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.enca.com/south-africa/who-bathebile-dlamini|title=What you should know about new ANCWL leader, Bathabile Dlamini|last=Magcaba|first=Sbonokuhle|date=2015-08-08|website=eNCA|language=en|access-date=2017-05-01}}</ref>\n\nDlamini was politically active from an early age. In 1983 she became one of the founding members of Imbali Youth Organisation, an affiliate of the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]], which worked closely with the [[South African Students Congress]] and Imbali Civic Organisation. In 1985, she joined the South African National Students Congress as one of only a few women who participated in its politics. In 1989,  Dlamini graduated from the University of Zululand with a Bachelor of Arts (Honours) in Social Work which she passed with distinction.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== ANCWL ==\nIn 1991 she became part of interim leadership that built the African National Congress (ANC) Women's League structures in [[KwaZulu-Natal]]. She was then elected to the first Regional Executive Committee of the ANCWL. In 1992 and 1993, she served as Regional Secretary, and was elected as Deputy Secretary General of the ANCWL in 1993.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 1998 she was elected Secretary General of the ANCWL, and served for two terms until 2008.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn 7 August 2015, Dlamini was elected as the ANCWL's new leader, replacing then-[[Minister of Basic Education]], [[Angie Motshekga]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2017 Dlamini campaigned for former [[African Union]] chairperson [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]] to be elected as president of the ANC.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-03-06-queen-con-bathabile-dlamini-the-face-of-the-ancs-future/|title=Queen Con: Bathabile Dlamini, the face of the ANC\u2019s future|last=Munusamy|first=Ranjeni|date=2017-03-06|website=The Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2017-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Parliament ==\nIn 2001, Dlamini was appointed as a Member of [[Parliament of South Africa|Parliament]] \n\n=== Travelgate ===\nIn 2006, the [[Scorpions (South Africa)|Directorate of Special Operations]] implicated Dlamini and thirteen other ANC MPs in what South African media called the \"Travelgate\" scandal, a scandal involving abuse of Parliamentary travel vouchers. Her charge sheet stated that she knew the travel vouchers could be used only for air travel but nevertheless used them to cover the costs of hotel accommodation, car rentals, and other benefits. She was convicted of fraud after pleading guilty to a total of R245,000 in fraudulent travel claims.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2006-10-16-travelgate-14-plead-guilty|title=Travelgate: 14 plead guilty|last=Maclennan|first=Ben|date=16 Oct 2006|publisher=Mail & Guardian|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nDlamini subsequently lost her position as a member of Parliament. However, at the [[52nd National Conference of the African National Congress|52nd National Conference of the ANC]] in December 2007, Dlamini was elected to the ANC's [[National Executive Committee of the African National Congress|National Executive]] and National Working Committees.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Department of Social Development ==\nDlamini was appointed as Deputy Minister of [[Department of Social Development (South Africa)|Social Development]] on 11 May 2009, and became Minister of Social Development on 1 November 2010.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAs Chairperson of the Inter-Ministerial Committee (IMC) on Gender Based Violence, she led the roll out of the Gender-Based Violence Command Centre, a 24-hour call centre which supported and counselled victims of gender-based violence. Dlamini also chaired the IMC on Combating Substance Abuse and the IMC for Early Childhood Development.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2016, Dlamini was challenged by the opposition [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] after she defended the amount of R753 per month that a social grant beneficiary receives as \"enough to buy adequate food as well as additional non-food items\", while she herself stayed at hotels costing R11,000 a night.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/government/126711/minister-who-said-south-africans-can-survive-on-r753-accused-of-r11000-luxury-hotel-room-splurge/|title=Minister who said South Africans can survive on R753, accused of R11,000 luxury hotel room splurge|date=13 June 2016|accessdate=19 March 2017|publisher=Business Tech}}</ref> In late 2016 she also accepted at luxury car valued at R1.3 million, and her deputy, Hendrietta Bogopane-Zulu, a R1.1 million car.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mokone|first1=Thabo|title=Bathabile Dlamini scores new R1.3 million luxury sedan for herself|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2017/05/10/Bathabile-Dlamini-scores-new-R1.3-million-luxury-sedan-for-herself|accessdate=10 May 2017|date=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Grants crisis ===\n{{main|Department of Social Development (South Africa)#Grants crisis}}As Minister of Social Development, Dlamini failed to realise the government's plan to take over payment of South Africa's social grants by 31 March 2017, when the existing arrangement with [[Cash Paymaster Services]] to distribute payments had been due to expire. This created a concern that welfare recipients would not receive grant payments from 1 April 2017.  Dlamini was criticised for her lack of action and her inability to ensure either a new service contract or the insourcing of the service. She was also criticised for her handling of the media during the controversy.<ref name=\":2\" /> On 6 March 2017, the contract with Cash Paymaster Services was renewed for another 2 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2017/03/06/its-a-deal-the-new-social-grants-contract-is-a-done-deal/|title=It's A Deal: The New Social Grants Contract Is A Done Deal|last=Evans|first=Jenni|date=6 March 2017|website=Huffington Post South Africa|access-date=2017-03-06}}</ref>\n\nThe Constitutional Court held Dlamini primarily responsible for the crisis,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2017-03-17-constitutional-court-rules-in-sassa-grants-saga/|title=Dlamini responsible for social grants crisis, says Constitutional Court|last=Quintal|first=Genevieve|date=2017-03-17|work=Business Day Live|access-date=2017-05-09|language=en-US}}</ref> with Chief Justice [[Mogoeng Mogoeng]] saying there was no explanation for the incompetence displayed by her and SASSA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/no-explanation-for-sassa-dlaminis-incompetence-mogoeng-20170315|title=No explanation for Sassa, Dlamini's 'incompetence' - Mogoeng|last=Chabalala|first=Jeanette|date=2017-03-15|work=News24|access-date=2017-05-09|last2=Raborife|first2=Mpho}}</ref> According to constitutional scholar [[Pierre de Vos]], the Constitutional Court had concluded that SASSA and Dlamini could not be trusted to do their constitutionally mandated job to ensure delivery of social grants, and could not be trusted not to lie to the courts in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2017-03-17-sassa-grant-crisis-in-this-game-of-thrones-can-social-development-minister-bathabile-dlamini-survive/|title=Sassa grant crisis: In this game of thrones, can Social Development Minister Bathabile Dlamini survive?|last=de Vosq|first=Pierre|date=2017-03-17|website=The Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2017-05-08}}</ref>\n\nIn September of 2018 the Constitutional Court found, unanimously, that Dlamini ought to be held accountable in her personal capacity for 20% of the costs of the case brought against her by Black Sash Trust and Freedom Under Law. Further, she was found to have misled the court \u2013 that is, she lied under oath \u2013 in order to protect herself. The National Prosecuting Authority will decide whether or not to charge her with perjury.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Saba |first1=Athandiwe |title=Bathabile Dlamini slapped with court costs, possible perjury probe |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-09-27-bathabile-dlamini-slapped-with-court-costs-possible-perjury-probe |date=2018-09-27|accessdate=9 November 2018 |publisher=Mail and Guardian}}</ref>\n\nDespite her failures, President [[Jacob Zuma]] continued to support Dlamini.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldlive.co.za/news/2017/03/16/zuma-stands-bathabile-dlamini/|title=Zuma stands by Bathabile Dlamini|last=Ndenze|first=Babalo|date=2017-03-16|website=The Herald Live|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-08}}</ref> She in turn supported Zuma's preferred candidate, Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma, in her campaign to succeed him as ANC leader and South Africa's president.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/rdm/politics/2017-03-09-politics-live-why-bathabile-dlamini-is-untouchable/|title=POLITICS LIVE: Why Bathabile Dlamini is untouchable|last=Hartley|first=Ray|date=2017-03-09|work=Business Day|access-date=2017-05-08|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Absenteeism ===\nThe Minister was also criticised for not appearing before Parliament or in DSD portfolio committee meetings during and in the wake of the grants crisis.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.itweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=159813|title=SASSA fails to get affairs in order|last=Mzekandaba|first=Simnikiwe|date=2017-03-01|work=ITWeb Technology News|access-date=2017-05-07}}</ref> The Parliamentary Monitoring Group's People's Assembly indicated that Dlamini was among the most prolific attendees at parliamentary committee meetings in 2016. However, her attendance waned in 2017, when she was expected to account for the grants crisis; between her and her Deputy Minister, [[Hendrietta Bogopane-Zulu]], by the first week of May, the DSD had appeared in only three of the nine meetings that had taken place in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/bathabile-bunks-parly-meetings-20170506|title=Bathabile bunks Parly meetings|last=Makinana|first=Andisiwe|date=2017-05-07|work=City Press|access-date=2017-05-08}}</ref> In February, Dlamini failed to appear before Parliament's [[Standing Committee on Public Accounts]] (SCOPA) to account for irregular expenditure of about R1 billion by the [[South African Social Security Agency]] (SASSA) during the 2016/2017 financial year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-02-28-social-grants-crisis-rogue-minister-on-a-suicide-mission-bathabile-dlamini-undermines-parliament-again|title=Social Grants Crisis: Rogue minister on a suicide mission \u2013 Bathabile Dlamini undermines Parliament, again|last=Thamm|first=Marianne|date=28 February 2017|publisher=Daily Maverick|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"staff\">{{cite web |last1=Staff Writer |title=These are the ministers who still haven\u2019t showed up to parliamentary meetings this year |url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/government/260329/these-are-the-ministers-who-still-havent-showed-up-to-parliamentary-meetings-this-year/ |website=businesstech.co.za|date = 23 July 2018 |accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Private Security ===\nIn mid-May 2017, Minister Dlamini appeared before a parliamentary SCOPA meeting where, amongst other issues, she was questioned about R1 million spent on private VIP security for her children, paid for by SASSA.<ref name=\"dailymaverick.co.za\">{{cite news|last1=Thamm|first1=Marianne|title=Bathabile Dlamini admits Sassa paid for private security for her children|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-05-17-bathabile-dlamini-admits-sassa-paid-for-private-security-for-her-children/#.WRwNfFP5iRs|accessdate=17 May 2017|date=17 May 2017}}</ref> Responding to questions about this very irregular arrangement, Dlamini responded that \"some people understand government more than others\u201d, and that she had to resort to private security due to the fact that \"government processes take a long period\u201d. She further claimed that, despite the VIP protection she received through the South African Police Service (SAPS), her home was broken into on three separate occasions.<ref name=\"dailymaverick.co.za\"/>In 2018, she requested for security following threats made on her family. This led to the inquiry of about 2 million rands which she then needed to pay back for the services after opposition party members request she pays for the services. <ref>https://m.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sassa-wants-to-recoup-r2m-spent-on-security-for-bathabile-dlaminis-children-20180504 | Sassa wants to recoup R2m spent on security for Bathabile Dlamini's children | News24</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dlamini, Bathabile}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:University of Zululand alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Brooxy4444", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bathabile_Dlamini"}
{"title_page": "Brockagh", "text_new": "[[File:St Marys Catholic Church,Brockagh.jpg|thumb|St Brigids Catholic Church]]\n\n'''Brockagh''' (or '''Brocagh''',<ref>[http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/article/1349/brocagh-and-belville-house \"Brocagh and Belville House\"], Culture Northern Ireland</ref> {{etymology|ga|Brocach|[[badger]] warren}}) is a village in [[County Tyrone]], [[Northern Ireland]]. It is on the western shore of [[Lough Neagh]], about {{convert|7|km|mi}} east of [[Coalisland]] and north of [[Washing Bay]]. It lies within the [[Dungannon and South Tyrone Borough Council]] area. They are best known for their domination of derrytresk in the u16 final a few years back. Brocagh GAA have not hit the peaks of their football yet, with the rise of players such as marc canavan, Brandon Mckiver, Shea Ryan and last but not least lee wylie. With the corona Virus outbreak as of late, castle bay bar has not pulled a pint in many weeks which leaves a few men under the weather. <ref name=\"PS\">{{cite web | title=Brockagh/Mountjoy | work=Planning Service - Dungannon & South Tyrone Area Plan 2010 | url=http://www.planningni.gov.uk/index/policy/dev_plans/devplans_az/dungannon_2010/dungannon_settlements/dungannon_villages/dungannon_brockagh.htm | accessdate=2009-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nThe village consists mostly of single dwellings and farm buildings, although some in-depth development has recently taken place to the north of Mountjoy Road and to the west of Ballybeg Road. Land adjacent to the Duckingstool River may be subject to flooding.<ref name=\"PS\"/>\n\n== Places of interest ==\n[[File:Mountjoy Castle,County Tyrone.jpg|thumb|Mountjoy Castle]]\n*[[Mountjoy Castle]] is situated near the village of Brocagh, on a hill overlooking [[Lough Neagh]]. It was built by [[Charles Blount, 1st Earl of Devonshire|Lord Mountjoy]] in 1602 and partly burned in 1643.\n\n== People ==\n;Venerable Mary Angeline Teresa\n\nOn 28 June 2012 Pope Benedict XVI authorized the Congregation for the Causes of Saints in Rome to promulgate the decree of Heroic Virtues of their Foundress, Mother Mary Angeline Teresa, O.Carm.\n\nBrigid Teresa McCrory  was born on 21 January 1893 in Brockagh, Tyrone, Ireland. When she was seven years of age her family migrated to Bellshill Mossend, Scotland, and at the age of nineteen she left home to become a Little Sister of the Poor. In 1915 she was sent to the United States, and in the late 1920s founded the [[Carmelite Sisters for the Aged and Infirm]]. She opened 59 homes for the aged and died on 21 January 1984, her birthday.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n== Education ==\n*St. Brigid's Primary School, Brocagh\n\n==Sport==\n*[[Brocagh Emmetts]] [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] club is based in the village.\n*[[Naomh Br\u00edd Brocagh]] [[Camogie association]] club is also based in the village\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of villages in Northern Ireland]]\n*[[List of towns in Northern Ireland]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161002171923/http://stbrigidsps.co.uk/ St. Brigid's Primary School, Brocagh]\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Brockagh}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{NI County Tyrone}}\n{{coord|54|33|N|6|36|W|region:GB_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in County Tyrone]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:St Marys Catholic Church,Brockagh.jpg|thumb|St Brigids Catholic Church]]\n\n'''Brockagh''' (or '''Brocagh''',<ref>[http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/article/1349/brocagh-and-belville-house \"Brocagh and Belville House\"], Culture Northern Ireland</ref> {{etymology|ga|Brocach|[[badger]] warren}}) is a village in [[County Tyrone]], [[Northern Ireland]]. It is on the western shore of [[Lough Neagh]], about {{convert|7|km|mi}} east of [[Coalisland]] and north of [[Washing Bay]]. It lies within the [[Dungannon and South Tyrone Borough Council]] area.<ref name=\"PS\">{{cite web | title=Brockagh/Mountjoy | work=Planning Service - Dungannon & South Tyrone Area Plan 2010 | url=http://www.planningni.gov.uk/index/policy/dev_plans/devplans_az/dungannon_2010/dungannon_settlements/dungannon_villages/dungannon_brockagh.htm | accessdate=2009-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nThe village consists mostly of single dwellings and farm buildings, although some in-depth development has recently taken place to the north of Mountjoy Road and to the west of Ballybeg Road. Land adjacent to the Duckingstool River may be subject to flooding.<ref name=\"PS\"/>\n\n== Places of interest ==\n[[File:Mountjoy Castle,County Tyrone.jpg|thumb|Mountjoy Castle]]\n*[[Mountjoy Castle]] is situated near the village of Brocagh, on a hill overlooking [[Lough Neagh]]. It was built by [[Charles Blount, 1st Earl of Devonshire|Lord Mountjoy]] in 1602 and partly burned in 1643.\n\n== People ==\n;Venerable Mary Angeline Teresa\n\nOn 28 June 2012 Pope Benedict XVI authorized the Congregation for the Causes of Saints in Rome to promulgate the decree of Heroic Virtues of their Foundress, Mother Mary Angeline Teresa, O.Carm.\n\nBrigid Teresa McCrory  was born on 21 January 1893 in Brockagh, Tyrone, Ireland. When she was seven years of age her family migrated to Bellshill Mossend, Scotland, and at the age of nineteen she left home to become a Little Sister of the Poor. In 1915 she was sent to the United States, and in the late 1920s founded the [[Carmelite Sisters for the Aged and Infirm]]. She opened 59 homes for the aged and died on 21 January 1984, her birthday.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n== Education ==\n*St. Brigid's Primary School, Brocagh\n\n==Sport==\n*[[Brocagh Emmetts]] [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] club is based in the village.\n*[[Naomh Br\u00edd Brocagh]] [[Camogie association]] club is also based in the village\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of villages in Northern Ireland]]\n*[[List of towns in Northern Ireland]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161002171923/http://stbrigidsps.co.uk/ St. Brigid's Primary School, Brocagh]\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Brockagh}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{NI County Tyrone}}\n{{coord|54|33|N|6|36|W|region:GB_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in County Tyrone]]\n", "name_user": "84.13.228.186", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brockagh"}
{"title_page": "Triple Concerto No. 2", "text_new": "The '''Triple Concerto No. 2''', [[Opus number|Op]]. 139, is a [[Triple concerto|concerto for three instruments]], [[violin]],  [[harp]] and [[double bass]], and orchestra by [[Dmitri Smirnov (composer)|Dmitri Smirnov]], composed in 2003.\n\n== History ==\nSmirnov composed several [[concerto]]s for single instruments, and two triple concertos for three instruments, the Triple Concerto No. 1 for [[saxophone]], [[piano]], [[double bass]], [[String instrument|strings]] and [[percussion]] in 1977<ref name=\"Sikorski\" /> when he lived in Russia,<ref name=\"Boosey\" /> and the Triple Concerto No. 2 for [[violin]], [[harp]], double bass and orchestra in 2003,<ref name=\"No. 2\" /> when he was a resident of England.<ref name=\"Boosey\" /> It was published by [[Boosey & Hawkes]].<ref name=\"No. 2\" />\n\nThe world premiere of the Triple Concerto No. 2 was performed at the [[Barbican Centre]] in London on 26 May 2004. In the concert marking the centenary of [[London Symphony Orchestra & Chorus]] (LSO), it was called LSO Centenary Concertante, and was combined with Mahler's [[Symphony No. 2 (Mahler)|Second Symphony]] \"Resurrection\", with [[Andrew Davis (conductor)|Andrew Davis]] conducting the [[London Symphony Orchestra & Chorus]].<ref name=\"No. 2\" /><ref name=\"Russell\" /> The soloists were violinist [[Gordan Nikolitch]], harpist Bryn Lewis, and double bassist [[Rinat Ibragimov (musician)|Rinat Ibragimov]],<ref name=\"No. 2\" /> all principal players of the LSO.<ref name=\"Russell\" />\n\n== Scoring ==\nThe Triple Concerto is structured in three sections or [[Movement (music)|movements]]:<ref name=\"Russell\" />\n# Con moto\n# Lento\n# Presto\n\nSmirnov scored the work for the three solo instruments, and an orchestra consisting of [[piccolo]], [[cor anglais]], [[bass clarinet]], [[percussion]] (3-4 players of [[timpani]], [[Triangle (musical instrument)|triangle]], [[suspended cymbal]], [[maraca]]s, [[Woodblock (instrument)|woodblock]], [[bongo]]s, [[tom-tom]], [[gong]]s, [[tam-tam]], [[side drum]], [[base drum]], [[glockenspiel]], [[xylophone]], [[bell]]s), and strings.<ref name=\"No. 2\" /> The concerto takes about 25 minutes to perform.<ref name=\"Russell\" />\n\nThe first movement has been described be a reviewer as \"music meant to wound\", the second movement as \"unsettling and angst-ridden\", and the third movement compared a [[Alfred Hitchcock|Hitchcock]] film track.<ref name=\"Russell\" /> The three solo instruments complement each other, compared to voice types soprano of the violin, mezzo-soprano of the harp, and basso profundo of the double bass. They are at times combined sounding like one voice, at times \"also play in radical styles with distinctly foreign sounding voices\".<ref name=\"Russell\" /> Episodes follow eache other in collage fashion, in intentionally heterogen styles and sounds.<ref name=\"Russell\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Russell\">{{cite web\n| last = Russell\n| first = Alex\n| url = http://www.musicweb-international.com/SandH/2004/May-Aug04/smirnov_mahler265.htm\n| title = Dmitri Smirnov & Gustav Mahler; Gordan Nikolitch (violin), Rinat Ibragimov (double-bass), Bryn Lewis (harp); Laura Claycomb (sop), Michelle DeYoung (mez-sop); London Symphony Orchestra & Chorus; Sir Andrew Davis (conductor); Barbican Centre, 26th May, 2004\n| website = musicweb-international.com\n| date = August 2004\n| accessdate = 15 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"No. 2\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.boosey.com/cr/music/Dmitri-Smirnov-Triple-Concerto-No-2/46105\n| title = Smirnov, Dmitri / Triple Concerto No.2 op. 139 (2003) \n| website = [[Boosey & Hawkes]]\n| date = \n| accessdate = 22 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Boosey\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.boosey.com/pages/cr/composer/composer_main.asp?composerid=2700\n| title = Dmitri N. Smirnov / Biography\n| website = [[Boosey & Hawkes]]\n| date = 2001\n| accessdate = 15 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sikorski\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.sikorski.de/475/en/0/a/0/orchestral_music/1006557_index.html\n| title = Triple Concerto No. 1\n| website = [[Hans Sikorski|Sikorski]]\n| date = \n| language = de\n| accessdate = 22 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n<!--\n==External links==\n{{authority control}}-->\n\n[[Category:2003 compositions]]\n[[Category:Concertos for multiple instruments]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Triple Concerto No. 2''', [[Opus number|Op]]. 139, is a [[Triple concerto|concerto for three instruments]], [[violin]],  [[harp]] and [[double bass]], and orchestra by [[Dmitri Smirnov (composer)|Dmitri Smirnov]], composed in 2003.\n\n== History ==\nSmirnov composed several [[concerto]]s for single instruments, and two triple concertos for three instruments, the Triple Concerto No. 1 for [[saxophone]], [[piano]], [[double bass]], [[String instrument|strings]] and [[percussion]] in 1977<ref name=\"Sikorski\" /> when he lived in Russia,<ref name=\"Boosey\" /> and the Triple Concerto No. 2 for [[violin]], [[harp]], double bass and orchestra in 2003,<ref name=\"No. 2\" /> when he was a resident of England.<ref name=\"Boosey\" /> It was published by [[Boosey & Hawkes]].<ref name=\"No. 2\" />\n\nThe world premiere of the Triple Concerto No. 2 was performed at the [[Barbican Centre]] in London on 26 May 2004. In the concert marking the centenary of [[London Symphony Orchestra & Chorus]] (LSO), it was called LSO Centenary Concertante, and was combined with Mahler's [[Symphony No. 2 (Mahler)|Second Symphony]] \"Resurrection\", with [[Andrew Davis (conductor)|Andrew Davis]] conducting the [[London Symphony Orchestra & Chorus]].<ref name=\"No. 2\" /><ref name=\"Russell\" /> The soloists were violinist [[Gordan Nikolitch]], harpist Bryn Lewis, and double bassist [[Rinat Ibragimov (musician)|Rinat Ibragimov]],<ref name=\"No. 2\" /> all principal players of the LSO.<ref name=\"Russell\" />\n\n== Scoring ==\nThe Triple Concerto is structured in three sections or [[Movement (music)|movements]]:<ref name=\"Russell\" />\n# Con moto\n# Lento\n# Presto\n\nSmirnov scored the work for the three solo instruments, and an orchestra consisting of [[piccolo]], [[cor anglais]], [[bass clarinet]], [[percussion]] (3-4 players of [[timpani]], [[Triangle (musical instrument)|triangle]], [[suspended cymbal]], [[maraca]]s, [[Woodblock (instrument)|woodblock]], [[bongo]]s, [[tom-tom]], [[gong]]s, [[tam-tam]], [[side drum]], [[base drum]], [[glockenspiel]], [[xylophone]], [[bell]]s), and strings.<ref name=\"No. 2\" /> The concerto takes about 25 minutes to perform.<ref name=\"Russell\" />\n\nThe first movement has been described be a reviewer as \"music meant to wound\", the second movement as \"unsettling and angst-ridden\", and the third movement compared a [[Alfred Hitchcock|Hitchcock]] film track.<ref name=\"Russell\" /> The three solo instruments complement each other, compared to voice types soprano of the violin, mezzo-soprano of the harp, and basso profundo of the double bass. They are at times combined sounding like one voice, at times \"also play in radical styles with distinctly foreign sounding voices\".<ref name=\"Russell\" /> Episodes follow eache other in collage fashion, in intentionally heterogen styles and sounds.<ref name=\"Russell\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Russell\">{{cite web\n| last = Russell\n| first = Alex\n| url = http://www.musicweb-international.com/SandH/2004/May-Aug04/smirnov_mahler265.htm\n| title = Dmitri Smirnov & Gustav Mahler; Gordan Nikolitch (violin), Rinat Ibragimov (double-bass), Bryn Lewis (harp); Laura Claycomb (sop), Michelle DeYoung (mez-sop); London Symphony Orchestra & Chorus; Sir Andrew Davis (conductor); Barbican Centre, 26th May, 2004\n| website = musicweb-international.com\n| date = August 2004\n| accessdate = 15 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"No. 2\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.boosey.com/cr/music/Dmitri-Smirnov-Triple-Concerto-No-2/46105\n| title = Smirnov, Dmitri / Triple Concerto No.2 op. 139 (2003) \n| website = [[Boosey & Hawkes]]\n| date = \n| accessdate = 22 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Boosey\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.boosey.com/pages/cr/composer/composer_main.asp?composerid=2700\n| title = Dmitri N. Smirnov / Biography\n| website = [[Boosey & Hawkes]]\n| date = 2001\n| accessdate = 15 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sikorski\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.sikorski.de/475/en/0/a/0/orchestral_music/1006557_index.html\n| title = Triple Concerto No. 1\n| website = [[Hans Sikorski|Sikorski]]\n| date = \n| language = de\n| accessdate = 22 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n<!--\n==External links==\n{{authority control}}-->\n\n[[Category:2004 compositions]]\n[[Category:Concertos for multiple instruments]]\n", "name_user": "Gerda Arendt", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triple_Concerto_No._2"}
{"title_page": "Luis \u00c1valos", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Luis \u00c1valos\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| birthname = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1946|9|02}}\n| birth_place = [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2014|1|22|1946|9|02}}\n| death_place = [[Burbank, California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| spouse     = \n| occupation = Actor\n|education = [[New York University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n}}\n\n'''Luis \u00c1valos''' (September 2, 1946 \u2013 January 22, 2014) was a [[Cuba]]n [[character actor]]. He made numerous film and television appearances, most notably in the 1971\u20131977 children's television show ''[[The Electric Company]]''. \n\n==Early years==\nAfter being born in Havana, Cuba, \u00c1valos came to the United States with his family when he was a child. He earned a degree in theater from [[New York University]].<ref name=\"opa\">{{cite book|last1=Lentz|first1=Harris M. III|title=Obituaries in the Performing Arts, 2014|date=2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9780786476664|pages=16-17|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=11diCQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=intitle:Obituaries+intitle:in+intitle:the+intitle:Performing+intitle:Arts&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiYvf_0qf_TAhWK54MKHVtEDzEQ6AEILDAB#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\u00c1valos acted with the [[Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts|Lincoln Center]] Repertory Theater.<ref name=opa/> His [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] credits include ''Narrow Road to the Deep North'' (1972), ''The Good Woman of Setzuan'' (1970), ''Beggar on Horseback'' (1970), and ''Camino Real'' (1970).<ref>{{cite web|title=Roles (8)|url=http://www.playbill.com/person/luis-avalos-vault-0000092064|website=Playbill Vault|publisher=Playbill|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe joined ''The Electric Company'' in season two, most notably playing Doctor Doolots (a play on ''[[Doctor Doolittle]]''). He was in seasons two through six of this show. He was good friends with fellow ''[[Electric Company]]'' star [[Rita Moreno]]. His most notable movie role was as Ramon in the 1979 comedy ''[[Hot Stuff (1979 film)|Hot Stuff]]'', in which he starred alongside [[Jerry Reed]], [[Dom Deluise]], and [[Suzanne Pleshette]].\n\n\u00c1valos also starred as Jesse Rodriguez on the short-lived situation comedy ''[[Condo (TV series)|Condo]]'' with [[McLean Stevenson]],<ref name=\"etvs\">{{cite book|last1=Terrace|first1=Vincent|title=Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010|date=2011|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers|location=Jefferson, N.C.|isbn=978-0-7864-6477-7|page=206|edition=2nd}}</ref> and as Dr. Tomas Esquivel on the short-lived situation comedy ''[[E/R]]'' with [[Elliott Gould]] and [[Mary McDonnell]].{{r|etvs|page1=310}} He played Dr. Sanchez on ''[[Highcliffe Manor]]'' on NBC in 1979{{r|etvs|page1=460}} and Crecencio Salos in ''[[Ned Blessing: The True Story of My Life]]'' on CBS in 1993.{{r|etvs|page1=747}} Additionally, he starred as Stavi in the comedy ''[[The Ringer (2005 film)|The Ringer]]'' with [[Johnny Knoxville]].\n\nAvalos appeared on the ''[[Barney Miller]]'' show.  He was in the episode \"Chase\" in 1977 and also the episode \"Bones\" in 1982.\n\nIn 2000, he founded the Americas Theatre Arts Foundation in Los Angeles to support Latin American-inspired dramatic productions.<ref name=\"v\">{{cite web|last1=Seikaly|first1=Andrea|title=\u2018The Electric Company\u2019 Actor Luis Avalos Dies at 67|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/obituaries-people-news/the-electric-company-actor-luis-avalos-dies-at-67-1201069807/|website=Variety|accessdate=20 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520235053/http://variety.com/2014/tv/obituaries-people-news/the-electric-company-actor-luis-avalos-dies-at-67-1201069807/|archivedate=20 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nAvalos died on January 22, 2014, of heart failure, after a [[heart attack]]. He was buried at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]] in [[Los Angeles]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/28/arts/television/luis-avalos-actor-on-the-electric-company-dies-at-67.html|title=Luis \u00c1valos, Actor on \u2018The Electric Company,\u2019 Dies at 67|date=28 January 2014|work=The New York Times|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> at Burbank.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/obituaries/la-me-passings-20140128,0,7327295.story#axzz2rZKcfkAt|title=Obituary: Luis Avalos - LA Times|author=Los Angeles Times|date=27 January 2014|work=latimes.com|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latintimes.com/luis-avalos-dies-electric-company-cuban-actor-dead-67-146777|title=Luis \u00c1valos Dies: \u2018The Electric Company\u2019 Cuban Actor Dead At 67|author=Armando Tinoco|work=Latin Times|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | Film\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1973|| ''[[Badge 373]]'' || Chico ||\n|-\n|1979|| ''[[Hot Stuff (1979 film)|Hot Stuff]]'' || Ramon ||\n|-\n|1980|| ''[[The Hunter (1980 film)|The Hunter]]'' || Poker Player #3 ||\n|-\n|1980|| ''[[Sunday Lovers]]'' || || (segment \"Skippy\")\n|-\n|1980|| ''[[Stir Crazy (film)|Stir Crazy]]'' || Chico ||\n|-\n|1982|| ''[[Love Child (1982 film)|Love Child]]'' || Tony ||\n|-\n|1986|| ''[[Ghost Fever]]'' || Benny ||\n|-\n|1989|| ''Criminal Act'' || Coroner ||\n|-\n|1991|| ''[[Fires Within]]'' || Victor Hernandez ||\n|-\n|1991|| ''[[The Butcher's Wife]]'' || Luis ||\n|-\n|1995|| ''Lone Justice 2'' || rowspan=\"2\"|Crecencio ||\n|-\n|1996|| ''Lone Justice: Showdown at Plum Creek'' ||\n|-\n|1997|| ''[[Jungle 2 Jungle]]'' || Abe ||\n|-\n|1999|| ''[[Love Stinks (film)|Love Stinks]]'' || Judge ||\n|-\n|2002|| ''[[Wishcraft]]'' || Mayor Phelan ||\n|-\n|2003|| ''[[Hollywood Homicide]]'' || Det. Willie Palmero ||\n|-\n|2005|| ''[[The Ringer (2005 film)|The Ringer]]'' || Stavi ||\n|-\n|2008|| ''[[Five Dollars a Day]]'' || Martinez || (final film role)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0042757}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=7176|name=Luis \u00c1valos}}\n* {{findagrave|123993943}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Avalos, Luis}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American sketch comedians]]\n[[Category:Cuban male film actors]]\n[[Category:Cuban male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from Havana]]\n[[Category:20th-century Cuban male actors]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n\n{{Cuba-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Luis \u00c1valos\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| birthname = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1946|9|02}}\n| birth_place = [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2014|1|22|1946|9|02}}\n| death_place = [[Burbank, California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| spouse     = \n| occupation = Actor\n|education = [[New York University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n}}\n\n'''Luis \u00c1valos''' (September 2, 1946 \u2013 January 22, 2014) was a [[Cuba]]n [[character actor]]. He made numerous film and television appearances, most notably in the 1971\u20131977 children's television show ''[[The Electric Company]]''. \n\n==Early years==\nAfter being born in Havana, Cuba, \u00c1valos came to the United States with his family when he was a child. He earned a degree in theater from [[New York University]].<ref name=\"opa\">{{cite book|last1=Lentz|first1=Harris M. III|title=Obituaries in the Performing Arts, 2014|date=2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9780786476664|pages=16-17|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=11diCQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=intitle:Obituaries+intitle:in+intitle:the+intitle:Performing+intitle:Arts&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiYvf_0qf_TAhWK54MKHVtEDzEQ6AEILDAB#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\u00c1valos acted with the [[Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts|Lincoln Center]] Repertory Theater.<ref name=opa/> His [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] credits include ''Narrow Road to the Deep North'' (1972), ''The Good Woman of Setzuan'' (1970), ''Beggar on Horseback'' (1970), and ''Camino Real'' (1970).<ref>{{cite web|title=Roles (8)|url=http://www.playbill.com/person/luis-avalos-vault-0000092064|website=Playbill Vault|publisher=Playbill|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe joined ''The Electric Company'' in season two, most notably playing Doctor Doolots (a play on ''[[Doctor Doolittle]]''). He was in seasons two through six of this show. He was good friends with fellow ''[[Electric Company]]'' star [[Rita Moreno]]. His most notable movie role was as Ramon in the 1979 comedy ''[[Hot Stuff (1979 film)|Hot Stuff]]'', in which he starred alongside [[Jerry Reed]], [[Dom Deluise]], and [[Suzanne Pleshette]].\n\n\u00c1valos also starred as Jesse Rodriguez on the short-lived situation comedy ''[[Condo (TV series)|Condo]]'' with [[McLean Stevenson]],<ref name=\"etvs\">{{cite book|last1=Terrace|first1=Vincent|title=Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010|date=2011|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers|location=Jefferson, N.C.|isbn=978-0-7864-6477-7|page=206|edition=2nd}}</ref> and as Dr. Tomas Esquivel on the short-lived situation comedy ''[[E/R]]'' with [[Elliott Gould]] and [[Mary McDonnell]].{{r|etvs|page1=310}} He played Dr. Sanchez on ''[[Highcliffe Manor]]'' on NBC in 1979{{r|etvs|page1=460}} and Crecencio Salos in ''[[Ned Blessing: The True Story of My Life]]'' on CBS in 1993.{{r|etvs|page1=747}} Additionally, he starred as Stavi in the comedy ''[[The Ringer (2005 film)|The Ringer]]'' with [[Johnny Knoxville]].\n\nAvalos appeared on the ''[[Barney Miller]]'' show.  He was in the episode \"Chase\" in 1977 and also the episode \"Bones\" in 1982.\n\nIn 2000, he founded the Americas Theatre Arts Foundation in Los Angeles to support Latin American-inspired dramatic productions.<ref name=\"v\">{{cite web|last1=Seikaly|first1=Andrea|title=\u2018The Electric Company\u2019 Actor Luis Avalos Dies at 67|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/obituaries-people-news/the-electric-company-actor-luis-avalos-dies-at-67-1201069807/|website=Variety|accessdate=20 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520235053/http://variety.com/2014/tv/obituaries-people-news/the-electric-company-actor-luis-avalos-dies-at-67-1201069807/|archivedate=20 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nAvalos died on January 22, 2014, of heart failure, after a [[heart attack]]. He was buried at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]] in [[Los Angeles]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/28/arts/television/luis-avalos-actor-on-the-electric-company-dies-at-67.html|title=Luis \u00c1valos, Actor on \u2018The Electric Company,\u2019 Dies at 67|date=28 January 2014|work=The New York Times|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> at Burbank.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/obituaries/la-me-passings-20140128,0,7327295.story#axzz2rZKcfkAt|title=Obituary: Luis Avalos - LA Times|author=Los Angeles Times|date=27 January 2014|work=latimes.com|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latintimes.com/luis-avalos-dies-electric-company-cuban-actor-dead-67-146777|title=Luis \u00c1valos Dies: \u2018The Electric Company\u2019 Cuban Actor Dead At 67|author=Armando Tinoco|work=Latin Times|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | Film\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Note