rs football|Murray State]]\n| \n| ''Sep. 26'' \u2013 [[South Alabama Jaguars football|South Alabama]]\n| ''Sep. 25'' \u2013 [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State]]\n| \n|-\n| ''Nov. 27'' \u2013 [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| ''Nov. 26'' \u2013 at [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| ''Nov. 25'' \u2013 [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| ''Nov. 30'' \u2013 at [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| ''Nov. 29'' \u2013 [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| ''Nov. 28'' \u2013 at [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| ''Nov. 27'' \u2013 [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| ''Nov. 25'' \u2013 at [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Kentucky Wildcats football navbox}}\n{{University of Kentucky}}\n{{Southeastern Conference football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kentucky Wildcats Football}}\n[[Category:Kentucky Wildcats football|*]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1891]]\n[[Category:1891 establishments in Kentucky]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Football team of the University of Kentucky}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| TeamName = Kentucky Wildcats football\n| CurrentSeason = 2020 Kentucky Wildcats football team\n| Image = Kentucky Wildcats logo.svg\n| ImageSize = 150\n| FirstYear = 1881\n| AthleticDirector = [[Mitch Barnhart]]\n| HeadCoach = [[Mark Stoops]]\n| HeadCoachYear = 7th\n| HCWins = 44 <!-- As of games through 11/30/19 -->\n| HCLosses = 44 <!-- As of games through 11/30/19 -->\n| Stadium = [[Kroger Field]]\n| Location = [[Lexington, Kentucky]]\n| StadCapacity = 61,000\n| StadSurface = Field Turf \n| Conference= [[Southeastern Conference]]\n| ConfDivision = Eastern\n| PastAffiliations =\n| AllAmericans = {{American college football All-Americans|Kentucky|ref=Y}}\n| uniform =\n| WebsiteName = ukathletics.com\n| WebsiteURL = https://ukathletics.com/index.aspx?path=football\n| ATWins = 623\n| ATLosses = 626\n| ATTies = 44\n| BowlWins = 10\n| BowlLosses = 9\n| BowlTies = \n| NatlTitles = 1 (1950)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/ukathletics.com/documents/2017/8/24/1718_FB_MediaGuide_WEB.pdf |title=2017 Kentucky Football Media Guide |publisher=University of Kentucky |accessdate=February 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306175117/https://s3.amazonaws.com/ukathletics.com/documents/2017/8/24/1718_FB_MediaGuide_WEB.pdf |archive-date=March 6, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| ConfTitles = 2\n| Heismans =\n| FightSong = [[On, On, U of K]], [[Kentucky Fight]]\n| MascotDisplay = [[Wildcat]], [[Scratch (mascot)|Scratch]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/kty-m-footbl-archive.html |title=Kentucky Wildcats Official Athletic Site \u2013 Football |publisher=Ukathletics.com |accessdate=May 21, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEnkDVhh?url=http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/kty-m-footbl-archive.html |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> \n| MarchingBand = [[Wildcat Marching Band]]\n| PagFreeLabel = Outfitter\n| PagFreeValue = [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n| Rivalries = [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]] ([[Governor's Cup (Kentucky)|rivalry]])<br />[[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] ([[Kentucky\u2013Tennessee football rivalry|rivalry]])<br />[[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana]] ([[The Bourbon Barrel|rivalry]])<br />[[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]] ([[Kentucky\u2013Vanderbilt football rivalry|rivalry]])\n}}\n\nThe '''Kentucky Wildcats football''' program represents the [[University of Kentucky]] in the sport of [[American football]]. The Wildcats compete in the [[Football Bowl Subdivision]] (FBS) of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) and the Eastern Division of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC). The Wildcats play their home games at [[Kroger Field]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky]] and are currently led by head coach [[Mark Stoops]].\n\n==History==\n{{See also|List of Kentucky Wildcats football seasons}}\n\n===Early history (1881\u20131945)===\n[[File:A. M. Miller 1917.jpg|150px|thumb|A. M. Miller, Kentucky's first head football coach]]\nUntil about 1913, the modern University of Kentucky was referred to as \"Kentucky State College\" and nearby [[Transylvania University]] was known as \"Kentucky University\". In 1880, Kentucky University and [[Centre College]] played the first intercollegiate football game in [[Kentucky]]. Kentucky State first fielded a football team in [[1881 Kentucky State College football team|1881]], playing three games against [[Battle on Broadway|rival]] [[1881 Kentucky University football team|Kentucky University]].  The team was revived in 1891. Both the inaugural 1881 squad and the revived 1891 squad have unknown coaches according to university records in winning two games and losing three.<ref name=k177>''Kentucky Football Media Guide'', p. 177</ref> The 1891 team's colors were blue and light yellow, decided before the [[Centre College\u2013Kentucky rivalry|Centre\u2013Kentucky]] game on December 19. A student asked \"What color blue?\" and varsity letterman [[Richard C. Stoll]] pulled off his necktie, and held it up. This is still held as the origin of Kentucky's shade of blue.  The next year light yellow was dropped and changed to white.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uky.edu/base/webuk/subpages/traditions.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-09-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824191752/http://www.uky.edu/base/webuk/subpages/traditions.html |archivedate=August 24, 2015 }}</ref> The 1892 team was coached by [[A. M. Miller]], and went 2\u20134\u20131.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/kty-m-footbl-archive.html |title=Kentucky Wildcats Official Athletic Site \u2013 Football |work=ukathletics.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BEnkDVhh?url=http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/kty-m-footbl-archive.html |archivedate=October 7, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nThe greatest UK team of this era was the [[1898 Kentucky State College football team|1898]] squad, known simply to Kentuckians as \"The Immortals.\"<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/> To this day, the Immortals remain the only undefeated, untied, and unscored upon team in UK football history.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/> The Immortals were coached by [[W. R. Bass]] and ended the year a perfect 7\u20130\u20130, despite an average weight of 147 pounds per player.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/> Victories came easily for this squad, as the Immortals raced by Kentucky University (18- 0), Georgetown (28\u20130), Company H of the 8th Massachusetts (59\u20130), Louisville Athletic Club (16\u20130), Centre (6\u20130), 160th Indiana (17\u20130) and Newcastle Athletic Club (36\u20130).<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/>\n\nHead coach [[Jack Wright (American football)|Jack Wright]] led the team to a 7\u20131 record in [[1903 Kentucky State College football team|1903]], losing only to rival and southern champion [[1903 Kentucky University Pioneers football team|Kentucky University]].<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/>\n\n[[Fred Schacht]] posted a 15\u20134\u20131 record in two seasons but died unexpectedly after his second season.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/> [[J. White Guyn]] also had success leading the Wildcats, posting a 17\u20137\u20131 record in his three years.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/>\n\n[[Edwin Sweetland]] went 16\u20133 in three seasons ([[1909 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1909]]\u20131910 and [[1912 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1912]]) but resigned due to poor health.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/> Sweetland also served as Kentucky's first athletics director.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/> The 1909 team upset the [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois Fighting Illini]]. Upon their welcome home, Philip Carbusier said that they had \"fought like wildcats,\" a nickname that stuck.<ref>Michael Leo Donovan, ''Yankees to Fighting Irish : What's Behind Your Favorite Team's Name'' (Taylor Trade Publications, 2004), p107</ref>\n\n[[File:Doc_rodes.jpg|thumb|140px|Doc Rodes.]]\n\n[[John J. Tigert]] coached Kentucky for two seasons ([[1915 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1915]]\u2013[[1916 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1916]]) with each season having one loss. 1915 captain [[Charles C. Schrader]] was [[College Football All-Southern Team|All-Southern]]. The 1916 team fought the [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] (SIAA) co-champion [[1916 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee Volunteers]] to a scoreless tie. The year's only a loss, 45\u20130 to the [[Irby Curry]]-led [[1916 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|Vanderbilt Commodores]], was the dedication of [[Stoll Field]].  Quarterbacks Curry and Kentucky's [[Doc Rodes]] were both selected All-Southern at year's end. Vanderbilt coach [[Dan McGugin]] stated \"If you would give me Doc Rodes, I would say he was a greater player than Curry.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigbluehistory.net/bb/statistics/playermilitary.html|title=Kentucky Players who served in the Military|access-date=September 17, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923194648/http://www.bigbluehistory.net/bb/statistics/playermilitary.html|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCoach [[Harry Gamage]] had a 32\u201325\u20135 record during his seven seasons from 1927 to 1933.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/> [[A.D. Kirwan]], who would go on to be the president of the university, coached the Wildcats from 1938 to 1944 and posted a 24\u201328\u20134 record in those six seasons.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/>\n\nLongtime athletics director [[Bernie Shively]] also served as Kentucky's head football coach for the 1945 season.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com\"/>\n\n===Paul \"Bear\" Bryant era (1946\u20131953)===\nCoach [[Bear Bryant|Paul \"Bear\" Bryant]] was Kentucky's head football coach for eight seasons.<ref name=\"sports-reference.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/bear-bryant-1.html |title=Bear Bryant |work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140706234430/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/bear-bryant-1.html |archivedate=July 6, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Bear Bryant]] came to Kentucky from [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2013/09/100_facts_about_bear_bryant_yo.html|title=100 years of Bear Bryant; 100 facts you may not know|work=AL.com|accessdate=May 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721174007/http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2013/09/100_facts_about_bear_bryant_yo.html|archive-date=July 21, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Under Bryant's tutelage, the Wildcats won the 1947 [[Great Lakes Bowl]], lost the 1950 [[Orange Bowl (game)|Orange Bowl]], won the 1951 [[Sugar Bowl]] and the 1952 [[Cotton Bowl Classic]].<ref name=\"sports-reference.com\"/> In final AP polls, the Wildcats were ranked No. 11 in 1949, No. 7 in 1950, No. 15 in 1951, No. 20 in 1952 and No. 16 in 1953.<ref name=\"sports-reference.com\"/> The final 1950 poll was taken prior to the bowl games; Kentucky then defeated undefeated and No. 1 ranked Oklahoma in the Sugar Bowl and finished with the number 1 ranking in 3 major polls,<ref name=\"sports-reference.com\"/> ending the Sooners 31-game winning streak. Bryant won SEC Coach of the Year honors in 1950 and then left after eight seasons to accept the head football coach position at [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]].\n\nAssistant coaches at Kentucky under Bryant who went on to become head coaches include [[Paul Dietzel]], [[Frank Moseley]], [[Jim Owens]] and [[Phil Cutchin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coachingroots.com/football/coaches/bear-bryant/coaching-tree |title=Coaching Tree : Bear Bryant|accessdate=February 19, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202221411/http://coachingroots.com/football/coaches/bear-bryant/coaching-tree |archivedate=February 2, 2014 }}</ref> Notable players who played for Bryant at Kentucky include [[Howard Schnellenberger]], [[Jim Mackenzie (American football)|Jim Mackenzie]], [[Jerry Claiborne]], [[Steve Meilinger]], [[George Blanda]], [[Vito Parilli]], and [[Bob Gain]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Rickerd |first=Brian |url=http://www.state-journal.com/sports/2013/10/14/university-of-kentucky-football-great-meilinger-has-only-one-regret-about-hall-of-fame |title=University of Kentucky football great Meilinger has only one regret about Hall of Fame \u2013 Frankfort & Franklin County, Kentucky |publisher=State-journal.com |date=October 14, 2013 |accessdate=May 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722055237/http://www.state-journal.com/sports/2013/10/14/university-of-kentucky-football-great-meilinger-has-only-one-regret-about-hall-of-fame |archive-date=July 22, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Blanton Collier era (1954\u20131961)===\n[[Cleveland Browns]] assistant [[Blanton Collier]] was hired to replace Bryant as head football coach at Kentucky in late 1953.<ref name=\"aseaofblue.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aseaofblue.com/2013/6/17/4426374/kentucky-football-the-blanton-collier-years-part-two-1954-1961|title=Kentucky Football:  The Blanton Collier Years (Part Two) 1954 -1961|author=Hank Rippetoe|work=A Sea of Blue|access-date=February 1, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203153040/http://www.aseaofblue.com/2013/6/17/4426374/kentucky-football-the-blanton-collier-years-part-two-1954-1961|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> After completing his first season at Kentucky, Collier was named SEC Coach of the Year after posting a 7\u20132 record.<ref name=\"aseaofblue.com\"/> Collier's assistants during his tenure at Kentucky included the likes of [[Bill Arnsparger]], [[Chuck Knox]], [[Howard Schnellenberger]], and [[Don Shula]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musclesofiron.com/articles/blanton-collier/|title=Muscles of Iron|work=Musclesofiron.com|accessdate=May 21, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140218211325/http://www.musclesofiron.com/articles/blanton-collier/|archivedate=February 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDespite having a winning record, 41\u201336\u20133 in eight seasons, Collier was fired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentucky.com/2012/10/06/2362609/mark-story-blanton-colliers-daughter.html|title=Lexington, KY local and state news by the Lexington Herald-Leader - Kentucky.com|work=Kentucky.com|accessdate=May 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140218230350/http://www.kentucky.com/2012/10/06/2362609/mark-story-blanton-colliers-daughter.html|archive-date=February 18, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Collier struggled to recruit for much of his tenure, about which frustrated fans wrote letters of complaint to the university.<ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1135637/index.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203003548/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1135637/index.htm |date=December 3, 2013 }}</ref> Collier is the last Kentucky head football coach to leave the Wildcats with a winning record.\n\n===Charlie Bradshaw era (1962\u20131968)===\n[[Charlie Bradshaw (American football coach)|Charlie Bradshaw]], an [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] assistant under [[Bear Bryant]], was hired to replace the fired Collier.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aseaofblue.com/2013/8/14/4570622/kentucky-football-tales-from-the-dark-side-charlie-bradshaw-part-three|title=Kentucky Football Tales from the Dark Side: Charlie Bradshaw Part Three|author=Hank Rippetoe|work=Aseaofblue.com|accessdate=May 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721175911/http://www.aseaofblue.com/2013/8/14/4570622/kentucky-football-tales-from-the-dark-side-charlie-bradshaw-part-three|archive-date=July 21, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite all the hype about being a Bear Bryant assistant, Bradshaw's tenure turned out to be a disappointment, as he was unable to have much success with the Wildcats. He had a 25\u201341\u20135 record in seven seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fanbase.com/1-Charlie-Bradshaw|title=Charlie Bradshaw|work=Fanbase.com|accessdate=May 21, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160118090634/http://www.fanbase.com/1-charlie-bradshaw/|archivedate=January 18, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bradshaw is the last Kentucky coach to defeat [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] twice in Knoxville, and the last Kentucky coach to defeat [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] twice.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> He was also the last to defeat a No. 1 ranked team in the country until [[Rich Brooks]] in 2007.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n \nBradshaw, a harsh, brutal coach,<ref name=\"cappaa.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cappaa.com/the-thin-thirty|title=THE THIN THIRTY|work=cappaa.com|access-date=February 1, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203223136/http://www.cappaa.com/the-thin-thirty|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> was the head coach of the infamous [[Thin Thirty]] Kentucky team. Kentucky had 88 players when Bradshaw arrived, but by season's end, only 30 players were on the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aseaofblue.com/2013/7/29/4525020/kentucky-football-history-tales-from-the-dark-side-the-charlie|title=Kentucky Football History:  Tales from the Dark Side \u2013 The Charlie Bradshaw Years Part Two|author=Hank Rippetoe|work=Aseaofblue.com|accessdate=May 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721175924/http://www.aseaofblue.com/2013/7/29/4525020/kentucky-football-history-tales-from-the-dark-side-the-charlie|archive-date=July 21, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The story of that team is told in the 2007 book ''The Thin Thirty'' by Shannon Ragland.<ref name=\"cappaa.com\"/> Bradshaw also recruited [[Nate Northington]], the first African American to play in an SEC athletic contest (1967).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nkaa.uky.edu/record.php?note_id=570|title=Notable Kentucky African Americans \u2013 Northington, Nathaniel \"Nate\"|author=University of Kentucky Libraries|work=Nkaa.uky.edu|accessdate=May 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150509125622/http://nkaa.uky.edu/record.php?note_id=570|archive-date=May 9, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===John Ray era (1969\u20131972)===\n[[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]] assistant [[John Ray (American football)|John Ray]] took over as head football coach in late 1969. Ray's teams consistently had solid defenses, but struggled to produce on the offensive end.<ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1082851/2/index.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203150128/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1082851/2/index.htm |date=February 3, 2014 }}</ref> Ray's teams failed to win more than three games in a single season, going a dismal 10\u201333 overall in Ray's four seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/john-ray-2.html |title=John Ray |work=Sports-Reference.com |accessdate=May 21, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722173038/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/john-ray-2.html |archivedate=July 22, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Ray's contract was not renewed after the 1972 season.\n\n===Fran Curci era (1973\u20131981)===\n[[File:University of Kentucky Football (1987.573).jpg|thumb|left|A football signed by Kentucky head coach Fran Curci and gifted to President [[Gerald Ford]].]]\n\nKentucky hired [[Fran Curci]] away from [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] after Ray was let go.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1454&dat=19811128&id=KGxOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HhQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2519,6371338|title=Star-News \u2013 Google News Archive Search|work=Google.com|accessdate=May 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117041352/https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1454&dat=19811128&id=KGxOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HhQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2519,6371338|archive-date=November 17, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The 1976 Wildcats tallied their first winning season in 13 years and won the [[Peach Bowl]],<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/fran-curci-1.html |title=Fran Curci |work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |accessdate=May 21, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722173046/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/fran-curci-1.html |archivedate=July 22, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> finishing No. 18 in the final AP poll.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> For all intents and purposes, however, Curci's tenure ended soon afterward, when the NCAA slapped the Wildcats with two years' probation for numerous recruiting and amateurism violations.  They were banned from postseason play and live television in 1977.  The most damaging sanction in the long term, however, was being limited to only 25 scholarships in 1977 and 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web1.ncaa.org/LSDBi/exec/miSearch?miSearchSubmit=publicReport&key=307&publicTerms=THIS%20PHRASE%20WILL%20NOT%20BE%20REPEATED |title=Legislative Services Database - LSDBi |website=Web1.ncaa.org |accessdate=2017-04-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117033326/https://web1.ncaa.org/LSDBi/exec/miSearch?miSearchSubmit=publicReport&key=307&publicTerms=THIS%20PHRASE%20WILL%20NOT%20BE%20REPEATED |archive-date=November 17, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe 1977 Kentucky team went 10\u20131, went undefeated in SEC play, won a share of the SEC title and finished the season ranked No. 6 in the AP poll.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> Due to the sanctions, however, the Wildcats were not able to go to a bowl. Kentucky finished at No. 6 and [[Penn State Nittany Lions football|Penn State]] at No. 5 despite the fact that Kentucky defeated Penn State at Penn State during the regular season. Curci was unable to put together another winning team as a result of the reduced scholarships, and was fired after the 1981 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1915&dat=19811125&id=dwMhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=WXUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1214,5415929|title=The Day \u2013 Google News Archive Search|work=Google.com|accessdate=May 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117043726/https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1915&dat=19811125&id=dwMhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=WXUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1214,5415929|archive-date=November 17, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Jerry Claiborne era (1982\u20131989)===\n[[File:Jerry Claiborne (1965 Bugle).png|150 px|thumb|Coach Claiborne]]\nCoach [[Jerry Claiborne]] returned to his alma mater from [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.fredericknewspost.com/archive/article_e7a7b26d-c2d0-5a1c-b41d-3c471a5ae549.html|title=History Lesson: The late Jerry Claiborne turned around Maryland's football program|work=The Frederick News-Post|accessdate=May 21, 2015}}</ref> He led the Wildcats to the [[1983 Hall of Fame Classic Bowl|1983 Hall of Fame Bowl]] and the [[1984 Hall of Fame Classic Bowl|1984 Hall of Fame Bowl]],<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/jerry-claiborne-1.html |title=Jerry Claiborne |work=Sports-Reference.com |accessdate=May 21, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418022500/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/jerry-claiborne-1.html |archivedate=April 18, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> defeating a Wisconsin team ranked No. 20 in the polls to finish the season with a 9\u20133 record and a No. 19 ranking in the final AP and UPI polls.<ref name=\"collegefootball.bz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.collegefootball.bz/kentucky |accessdate=February 19, 2016|title=Kentucky Wildcats \u2013 All Time Record 581-593-44 (0.495)\n |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206071116/http://collegefootball.bz/kentucky |archivedate=February 6, 2015 }}</ref> Claiborne also won SEC Coach of the Year honors in 1983. The [[E.J. Nutter Training Facility]] was built in 1987. Coach Claiborne and Kentucky experienced an era of constant change at the quarterback position following the 1987 season through his departure that included Ransdell, Wright, and High School All-American and two way starter (Quarterback/Safety) Ricky Lewis, prior to landing Mr. Kentucky Football Awardee Pookie Jones of Calloway County.<ref name=\"UKANutterFacility\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/athletic-dept/nutter-training-facility.html |title=E.J. Nutter Training Facility |publisher=[[University of Kentucky]] |accessdate=March 8, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107125259/http://www.ukathletics.com/athletic-dept/nutter-training-facility.html |archivedate=January 7, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Claiborne retired following the 1989 season<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1069225/index.htm |title=This Coach Did It Right|accessdate=February 19, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203145904/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1069225/index.htm |archivedate=February 3, 2014 }}</ref> and was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] as a coach in 1999. He was the last coach to defeat [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] until [[Joker Phillips]] in 2011 and the last coach to defeat [[Florida Gators football|Florida]] until [[Mark Stoops]] in 2018.<ref name=\"collegefootball.bz\"/> His final record at Kentucky is 41\u201346\u20133.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n\n===Bill Curry era (1990\u20131996)===\n[[Bill Curry]] surprised the college football world by leaving [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] for Kentucky in late 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://si.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1123088/index.htm|title=The Sports Illustrated Vault - SI.com|work=SI.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203214517/http://si.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1123088/index.htm|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/1990-01-09/sports/25908932_1_jerry-claiborne-roger-sayers-bill-curry|title=Bill Curry Hired By Kentucky|work=philly-archives|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071301/http://articles.philly.com/1990-01-09/sports/25908932_1_jerry-claiborne-roger-sayers-bill-curry|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite the high hopes that the Kentucky football program would rise under his leadership, Curry's Wildcats teams never achieved much success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollbamaroll.com/2010/5/19/1479785/more-on-bill-curry|title=More on Bill Curry...|author=outsidethesidelines|work=Roll 'Bama Roll|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202180521/http://www.rollbamaroll.com/2010/5/19/1479785/more-on-bill-curry|archive-date=February 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The Wildcats' best season under Curry was 1993, going on to play Clemson in the 1993 New Year's Eve Peach Bowl.  It would be his only winning season in seven years.  On the other side of the spectrum, his 1994 team went 1-10, the worst record in modern program history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/bill-curry-1.html |title=Bill Curry |work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201235909/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/bill-curry-1.html |archivedate=February 1, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Curry was asked to resign after seven seasons and just a .33 winning percentage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1996-11-24/sports/sp-2674_1_bill-curry|title=Curry Goes Out a Loser Against Tennessee|work=latimes|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222211047/http://articles.latimes.com/1996-11-24/sports/sp-2674_1_bill-curry|archive-date=February 22, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Curry's record at Kentucky was 26\u201352.<ref name=\"collegefootball.bz\"/>\n\n===Hal Mumme era (1997\u20132000)===\nCoach [[Hal Mumme]] came to Kentucky from [[Valdosta State Blazers football|Valdosta State]] and brought an exciting, high-scoring, pass-oriented offense known as the \"Air Raid\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/071100aaf.html|title=Hal Mumme Named Head Coach of Kentucky Football|work=ukathletics.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203001911/http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/071100aaf.html|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He led the Wildcats to the 1998 [[Outback Bowl]] and the 1999 [[Music City Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/hal-mumme-1.html |title=Hal Mumme |work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201235902/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/hal-mumme-1.html |archivedate=February 1, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Mumme achieved a 20\u201326 record in his four seasons.<ref name=\"usatoday30.usatoday.com\">{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/football/sfc/2001-02-06-mumme.htm|title=Mumme resigns as Kentucky football coach|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=November 27, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203141455/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/football/sfc/2001-02-06-mumme.htm|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Mumme coached star quarterback [[Tim Couch]], the top overall pick in the [[1999 NFL Draft]]. Mumme was popular among the Kentucky fans,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saturdaydownsouth.com/2011/kentucky-tim-couch-flashback/|title=Tim Couch Flashback: \"Dangerous As A Broken Fruit Jar\" \u2013 Saturday Down South|work=Saturday Down South|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203232050/http://www.saturdaydownsouth.com/2011/kentucky-tim-couch-flashback/|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> but the program was hit with severe sanctions for NCAA violations involving cash payments from an assistant coach to prospective recruits.<ref name=\"usatoday30.usatoday.com\"/> Although Mumme himself was not implicated in any violation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/college/news/2002/01/31/kentucky_probation_ap/|title=Kentucky gets three years probation |accessdate=February 19, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100419011044/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/college/news/2002/01/31/kentucky_probation_ap/ |archivedate=April 19, 2010 }}</ref> he resigned after the 2000 season.<ref name=\"usatoday30.usatoday.com\"/> Assistant coaches under Mumme at Kentucky included [[Mike Leach (American football coach)|Mike Leach]] and [[Sonny Dykes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smartfootball.blogspot.com/2009/04/ballad-of-hal-mumme.html|title=Smart Football|work=smartfootball.blogspot.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214172151/http://smartfootball.blogspot.com/2009/04/ballad-of-hal-mumme.html|archive-date=February 14, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Mumme is the last Kentucky coach to beat Alabama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/alabama/vs/kentucky|title=Winsipedia Alabama vs. Kentucky|access-date=September 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914132025/http://www.winsipedia.com/alabama/vs/kentucky|archive-date=September 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Guy Morriss era (2001\u20132002)===\n[[Guy Morriss]] was promoted from offensive line coach to head coach of the Wildcats after Mumme's resignation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/2001-02-07/sports/25317362_1_jeff-bowden-hal-mumme-guy-morriss|title=Kentucky Elevates Ex-eagle Morriss|work=philly-archives|access-date=January 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222355/http://articles.philly.com/2001-02-07/sports/25317362_1_jeff-bowden-hal-mumme-guy-morriss|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Under coach Morriss, the Wildcats went 2\u20139 in 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.totalfootballstats.com/Team_College.asp?id=149&Season=2001|title=2001 - Kentucky Wildcats Football Statistics and Results - Totalfootballstats.com|work=totalfootballstats.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323152028/http://totalfootballstats.com/Team_College.asp?id=149&season=2001|archive-date=March 23, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> but improved to a 7\u20135 record in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalchamps.net/NCAA/college_football_2002_schedules/kentucky.htm|title=Kentucky Wildcats 2002 Football Schedule|work=nationalchamps.net|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140619074856/http://www.nationalchamps.net/NCAA/college_football_2002_schedules/kentucky.htm|archive-date=June 19, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the Wildcats were not eligible for postseason play in 2002 due to NCAA sanctions from Mumme's tenure.<ref>[http://brainerddispatch.com/stories/020102/nsp_0201020043.shtml ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020212154850/http://brainerddispatch.com/stories/020102/nsp_0201020043.shtml |date=February 12, 2002 }}</ref> The most significant event of that season came in a loss to LSU (See: [[Bluegrass Miracle]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5200&ATCLID=162968|title=Henderson's 'Bluegrass Miracle' Stuns UK, 33\u201330|work=LSUsports.net|access-date=February 1, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203204945/http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5200&ATCLID=162968|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Morriss accepted an offer to become the head football coach at [[Baylor Bears football|Baylor]] after the 2002 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baylor.edu/mediacommunications/news.php?action=story&story=4369|title=Baylor University \u2013 Media Communications \u2013 News|work=Baylor University \u2013 Media Communications|access-date=November 25, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131129073744/http://www.baylor.edu/mediacommunications/news.php?action=story&story=4369|archive-date=November 29, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Rich Brooks era (2003\u20132009)===\nThe team's next head coach was former [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]] head coach [[Rich Brooks]], who was hired in December 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20021230/NEWS/212300001#gsc.tab=0|title=Brooks hired to coach Kentucky|work=TuscaloosaNews.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222020358/http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20021230/NEWS/212300001#gsc.tab=0|archive-date=February 22, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He led the team out of the probationary years to an 8\u20135 regular season record in [[2006 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2006]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalchamps.net/NCAA/college_football_2006_schedules/kentucky.htm|title=Kentucky Wildcats 2006 Football Schedule|work=nationalchamps.net|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130507052423/http://www.nationalchamps.net/NCAA/college_football_2006_schedules/kentucky.htm|archive-date=May 7, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> including a memorable upset over the defending SEC champion Georgia, snapping a nine-game losing streak to the Bulldogs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/colleges/georgia/football/story/_/id/7247538/georgia-bulldogs-last-five-matchups-vs-kentucky-wildcats|title=Georgia Bulldogs' last five matchups vs. Kentucky Wildcats|work=ESPN.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203040602/http://espn.go.com/colleges/georgia/football/story/_/id/7247538/georgia-bulldogs-last-five-matchups-vs-kentucky-wildcats|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Brooks also led the football team to its first bowl game since 1999 and its first bowl game victory since 1984, as Kentucky defeated the [[Clemson Tigers|Clemson University Tigers]] 28\u201320 in the Music City Bowl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dicksonherald.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20061229/SPORTS06/61229025|title=The Tennessean-Dickson|work=The Tennessean|access-date=June 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018050641/http://dicksonherald.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20061229%2FSPORTS06%2F61229025|archive-date=October 18, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[2007 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2007]], the Wildcats were ranked 8th in the nation before a loss to [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] on October 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/preview?gameId=272772579|title=Kentucky Wildcats vs South Carolina Gamecocks \u2013 Preview|work=ESPN.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203040712/http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/preview?gameId=272772579|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> After the loss to South Carolina, Kentucky bounced back on October 13 to defeat No. 1 [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] in a historic triple overtime game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=272860096|title=LSU Tigers vs Kentucky Wildcats \u2013 Recap|work=ESPN.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203040825/http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=272860096|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBrooks took Kentucky to four consecutive bowl games, winning the first three.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/010410aab.html|title=Brooks Retires at Kentucky|work=ukathletics.com|access-date=January 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107045343/http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/010410aab.html|archive-date=January 7, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The 2007 Kentucky Wildcats football defeated the [[Florida State Seminoles]] 35\u201328 in the 2007 [[Music City Bowl]] in Nashville, Tennessee, on December 31, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=273650052|title=Kentucky Wildcats vs Florida State Seminoles \u2013 Recap|work=ESPN.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031151434/http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=273650052|archive-date=October 31, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Quarterback [[Andre' Woodson]] was named the Music City Bowl MVP for the second year in a row.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/college/football/bowls/music.htm%7Ctitle=USATODAY.com%7Cwork=usatoday.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219162316/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/college/football/bowls/music.htm%7Ctitle%3DUSATODAY.com%7Cwork%3Dusatoday.com|url-status=dead|title=Server Error in /sports|archivedate=February 19, 2016|website=usatoday30.usatoday.com}}</ref> In 2008 the Wildcats opted to go to the Liberty Bowl instead of the Music City Bowl and defeated [[Conference USA]] champion [[East Carolina Pirates football|East Carolina]] 25\u201319.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=290020151|title=Kentucky Wildcats vs East Carolina Pirates \u2013 Recap|work=ESPN.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107043402/http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=290020151|archive-date=November 7, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2009, Brooks and Kentucky returned to the Music City Bowl, losing in a rematch to Clemson 21\u201313.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/12/27/music-city-bowl-clemson-b_n_404551.html|title=Music City Bowl: Clemson Beats Kentucky, 21\u201313|work=The Huffington Post|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203092051/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/12/27/music-city-bowl-clemson-b_n_404551.html|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Brooks retired after seven seasons with a 39\u201347 overall record.<ref name=\"ukathletics.com1\"/>\n\n===Joker Phillips era (2010\u20132012)===\nFormer Wildcat [[wide receiver]] and longtime assistant coach [[Joker Phillips]] was formally named head coach January 6, 2010 after Brooks' retirement; he had been Brooks' designated successor since 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wkyt.com/home/headlines/80804502.html|title=Phillips introduced as UK football coach|work=wkyt.com|access-date=January 6, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928120145/http://www.wkyt.com/home/headlines/80804502.html|archive-date=September 28, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Kentucky started off strong under Phillips with a win on the road against archrival Louisville.<ref name=\"fbschedules.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fbschedules.com/ncaa-10/sec/2010-kentucky-wildcats-football-schedule.php|title=2010 Kentucky Wildcats Football Schedule|work=FBSchedules.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204031156/http://www.fbschedules.com/ncaa-10/sec/2010-kentucky-wildcats-football-schedule.php|archive-date=February 4, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The 2010 squad snapped a long-standing losing streak to South Carolina Coach [[Steve Spurrier]] by defeating the Gamecocks at [[Kroger Field]].<ref name=\"fbschedules.com\"/> However, they dropped games to both Ole Miss and Mississippi State, lost to a Florida team on a down year and once again failed to beat its other archrival Tennessee, having lost 26 in a row to the Vols,<ref name=\"fbschedules.com\"/> the longest losing streak by one team to another in college football. The Wildcats capped the season with a 27\u201310 loss to [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh]] in the [[BBVA Compass Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=310080096|title=Pittsburgh Panthers vs Kentucky Wildcats \u2013 Recap|work=ESPN.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023162959/http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=310080096|archive-date=October 23, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2011, Kentucky snapped the longest active FBS losing streak to any one team by defeating the Tennessee Vols 10\u20137 at Kroger Field.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/college-football/|title=NCAAF College Football News, Photos, Stats, Scores, Schedule & Videos|website=sports.yahoo.com}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2012, the day after a 40-0 home shutout by Vanderbilt resulting with a 1\u20139 record, UK athletics director [[Mitch Barnhart]] released a public letter to [[Big Blue Nation]] announcing that Phillips would not return for the 2013 season, but that he would finish out the 2012 season as head coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/04/joker-phillips-fired-kentucky-football_n_2073427.html|title=Joker Phillips Fired: Kentucky Fires Football Coach|work=The Huffington Post|access-date=January 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107000719/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/04/joker-phillips-fired-kentucky-football_n_2073427.html|archive-date=January 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> With Joker's 5-year contract only being 3 years complete at the end of the season, the university has to pay $2.55 Million over the final 2 years of the contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationofblue.com/firing-joker-phillips-wasnt-cheap/|title=Firing Joker Phillips Wasn't Cheap|author=+Scott Anderson|work=Nation of Blue|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202182442/http://www.nationofblue.com/firing-joker-phillips-wasnt-cheap/|archive-date=February 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Mark Stoops era (2013\u2013present)===\n{{very long section|date=December 2018}}\n[[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]] defensive coordinator [[Mark Stoops]], brother of legendary former [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]] head coach [[Bob Stoops]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seccountry.com/kentucky/mark-stoops-brother-bob-stoops-oklahoma-retires|title=Mark Stoops on brother Bob Stoops: 'Bob truly represents what is good about college football'|date=June 7, 2017|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607235205/https://www.seccountry.com/kentucky/mark-stoops-brother-bob-stoops-oklahoma-retires|archive-date=June 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> was hired as Kentucky's head football coach in late 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/8683310/mark-stoops-florida-state-seminoles-defensive-coordinator-hired-head-coach-kentucky-wildcats|title=Mark Stoops, Florida State Seminoles defensive coordinator, hired as head coach of Kentucky Wildcats|work=ESPN.com|access-date=January 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107002005/http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/8683310/mark-stoops-florida-state-seminoles-defensive-coordinator-hired-head-coach-kentucky-wildcats|archive-date=January 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> One of Stoops' first moves was hiring offensive coordinator [[Neal Brown]], who brought back the \"Air Raid\" offense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121012aaa.html|title=Neal Brown Named Offensive Coordinator, Quarterbacks Coach|work=ukathletics.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203002437/http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121012aaa.html|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> After nine months as the head coach of the Wildcats, Stoops and his staff signed the highest ranked recruiting class in program history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aseaofblue.com/2013/2/7/3961856/uk-football-mark-stoops-altering-perceptions-and-expectations|title=UK football: Mark Stoops \u2013 Altering perceptions and expectations|author=SethBurchett|work=A Sea of Blue|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201210539/http://www.aseaofblue.com/2013/2/7/3961856/uk-football-mark-stoops-altering-perceptions-and-expectations|archive-date=February 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStoops's first season at Kentucky was a struggle, as the Wildcats duplicated the 2\u201310 record from 2012.<ref name=\"fbschedules.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fbschedules.com/ncaa-13/sec/2013-kentucky-wildcats-football-schedule.php|title=2013 Kentucky Wildcats Football Schedule|work=FBSchedules.com|access-date=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204031152/http://www.fbschedules.com/ncaa-13/sec/2013-kentucky-wildcats-football-schedule.php|archive-date=February 4, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Kentucky's wins in 2013 were over a winless [[Miami RedHawks football|Miami (OH)]] and [[Football Championship Subdivision|FCS]] opponent [[Alabama State Hornets football|Alabama State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=333060096|title=Alabama State vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - November 2, 2013 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805101933/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=333060096|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"fbschedules.com1\"/> In Stoops's second season, the Wildcats broke a 17-game SEC losing streak when they beat [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]] the fourth game into the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/kentucky-tops-vanderbilt-17-7-ends-sec-drought-192155739--ncaaf.html|title=Kentucky tops Vanderbilt 17\u20137, ends SEC drought|date=September 27, 2014|work=Yahoo Sports|access-date=November 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117173123/https://sports.yahoo.com/news/kentucky-tops-vanderbilt-17-7-ends-sec-drought-192155739--ncaaf.html|archive-date=November 17, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The Wildcats finished the 2014 season with a 5\u20137 record.<ref>{{cite web |author=A |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2014/12/01/stoops-wildcats-progressed-despite-5-7-finish/19752277/ |title=Stoops: Wildcats progressed despite 5\u20137 finish |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=December 1, 2014 |accessdate=May 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160118090633/http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2014/12/01/stoops-wildcats-progressed-despite-5-7-finish/19752277/ |archive-date=January 18, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> After the season, offensive coordinator [[Neal Brown]] left to take the head coaching job at [[Troy Trojans football|Troy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2014/11/29/7296683/neal-brown-troy-kentucky-football-coach|title=Troy hires Kentucky's Neal Brown as head coach|author=Jason Marcum|publisher=Vox Media|work=SBNation.com|access-date=December 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805150207/https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2014/11/29/7296683/neal-brown-troy-kentucky-football-coach|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2015, Stoops's third season, the Wildcats duplicated their 5\u20137 record from 2014. They lost to [[Florida Gators football|Florida]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603853|title=Florida vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - September 19, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805101210/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603853|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603898|title=Auburn vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - October 15, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805101848/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603898|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603889|title=Kentucky vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - October 24, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805101851/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603889|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603875|title=Tennessee vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - October 31, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805140405/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603875|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603907|title=Kentucky vs. Georgia - Game Recap - November 7, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805140906/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603907|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603937|title=Kentucky vs. Vanderbilt - Game Recap - November 14, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805101427/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603937|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603916|title=Louisville vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - November 28, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805140759/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603916|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and they defeated [[Louisiana\u2013Lafayette Ragin' Cajuns football|Louisiana-Lafayette]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603832|title=Louisiana vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - September 5, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805101253/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603832|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603867|title=Kentucky vs. South Carolina - Game Recap - September 12, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720185235/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603867|archive-date=July 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603846|title=Missouri vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - September 26, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805140452/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603846|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Eastern Kentucky Colonels football|Eastern Kentucky]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603880|title=Eastern Kentucky vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - October 3, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805101436/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603880|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Charlotte 49ers football|Charlotte]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603926|title=Charlotte vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - November 21, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805101434/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400603926|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn December 18, 2015, offensive coordinator [[Shannon Dawson]], who was hired to replace Neal Brown, announced he would not return to the program for the 2016 season as the offensive coordinator, a result of the team's struggles over the previous few years.<ref name=DawsonCJ>{{cite news |title=Shannon Dawson out as Kentucky OC|first=Jon|last=Hale|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/kentucky/2015/12/17/report-shannon-dawson-out-uk-oc/77480196/|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|location=Louisville|date=December 18, 2015|accessdate=December 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=DawsonLHL>{{cite news|title=Kentucky's Shannon Dawson won't return next season|first=Jennifer|last=Smith|url=http://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-football/article50245750.html|newspaper=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|date=December 18, 2015|accessdate=December 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219155931/http://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-football/article50245750.html|archive-date=December 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>  In his place Kentucky hired [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]] offensive coordinator [[Eddie Gran]] as the assistant head coach of offense at Kentucky. Cincinnati quarterbacks coach [[Darin Hinshaw]] has also joined the UK staff as quarterbacks coach and co-offensive coordinator.<ref name=GranCJ>{{cite news |title=Gran, Hinshaw join Kentucky football staff|first=Jon|last=Hale|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/kentucky/2015/12/29/source-gran-hinshaw-join-uk-staff/78011934/|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|location=Louisville|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=GranLHL>{{cite news|title=UK football hires Cincinnati's Eddie Gran to be assistant head coach of the offense|first=Jennifer|last=Smith|url=http://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-football/article52048175.html|newspaper=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|date=December 29, 2015|accessdate=December 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101120353/http://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-football/article52048175.html|archive-date=January 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Kentucky began the 2016 season with a loss to [[Southern Miss Golden Eagles football|Southern Miss]] by a score of 44\u201335, after blowing a 25-point lead.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400868973 |title=Southern Mississippi vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - September 3, 2016 |publisher=ESPN |date=2016-09-04 |accessdate=2017-04-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312051503/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400868973 |archive-date=March 12, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Ironically, Shannon Dawson, who was fired by Kentucky as offensive coordinator just months earlier, had been hired to serve as Southern Miss' offensive coordinator.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2016/02/11/shannon-dawson-southern-miss-offensive-coordinator/80223536/ |title=Shannon Dawson to be Southern Miss offensive coordinator |website=Usatoday.com |date=2016-02-11 |accessdate=2017-04-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520163754/https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2016/02/11/shannon-dawson-southern-miss-offensive-coordinator/80223536/ |archive-date=May 20, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Kentucky would finish 7\u20136 (4\u20134 SEC) on the season, which included snapping a five-game losing streak to archrival [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]] by a score of 41\u201338,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400869071 |title=Kentucky vs. Louisville - Game Recap - November 26, 2016 |publisher=ESPN |date=2016-11-26 |accessdate=2017-04-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170513023624/http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400869071 |archive-date=May 13, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> with a berth in the [[TaxSlayer Bowl]], their first bowl berth since 2010, a game they lost to [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech]] by a score of 33\u201318.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/ncfnation/post/_/id/135649/georgia-tech-survives-kentucky-comeback-bid-in-chippy-taxslayer-bowl |title=Georgia Tech survives Kentucky comeback bid in chippy TaxSlayer Bowl - College Football Nation Blog |publisher=ESPN |date=2016-12-31 |accessdate=2017-04-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102230114/http://www.espn.com/blog/ncfnation/post/_/id/135649/georgia-tech-survives-kentucky-comeback-bid-in-chippy-taxslayer-bowl |archive-date=January 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the 2017 season, the Wildcats opened the season with a victory over Southern Mississippi in Hattiesburg 24\u201317. The next week, the Wildcats defeated the Eastern Kentucky Colonels in their home opener at the newly renamed Kroger Field in Lexington. Following a road victory over the South Carolina Gamecocks, they failed to defeat the Florida Gators, whom they had not defeated since 1986. This extended the longest losing streak in SEC history to 31 years. Responding to the criticized loss to Florida, the Wildcats defeated Eastern Michigan and Missouri at Kroger Field, improving their record to 5\u20131.\n\nFollowing their bye week, the Kentucky Wildcats fell to #19-ranked Mississippi State team on the road, 45\u20137. However, the Wildcats improved to 6\u20132 by defeating the Tennessee Volunteers by a score of 29\u201326 at Kroger Field. The victory over Tennessee was Kentucky's second victory since 1984 over the Volunteers, and secured bowl eligibility. This was followed by a 37-34 home loss to Ole Miss and a dominating road win over unranked Vanderbilt. The Wildcats then lost to Georgia 42\u201313 in [[Sanford Stadium|Athens, Georgia]]. In their last regular season game against rival Louisville, Kentucky was beaten at home 44\u201317. Kentucky then proceeded to play [[2017 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]] in [[Nissan Stadium|Nashville, Tennessee]] in the [[2017 Music City Bowl|Music City Bowl]] on December 29, and lost 24\u201323.\n\nIn 2018, after beating [[2018 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|Central Michigan]], Kentucky went to Gainesville to face the [[2018 Florida Gators football team|Florida Gators]], who had won 31 straight against Kentucky, and ended their losing streak with a 27\u201316 win at [[Ben Hill Griffin Stadium|The Swamp]], the Wildcats' first win in Gainesville since 1979. They added wins in the next two weeks over [[2018 Murray State Racers football team|Murray State]] and #14 [[2018 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|Mississippi State]], the second of which put Kentucky into the Top 25, the Wildcats' first ranking since 2007. They then split the next two games, defeating [[2018 South Carolina Gamecocks football team|South Carolina]] for the fifth straight season before losing for the first time, an overtime loss to [[2018 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]] on the road. After the bye week, Kentucky defeated [[2018 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|Vanderbilt]] at home then beat [[2018 Missouri Tigers football team|Missouri]] on the road thanks to a last second TD pass. Those wins put the Wildcats at 7\u20131 and #9 in the College Football Playoff Rankings leading in to a home game against the [[2018 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia Bulldogs]]. In a matchup that determined the SEC East Division champion, the Wildcats were defeated at home 34\u201317. Kentucky then went on the road at [[2018 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]], falling to the Volunteers by a score of 24\u20137, ending their final SEC record at 5\u20133, the team's first winning season in conference play since 1977. In Kentucky's final home game of the season, senior day, the Wildcats defeated [[2018 Middle Tennessee Blue Raiders football team|Middle Tennessee]] by a score of 34\u201323. Kentucky closed the regular season with a 56\u201310 rout of [[2018 Louisville Cardinals football team|Louisville]] to win back the Governor's Cup. Kentucky was selected to play in the [[2019 Citrus Bowl|Citrus Bowl]] in [[Camping World Stadium|Orlando, Florida]] against #12 ranked [[2018 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]], and won 27-24. This capped only the third 10-win season in school history, and the first since 1977. The Wildcats finished ranked #12 in the AP poll, the first such end-season rank since the 1984 season.\n\n==Conference affiliations==\n* Independent (1881\u20131895)\n* [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] (1896\u20131904){{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n* Independent (1905\u20131911){{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n* Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association (1912\u20131921){{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Southern Conference]] (1922\u20131932)\n* [[Southeastern Conference]] (1933\u2013present)\n\n==Championships==\n\n===National championships===\nThe NCAA has never officially recognized a national champion from among the bowl coalition institutions, but in 2004 the NCAA commissioned [[Jeff Sagarin]] to use his computer model to retroactively determine the highest ranked teams for the years prior to the BCS. His champion for the 1950 season is Kentucky.<ref name=\"Walsh2007\">{{cite book|author=Christopher J. Walsh|title=Who's #1?: 100-Plus Years of Controversial National Champions in College Football|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=580XAQAAMAAJ|year=2007|publisher=Taylor Trade Pub.|isbn=978-1-58979-337-8|page=104}}</ref> The polls for the 1950 national champion, taken before the bowl games were played, list either Oklahoma (AP, Berryman, Helms, Litkenhous, UPI, Williamson), Princeton (Boand, Poling), or Tennessee (Billingsley, DeVold, Dunkel, Missouri, Don Faurot Football Research, National Championship Foundation, Sagarin (ELO-Chess)). Tennessee was the winner of the Cotton Bowl and the only team to beat Kentucky during the 1950 season. Oklahoma was named National Champion by AP and UPI Coaches' Poll, both which awarded their titles before the bowl games. Kentucky would go on to beat Oklahoma in the Sugar Bowl.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.org/champadmin/ia_football_past_champs.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080325105535/http://www.ncaa.org/champadmin/ia_football_past_champs.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-03-25 |title=Past Division I-A Football National Champions |date=2008-03-25 |accessdate=2017-04-03}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Kentucky Wildcats|Season|Coach|Selectors|Record|Bowl|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n| [[1950 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1950]] || [[Bear Bryant]] || [[Sagarin Ratings]] || 11\u20131  || [[1951 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] || [[1950 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]] || '''W''' 13\u20137\n|-\n|}\n\n===Conference championships===\nKentucky has won two conference championships, both in the [[Southeastern Conference]]. Kentucky also finished the [[1977 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1977 season]] with a 10\u20131 (6\u20130 SEC) record, but were not eligible for a share of the SEC championship or for postseason play due to NCAA probation.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Kentucky Wildcats|Season|Conference|Coach|Overall Record|Conference Record}}\n|- \n| [[1950 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1950]] || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] || [[Paul \"Bear\" Bryant]] || 11\u20131 || 5\u20131\n|- \n| [[1976 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1976]]\u2020 || [[Fran Curci]]|| 9\u20133<sup>\u2021</sup> || 5\u20131<sup>\u2021</sup> \n|}\n\u2020 Co-champions\n\n\u2021 Mississippi State forfeited their 1976 win over Kentucky, giving Kentucky an official 5\u20131 conference record and a share of the SEC title with [[1976 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]].\n\n==Bowl games==\n{{main|List of Kentucky Wildcats bowl games}}\nUK has played in 19 bowl games, compiling a record of 10\u20139. Note that in the table below, the year references the season, and not the actual date the game was played.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Kentucky Wildcats|Season|Coach|Bowl|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n| [[1947 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1947]] || rowspan=\"4\" |[[Bear Bryant]] || [[Great Lakes Bowl]] || [[Villanova Wildcats football|Villanova]] || '''W''' 24\u201314\n|-\n| [[1949 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1949]] ||    [[1950 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]] || [[1949 Santa Clara Broncos football team|Santa Clara]] || L 13\u201321\n|-\n| [[1950 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1950]] || [[1951 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] || [[1950 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]] || '''W''' 13\u20137\n|-\n| [[1951 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1951]] ||   [[1952 Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl Classic]] || [[TCU Horned Frogs football|TCU]] || '''W''' 20\u20137\n|-\n| [[1976 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1976]] || [[Fran Curci]] || [[1976 Peach Bowl|Peach Bowl]] || [[North Carolina Tar Heels football|North Carolina]] || '''W''' 21\u20130\n|-\n| [[1983 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1983]] || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Jerry Claiborne]] || [[1983 Hall of Fame Classic|Hall of Fame Classic]] || [[1983 West Virginia Mountaineers football team|West Virginia]] || L 16\u201320\n|-\n| [[1984 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1984]] || [[1984 Hall of Fame Classic|Hall of Fame Classic]] || [[1984 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]] || '''W''' 20\u201319\n|-\n| [[1993 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1993]] || [[Bill Curry]] || [[1993 Peach Bowl (December)|Peach Bowl]] || [[1993 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]] || L 13\u201314\n|-\n| [[1998 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1998]] || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Hal Mumme]] || [[1999 Outback Bowl|Outback Bowl]] || |[[1998 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]] ||L 14\u201326\n|-\n| [[1999 Kentucky Wildcats football team|1999]] || [[1999 Music City Bowl|Music City Bowl]] || [[1999 Syracuse Orangemen football team|Syracuse]] || L 13\u201320\n|-\n| [[2006 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2006]] || rowspan=\"4\" |[[Rich Brooks]] || [[2006 Music City Bowl|Music City Bowl]] ||[[2006 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]] || '''W''' 28\u201320\n|-\n| [[2007 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2007]] || [[2007 Music City Bowl|Music City Bowl]] || [[2007 Florida State Seminoles football team|Florida State]] ||'''W''' 35\u201328\n|-\n| [[2008 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2008]] || [[2009 Liberty Bowl|Liberty Bowl]] || [[2008 East Carolina Pirates football team|East Carolina]] || '''W''' 25\u201319\n|-\n| [[2009 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2009]] || [[2009 Music City Bowl|Music City Bowl]] || [[2009 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]] || L 13\u201321 \n|-\n| [[2010 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2010]] || [[Joker Phillips]] || [[2011 BBVA Compass Bowl|BBVA Compass Bowl]] || [[2010 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pittsburgh]] ||L 10\u201327\n|-\n| [[2016 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2016]] || rowspan=\"4\" | [[Mark Stoops]] || [[2016 TaxSlayer Bowl (December)|TaxSlayer Bowl]] || [[2016 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]] || L 18\u201333\n|-\n| [[2017 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2017]] || [[2017 Music City Bowl|Music City Bowl]] || [[2017 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]] || L 23\u201324\n|-\n| [[2018 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2018]] || [[2019 Citrus Bowl|Citrus Bowl]] || [[2018 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]] || '''W''' 27\u201324\n|-\n| [[2019 Kentucky Wildcats football team|2019]] || [[2019 Belk Bowl|Belk Bowl]] || [[2019 Virginia Tech Hokies football team|Virginia Tech]] || '''W''' 37\u201330\n|- \n|}\n\n==Rivalries==\n===Louisville===\n{{Main|Governor's Cup (Kentucky)}}\nFirst played in 1912, Louisville-Kentucky football series was revived in 1994 after the success of the basketball series that restarted in 1983. They played the first four games of the renewed series at Commonwealth Stadium (now Kroger Field) until [[Papa John's Cardinal Stadium]] (PJCS) was completed in 1997, at which time they began rotating the series between Louisville, Kentucky and Lexington, Kentucky. Kentucky leads the series 17-15, but trails the modern series 15-11. Kentucky played Louisville in the Cardinals' first 4 seasons and twice in the 1920s, holding the Cardinals scoreless in all contests. Kentucky then left the SIAA in 1922 to become a charter member of the Southeastern Conference and limited its play of in-state schools. It would be 70&nbsp;years before these two in-state rivals faced each other again.\n\nIn 2013, it was announced that the game would be moved to the final game of the season following Louisville's 2014 move to the ACC. This scheduling change fits with other end-of-year SEC vs. ACC rivalry games, such as [[Clean, Old-Fashioned Hate|Georgia vs. Georgia Tech]], [[Florida\u2013Florida State football rivalry|Florida vs. Florida State]] and [[Clemson\u2013South Carolina rivalry|South Carolina vs. Clemson]].\n\nIn 2018, Kentucky beat Louisville 56-10, winning by the largest margin since the rivalry restarted in 1994. The largest ever win in the rivalry was also by Kentucky which they won 73-0 in 1922, before the series went dormant.\n\nIn 2019, Kentucky beat Louisville 45-13. Kentucky quarterback Lynn Bowden broke the SEC record for yards rushing by a QB in a game with 284 total individual rushing yards. Also, the Wildcats broke their single game rushing record with 517 rushing yards against the Cardinals.\n\nKentucky leads the series 17\u201315 as of the conclusion of the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.winsipedia.com/kentucky/vs/louisville |title=Archived copy |access-date=October 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028033705/http://www.winsipedia.com/kentucky/vs/louisville |archive-date=October 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Tennessee===\n{{Main|Kentucky\u2013Tennessee football rivalry}}\nLike many college football rivalries, the Tennessee-Kentucky game had its own trophy for many years: a wooden beer barrel painted half blue and half orange. The trophy was awarded to the winner of the game every year from 1925 to 1997. The Barrel was introduced in 1925 by a group of former Kentucky students who wanted to create a material sign of supremacy for the rivalry. It was rolled onto the field that year with the words \"Ice Water\" painted on it to avoid any outcries over a beer keg symbolizing a college rivalry. The barrel exchange was retired in 1998 after two Kentucky football players died in an alcohol-related crash.\n\nTennessee leads the series 81\u201325\u20139 as of the conclusion of the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.winsipedia.com/kentucky/vs/tennessee |title=Archived copy |access-date=October 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030035532/http://www.winsipedia.com/kentucky/vs/tennessee |archive-date=October 30, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Indiana===\n{{Main|The Bourbon Barrel}}\nMore known for its basketball rivalry, the Indiana-Kentucky series was played annually from 1987 until 2005 in what was known as the \"Battle for the Bourbon Barrel\" game. The series rotated between Bloomington, Indiana and Lexington, Kentucky and the two teams played for a trophy called the \"Bourbon Barrel\" from 1987 until both schools mutually agreed to retire the trophy in 1999 following the alcohol-related death of two Kentucky football players.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idsnews.com/news/story.aspx?id=12909&search=golf&section=search |title=Oh, Four Oh Four |work=idsnews.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112011208/http://www.idsnews.com/news/story.aspx?id=12909&search=golf&section=search |archivedate=January 12, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Indiana leads the series 18\u201317\u20131 as of the conclusion of the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/kentucky/vs/indiana|title=Winsipedia - Kentucky Wildcats vs. Indiana Hoosiers football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n===Mississippi State===\n{{Main|Mississippi State-Kentucky football rivalry}}\nKentucky plays Mississippi State annually as their permanent West Division opponent. Through the 2019 meeting in [[Starkville, Mississippi|Starkville]], Mississippi State leads the series 24-23. There is currently no trophy awarded, but the two teams have met annually since 1990.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/games/mississippi-state/vs/kentucky - Mississippi State Bulldogs vs. Kentucky Wildcats football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n===Vanderbilt===\n{{Main|Kentucky\u2013Vanderbilt football rivalry}}\nHaving started in 1896, the Kentucky-Vanderbilt football series has been played annually since 1953.<ref name=\"mcubed.net\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mcubed.net/ncaaf/series/ky/van.shtml|title=mcubed.net : NCAAF Football : Series records : Kentucky vs. Vanderbilt|work=mcubed.net|access-date=January 11, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112013520/http://www.mcubed.net/ncaaf/series/ky/van.shtml|archive-date=January 12, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The two are divisional opponents in the SEC East. The series rotates between Nashville, Tennessee and Lexington, Kentucky. Kentucky leads the series 46\u201342\u20134 through the conclusion of the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/kentucky/vs/vanderbilt|title=Winsipedia - Kentucky Wildcats vs. Vanderbilt Commodores football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n==Individual Awards and Honors==\n===All-Americans===\nConsensus All-Americans in '''bold'''.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#ddf;| Player\n!  style=\"background:#ddf;| Position\n!  style=\"background:#ddf;| Year\n!  style=\"background:#ddf;| Unanimous\n!  style=\"background:#ddf;| Consensus\n!  style=\"background:#ddf;| Selectors\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| {{sortname|Clyde|Johnson|nolink=y}} || [[Tackle (American football)|T]] || [[1942 College Football All-America Team|1942]] || No || No || AP\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| {{sortname|Bob|Gain}} || [[Tackle (American football)|T]] || [[1949 College Football All-America Team|1949]] || No || No || All-Players, NY Sun, NEA\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| '''{{sortname|Bob|Gain}}''' || [[Tackle (American football)|T]] || [[1950 College Football All-America Team|1950]] || Yes || Yes || AP, UPI, INS, Camp, NEA, CP, FWAA-Look, AAB, FD, NYNews\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| '''{{sortname|Babe|Parilli}}''' || [[Quarterback|QB]] || [[1950 College Football All-America Team|1950]] || Yes || Yes || AP, INS, Camp, Colliers, NY News, Sporting News, AA\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| '''{{sortname|Bob|Gain}}''' || [[Quarterback|QB]] || [[1951 College Football All-America Team|1951]] || Yes || Yes || UP, INS, Camp, NEA, CP, AAB, NY News, All-Player\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| {{sortname|Doug|Moseley|nolink=y}} || [[Center (American football)|C]] || [[1951 College Football All-America Team|1951]] || No || No || AP, FWAA-Look\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| {{sortname|Steve|Meilinger}} || [[Defensive end|DE]] || [[1952 College Football All-America Team|1952]] || No || No || AP, NEA, All-Player\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| {{sortname|Stev